<FIRST>r a AM-Robertson-PTL     10-27 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Robertson-PTL,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBN Submits Bid For PTL Network</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Christian Broadcasting Network
founded by Marion G. ``Pat'' Robertson has submitted a bid to buy
the PTL Network's cable operation, CBN spokeswoman Frankie
Abourjilie said Thursday night.
   ``All I can tell you is we have submitted a bid,'' Ms.
Abourjilie said. ``There are numerous other bids.''
   She said she could not comment on the amount of the bid because
the bidding is confidential. ``If you divulge information related
to the bid, they eliminate you,'' she said.
   Ms. Abourjilie said she did not know when the bid was submitted,
only that it was sent in time for Friday's deadline.
   She said the PTL cable network reaches 7 million homes, compared
to 47 million reached by CBN. The bid is only for the cable
network, which includes satellites and cameras, Ms. Abourjilie
said. The bid has ``nothing to do with Heritage USA,'' she said.
   PTL filed for bankruptcy in June 1987, three months after
founder Jim Bakker resigned as head of the the ministry amid a sex
and money scandal.
   Stephen Mernick, a Toronto businessman who had agreed to buy the
ministry's assets, let his purchase contract expire Sept. 30
because he was unable to obtain title insurance for the Heritage
USA Christian campground near Fort Mill, S.C.
   Jim Bakker on Tuesday began serving a 45-year prison sentence
for defrauding members of the defunct PTL Club and television
ministry of $3.7 million.
</TEXT>
