<FIRST>r a PM-HugoWindfall     10-27 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo Windfall,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Well-Timed Windfall Due Former Ohioan Battered by Hurricane Hugo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iris Knorr's late husband put something
away for a rainy day and forgot about it.
   The rainy day came with Hurricane Hugo, which badly damaged the
hotel Mrs. Knorr runs in the Caribbean. An unexpected windfall
arrived shortly thereafter _$35,475.69 in stock that her husband
had left behind.
   Mrs. Knorr found out about the unknown assets thanks to an Ohio
state agency. Now, spending the money will be easy, she said
Thursday from the Caribbean island of Nevis, where expensive
repairs to her hotel are underway.
   Warren G. Knorr Sr. had purchased 897 shares of United Cable
Television Co. stock while the couple lived in Mansfield, Ohio.
   In 1980, the Knorrs moved to Nevis, in the Leeward Islands of
the Caribbean. They bought a 14-room inn, the Old Manor Hotel, on
an old sugar plantation. Shortly after they bought the hotel, Knorr
died.
   Mrs. Knorr didn't know about the stock sitting in a brokerage
account. In 1987, the account was declared inactive and the stock
was turned over to the Ohio Department of Commerce's Division of
Unclaimed Funds.
   The division takes responsibility for bank accounts, investments
and other assets left behind by people who move away or die without
claiming the money. The division sold the stock and placed the
money in an account in Knorr's name, where it continued to earn
interest.
   In some states, such accounts are maintained for a few years and
then revert to the state's general fund if no heir is found. In
Ohio, such an account could theoretically keep accumulating
interest forever. The division has 2.2 million accounts worth more
than $77 million. Its oldest account was started in 1865 and was
held by a bank until the division was established in 1968.
   Mrs. Knorr knew nothing of the stock when Hugo slammed into the
Caribbean on Sept. 16-17, with winds blowing at 140 mph. It killed
an estimated 56 people in the Caribbean and 29 more on the U.S.
mainland.
   Mrs. Knorr said the storm was unlike anything she had imagined.
   ``I thought it would never stop,'' she said. ``I've never been
in a tornado, but they're over in a few minutes. But this hurricane
....''
   The hotel suffered extensive exterior damage, also losing a part
of the roof, a poolside cabana and exterior light fixtures. Some of
the damage was covered by insurance, but not all, she said.
   The check from her late husband's stocks arrived a week ago and
will help with repairs to the roof and electrical system.
   Thomas Gerace, director of the Division of Unclaimed funds, said
Mrs. Knorr initially learned of her windfall from her son, who saw
it listed in advertisements prepared by the division and published
in Ohio newspapers.
   ``Being able to return the money to Mrs. Knorr under such
unusual circumstances makes this one of the most interesting cases
we have handled,'' Gerace said.
   Janet Peoples, a division spokeswoman, said Mrs. Knorr never
knew of her husband's dabbling in the market.
   ``She was elated about getting it in the first place ... and
ecstatic about getting it to rebuild,'' Ms. Peoples said.
   The division has paid 20,000 claims this year worth more than $7
million.
   ``I never even knew there was a Division of Unclaimed Funds,''
Mrs. Knorr said. ``I'm amazed that they were so diligent in finding
me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
