<FIRST>r a AM-PlantExplosion     10-27 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plant Explosion,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two More Bodies Found in Texas Plant Explosion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two more victims of a Phillips Petroleum
Co. plastic plant explosion were discovered Thursday night, and the
search continued for 15 more workers missing since the blast.
   The two bodies were found in the rubble outside a reactor
control room, said Phillips spokesman Scott Carlberg. A total of
seven bodies have been found so far.
   Carlberg also said that one of the bodies has been identified as
Jeffrey L. Harrison, 36, of Houston. None of the others have been
identified yet.
   The search process was slowed earlier in the day when officials
discovered a hydrocarbon leak near the blast site.
   Officials temporarily halted recovery work and ordered reporters
several hundred yards from the scene so other workers equipped with
monitors could determine if the level of vapor was dangerous.
   ``This is the kind of material we said we might encounter,''
said Carlberg. ``We're taking an extremely conservative safety
measure.''
   Phillips spokesman George Minter later said authorities believed
there was no danger.
   A series of explosions ripped through the plant Monday, injuring
more than 100 people.
   Crews manning bulldozers and cranes in the second day of
round-the-clock search work were moving Thursday toward a control
room area beneath a mangled reactor where many of the victims are
believed to have died.
   The victims found in the rubble were burned, and authorities
were using dental records to identify them.
   Three were found on Wednesday and one each on Monday and Tuesday.
   A 15-member federal team from the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration began its investigation of the accident Wednesday
but Phillips officials said the company efforts would concentrate
on recovery of victims before trying to find a cause for the blast.
   The plant daily produced 4.5 million pounds of plastic pellets _
about 20 percent of the national output _ used in manufacture of
milk jugs and grocery sacks.
</TEXT>
