<FIRST>u a PM-SFQuake-Armenians     10-27 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Armenians,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armenians Youngsters Say Quake Can't Compare With Their Disaster</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armenian youngsters who survived a
crippling earthquake in their country relived the horror after
coming here for treatment of physical and emotional problems.
   Fifteen-year-old Gayana Kaloustian whose hometown of Leninagan
was heavily damaged in the December 1988 quake in the Soviet
republic, said she was more frightened when the Bay area quake
struck Oct. 17.
   ``I didn't realize what was going on in Armenia, but I did
here,'' she said through an interpreter.
   But after the quake here ended, she said her fears vanished
because ``I was waiting for everything to fall down, but it
didn't.'' Her right leg was crushed in the Armenian quake, which
left thousands dead, injured and homeless.
   The children are staying at homes of Armenians who live in th
San Francisco Bay area and are undergoing treatment at the
Shriner's Hospital here. They were flown here by the Armenian
Relief Society, an international organization that collected $5
million in donations after the Armenian quake.
   Shriner's Hospital spokeswoman Mary Murphy said hospital
staffers and Armenian-Americans who have the children in their
homes feel ``they're responding very well emotionally. ... They're
doing extremely well.''
   The youngsters are ``feeling very safe since nothing fell down
on top of them,'' she said. ``That's what they associate with. We
just had a couple of lights fall on the floor at the hospital. Look
at the scene in Armenia. It was total devastation.''
   But for many of the children, the first reaction to the Bay area
quake was panic.
   One boy bolted outdoors and wouldn't enter a building for
several hours. Another couldn't eat and others cried, expecting the
worst.
   ``When the earthquake happened here, I was very frightened and I
cried,'' Meher Pahahlavian, 12, said. ``I was so scared I couldn't
eat.''
   His 10-year-old sister was killed in the 1988 quake, which
leveled their hometown of Spitak. He was brought here Oct. 1 for
treatment of a bone infection that developed from injuries suffered
when he was trapped in rubble for about two hours.
   ``Over there, it was horrible,'' he said. ``Over there,
everything tumbled down. But over here, nothing came down. ... I
wasn't half as scared as I was over there.''
   Still, the Oct. 17 quake and many aftershocks made a big
impression on the boy. ``When I'm alone, I really worry about
earthquakes,'' he said. ``But when you guys are with me, I seem to
forget.''
   Soviet psychiatrists who studied the emotional problems of
Armenian quake victims visited the children Thursday and said they
were doing well.
   Dr. Yuri Alexandrovsky, director of the National Center for
Neurotic and Borderline Psychiatric Disorders in Moscow, said
through an interpreter, ``The kids who experienced the Armenian
earthquake first were shocked much more than kids of similar age in
America.''
   ``They were afraid the houses here couldn't stand the earthquake
and they were waiting for the roofs to fall down,'' he said.
   ``But they returned to a normal state sooner than American kids
because the most fear for them was the collapse of buildings,''
said Alexandrovsky, who was one of four Soviets here to attend a
meeting of the International Society for the Traumatic Stress
Studies.
   ``It's nice to see the smiling faces of Armenian kids, because
it was awful to see the masks of horror on their faces during the
1988 earthquake when they were taken out of the ruins of their
houses.''
</TEXT>
