<FIRST>r i PM-CostaRica-Security     10-27 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Costa Rica-Security,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secret Service Imports 75-Foot Glass Wall to Protect Presidents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Costa Rica Meeting, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stiffest security measures in
Costa Rican history are in effect as hemispheric leaders gather to
celebrate the centennial of this nation's democracy.
   ``The leaders of drug trafficking have put a price on the heads
of some of the presidents,'' said Information Minister Jose Urbina,
trying to explain the security measures to a nation where the
president drives his own car to work and goes unescorted to movies
and restaurants.
   Streets in the center of town and along the 12-mile route to the
airport are closed to all but participants and accredited
journalists today and Saturday.
   This nation has no army, but 4,000 police officers have been
staging drills for weeks, charging across rooftops, closing the
airport, shutting off streets and creating temporary disruption for
almost everybody in this city of 1 million.
   Authorities erected a 75-foot-long glass wall in front of the
National Museum for Saturday's ceremonies dedicating Democracy
Plaza.
   The plaza is surrounded by numerous tall buildings that would
offer good vantage points to anyone who wanted to disrupt the
ceremonies.
   The buildings will be occupied by security forces Saturday, but
officials fearing for the safety of Presidents Bush and Virgilio
Barco of Colombia, as well as the 17 other hemispheric leaders
attending, decided that the best way to cut off any threat was to
build a glass wall 7 feet high across the podium.
   The glass was brought in on a U.S. Air Force transport plane and
erected Thursday under the supervision of U.S. Secret Service
agents.
   A Secret Service supervisor who refused to give his name said
the wall weighs 4.5 tons.
   ``It's pretty good,'' he said. ``It will do the job.''
</TEXT>
