<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-FreewayDesigner     10-27 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Freeway Designer,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freeway Designer Devastated by Roadway's Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sight of the earthquake-collapsed
section of Interstate 880 had a particularly devastating impact on
the man who designed the structure in the early 1950s. He watched
it crumble on television.
   ``I'm looking at a sandwich, and they're looking at a freeway,''
Clayton R. Giroux, 63, said in an emotional telephone interview
Wednesday with The Tribune of Oakland.
   Watching footage filmed from the Goodyear blimp when the
earthquake struck Oct. 17, Giroux knew before newscasters announced
it that the double-deck freeway had collapsed.
   ``I said, `My God, the blimp is panning over that and there's
got to be cars between there,''' he continued. ``I saw that it was
collapsed and I was horrified.''
   The days since the tragedy have been particularly trying for
Giroux, who has been in seclusion, ``pacing the floor and
fretting'' over what he considered one of his greatest engineering
achievements _ the state's first elevated freeway.
   ``I don't have guilt over it, just a stong sense of
disappointment and tragedy,'' he said. ``I cared very deeply about
doing a good engineering job and doing a job for an outfit that
serves people.''
   Giroux retired from the state Department of Transportation three
years ago. He began his career as a state bridge and highway
designer in 1948.
   Amid the flurry of criticism that the freeway was not built to
the engineering standards of its day, Giroux defended his creation.
   ``We were very proud of what we did,'' he said.
   Groux went on to explain that engineers included several
structural details in the design that quake experts now believe
contributed to the freeway's collapse.
   Steel hoops were placed in the structure's concrete columns to
stabilize the support system, but they ultimately make the pillars
vulnerable to buckling and collapse, experts say. Numerous,
criss-crossed ties are now used.
   ``The fraternity of engineers never knew that earthquakes
behaved in a way that would burst these columns,'' Giroux said.
</TEXT>
