<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     10-27 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLARKSVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who decorated his light aircraft
last year to look like a Christmas sleigh now has draped it with a
costume for Halloween _two witches and a spooky, flashing light.
   ``I really do it for the novelty ... for the kids, because they
think anything's possible, and it makes them see that anything you
want to do is possible,'' said Freddie Roberts.
   Roberts, a furniture builder in this city 45 miles northwest of
Nashville, flies a home-built gyrocopter. He's attached to it two
foam ``witches'' who have green faces and warts.
   After several forced landings caused by a problem with his fuel
tank, Roberts said he has the machine working well enough to spook
his neighbors.
   He said his wife ``hates for me to fly because I've broken a few
ribs.'' Last year, he was hurt when his ``sleigh'' hit a rock and
flipped several times on takeoff.
   Halloween night, with a blinking orange light on his craft,
he'll take to the air to entertain trick-or-treaters.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's only a wooden box with no sales
clerk or cash register at Harold Lineberger's pumpkin stand. You're
on your honor.
   ``Pumpkins $1, Honor System,'' a sign says. Lineberger isn't
worried.
   ``I'd say 99 percent of the people who buy pumpkins are
honest,'' Lineberger said. ``Most are families buying them as a
treat for the kids. People just don't steal with their families in
the car.''
   This week customers have bought scores of pumpkins and dropped a
dollar for each one into the locked box.
   ``I feel if you trust the public and let them know you trust
them, they'll reward you by being honest,'' he said.
   Lineberger has operated the stand off of Highway 275 in this
town about 20 miles west of Charlotte for eight years without a
clerk.
   ``I wouldn't try it with a table full of strawberries,'' he
says. ``But it's a good way to sell what I call low-profit produce
like pumpkins, broccoli and turnip greens. ... People don't like
them enough to steal them.''
</TEXT>
