<DOCNO> AP891027-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0248EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-GermanReunification     10-27 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-German Reunification,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush Is Out Front For Reunifying Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is leading the charge
for German reunification, an issue that conjures up memories of
World War II and makes some of the allies in Western Europe quite
nervous.
   The division of 80 million people between East and West was
never likely to be permanent. But the liberalization that Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has fostered in Eastern and Central
Europe _ and a flood of East German refugees _ puts the issue on
the front burner.
   President Bush dealt with it this week in an interview with R.W.
Apple Jr. of The New York Times and he did not hedge.
   ``I don't share the concern that some European countries have
about a reunified Germany because I think Germany's commitment to
and recognition of the importance of the alliance is unsinkable,''
he said.
   Bush was referring to trends to neutralism among the German
people, many of whom recoil in horror from what they heard or
remember about World War II and from the nuclear age it ushered in.
   ``I don't see Germany, in order to get reunification, going off
into what some are concerned about and that is a neutralist path
that puts them at odds, or potentially at odds, with their NATO
partners,'' Bush said.
   Referring carefully to the unspeakable, Helmut Sonnenfeldt, a
Berlin-born analyst and former State Department official, said
recently: ``If one means re-establishing the previous German Reich,
even in a somewhat smaller territory, I think that is probably not
in the cards for any time soon.''
   But, Sonnenfeldt said: ``I think there is a lot of concern in
Europe about the reconstitution of something that resembles the
previous united Germany that existed from 1871 on and especially in
the Hitlerian period.''
   Burton Yale Pines, senior vice president and director of
research at the Heritage Foundation, said Thursday that ``only we
can devise a framework in which a united Germany can emerge that
does not terrify its neighbors _ Eastern and Western.''
   West Germany has been a member of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization since 1955. Its admission to the U.S.-led alliance
against the Soviet Union confirmed its acceptance as a democracy
and also marked recognition of German rearmament.
   The turnabout since Hitler plunged the world in 1939 into the
worst war in recorded history, and set about to exterminate Jews
and other ``undesirables,'' was complete.
   Only Turkey within NATO has a larger armed force, 600,000
strong. Like the Germans, the Turks also confront the Soviet Union.
   Visiting Washington a few weeks ago, Manfred Woerner, the former
West German defense minister who is now NATO's secretary general,
predicted NATO will continue to exist, with changes.
   He even saw merit in the survival of the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact,
calling it a force for stability.
   And yet, East Germany may be catching the democratic fever. Some
60,000 of its citizens have fled to West Germany and those who
stayed behind want a better life. They need only to look to Hungary
to know it is possible within the Warsaw Pact.
   Egon Krentz, the new East German chief of state, was viewed
initially as an anti-reformer. Now some analysts are not so sure.
He appealed Tuesday for public support in overcoming an economic
and refugee crisis. ``Young and old, we must all work together,''
he said.
   If the lines between East and West begin to blur, so also might
the division of the two Germanys, and with it could go both NATO
and the Warsaw Pact.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, asked Monday after a
speech in San Francisco about the German question, replied: ``When
we talk about that we're talking about self-determination for the
peoples of East Germany ... achieved in peace and freedom so that
the people of East Germany ultimately will be integrated into a
community of democratic European nations.''
   Baker did not specify how this could be accomplished, but he
acknowledged that ``the word `reunification' conjures up visions of
a return to 1937 borders or perhaps a reunification that is not
achieved through peace and freedom.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Barry Schweid covers foreign affairs for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
