<FIRST>r w PM-DrugFunding     10-27 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Funding,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money for Drug War Moving Forward Again in Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost $3.2 billion to step up the war on
drugs is moving forward again in Congress after agreement between
House and Senate negotiators.
   The money represents the major congressional contribution to the
war that was launched by President Bush on Sept. 5 but appeared
stalled since the plan cleared the Senate on Sept. 27.
   A House-Senate conference committee on Thursday reached
agreement on the funds, which bring to $8.8 billion the total
commitment to the campaign against narcotics, $900 million more
than the administration initially sought.
   The House accepted overall funding levels for the war on drugs
contained in an $11.9 billion transportation bill the Senate
approved Sept. 27.
   Floor action on the bill in the House is expected Tuesday. It
was not immediately certain when the Senate plans to vote on the
measure.
   The Senate accepted a House proposal to change the way lawmakers
will cut other programs to pay for the drug war.
   As approved by the Senate, the bill called for a 0.43 percent
cut in programs throughout the government but only 0.3 percent of
it across the board. Congressional subcommittees were to make
adjustments in programs to get the rest of the money, thus avoiding
excessive cuts in defense.
   The plan agreed upon by the conferees would give the
congressional subcommittees more freedom to choose what would be
cut.
   The compromise also dropped 60 pages of drug-fighting program
authorizations that the Senate harnessed to the money bill.
   The package included measures ranging from requiring each state
to have a drug-fighting plan to programs that would pave the way
for assistance to coca-producing nations in the Andes.
   House members said the authorizations, dealing with substantive
programs, had no business on an appropriation bill.
   Speaker Thomas Foley, D-Wash., sent a letter to Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, promising that the House would
deal with the authorizations later.
   Rep. Lawrence Coughlin, R-Pa., questioned the leader of Senate
conferees, Appropriations Committee Chairman Robert C. Byrd,
D-W.Va., on whether the House would be allowed to vote on the
measures sought by the president in unaltered form.
   ``I accept the assurances of the leadership,'' Byrd said.
   Coughlin said afterward, though, that he remained worried that
the president's programs might come to the House floor packaged
with additional items unpalatable to Republicans and ``lord only
knows what.''
   ``Or the president's program would be so limited and watered
down,'' he added.
   Before the conferees acted, national drug control policy
director William J. Bennett had criticized Congress' slow pace in
acting on the president's proposal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891027-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0255EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FoodSafety     10-27 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Food Safety,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Criticize Bush's Pesticide Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's plan to improve pesticide
regulation is being criticized in Congress as doing nothing to make
food safer but praised for promoting needed bureaucratic
improvements.
   ``The president deserves credit for reforming the outdated and
extremely cumbersome procedures for removing dangerous pesticides
from use,'' Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., said Thursday. ``But
better procedures are meaningless if the safety standards are
weakened.''
   The president's proposal ``offers absolutely no assurances that
our food will be free of dangerous pesticides,'' he said.
   Waxman, chairman of the House Energy and Commerce subcommittee
on health and the environment, has introduced legislation of his
own to reform pesticide use and said he would consider Bush's
proposal during hearings within the next three weeks.
   Waxman's bill is among several in Congress that have various
plans for regulating the way chemicals are used in farming.
   Bush's proposal includes:
   _Redefining the criteria to be used for temporarily removing or
suspending from use a pesticide that poses a possible health
hazard, making it easier to get the chemical off the market even
though formal proceedings might still be under way.
   _Streamlining the procedures under which a dangerous pesticide
may be permanently removed from the market. Officials said the
process would reduce by at least half the four-to-eight years it
often takes for a chemical to be banned.
   _Providing tougher enforcement against misuse of pesticides,
including a proposal to increase penalties from $5,000 per day to
$25,000 per day.
   ``President Bush's proposal ... will enhance the government's
ability to remove potentially hazardous pesticides from the
marketplace,'' said Rep. Norman Lent, R-N.Y., ranking Republican on
the Energy and Commerce Committee.
   In the Senate, Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick Leahy
criticized Bush's plan.
   ``The administration is taking one step forward and two steps
back when it weakens important food safety protections in exchange
for some procedural improvements in pesticide regulations,'' said
Leahy, D-Vt.
   Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman, D-Conn., a member of the Senate
Environment and Public Works Committee, likened the Bush proposal
to an Impressionist painting.
   ``The closer you get to it, the fuzzier it looks,'' he said.
   Lawmakers complain about Bush's proposal to increase the risk
level allowed before a pesticide is removed from the market. Waxman
said that under the plan, cancer risks of chemicals used on crops
could be as high as 1 in 10,000.
   ``This is 100 times greater than the Food and Drug
Administration says is acceptable,'' Waxman said.
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., said it was ``unacceptable that
the administration is proposing to weaken current federal health
and safety standards, and then prohibit states from setting higher
standards themselves.''
   Uniform pesticide standards are needed for international trade
purposes, said Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter.
   ``State governments should not have a standard that is different
from those of the federal government,'' he said.
   Dean Kleckner, president of the American Farm Bureau Federation,
said Bush's plan was ``a workable approach'' that would ``make the
world's safest food supply even safer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
