<DOCNO> AP891027-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0721EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CongresstoPoland     10-27 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress to Poland,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Congress Wants to Help Its Polish Counterpart</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Congress wants to lend a helping hand
to its fledgling counterpart in Poland by providing the hardware
and software of western-style democracy.
   The Senate late Thursday approved a resolution that will send a
team of congressional experts to Poland to study the needs of the
newly formed parliament. They will come up with an aid package that
includes everything from telephones and typewriters to training in
how to write laws.
   ``While we're talking about the bigger issues of loan
stabilization, of economic reform, of food aid, it is quite
appropriate for Congress to give this as a first gift of
democracy,'' said Sen. Pete Domenici, a sponsor of the initiative.
   Poland's first open elections since before World War II, held in
April, gave the country its first non-communist-dominated
government in four decades. But the newly elected lawmakers, many
of them workers with no previous experience in government, soon
found they had inherited an empty shell of a legislature, Domenici
said.
   Used only to rubber-stamp decisions of previous communist
governments, the parliament has no mechanism for drafting laws, or
even keeping track of laws already on the books. There is no
organizational structure like the U.S. Congress' system of
committees. There are no workable rules of procedure for the Sejm,
the lower house, or the newly created Senate.
   Domenici and a group of former U.S. lawmakers went to Poland in
September to meet with a select group of the new legislators,
including members of the now-dominant Solidarity party and other
parties.
   The new elected officials are bright, able and motivated, he
said. One is a manager at a tractor factory, another a physician at
the Gdansk shipyards, another a college professor and another a
union leader. The group probably had more experience in organizing
protests than in governing; many had spent time in jail under the
old regime.
   ``We thought we were going to talk about economics, how you
create a capitalist system,'' Domenici, R-N.M., said in an
interview. ``They were interested in that, but they really wanted
to know how to run a parliament.
   ``It boiled down to basics: How do you gather information? How
do you get sufficient information-gathering equipment to keep track
of your laws? They have no library system, no simple computer
system, no copying machines. They don't have a system of producing
reports.
   ``So while we talked about a lot of philosophical things ...
they need some of the basic equipment that we take for granted,''
Domenici said. When the group _ which included former Sens. Walter
Mondale, Thomas Eagleton and Howard Baker, and former Rep. James
Jones _ suggested it could come up with some help, ``they were just
ecstatic,'' said Domenici.
   Congress, in the next few months, will send aides familiar with
computers, legislative research and parliamentary procedure to
Poland to inventory training and equipment needs. Congress then
will seek donations from the U.S. private sector to get the new
Senate and Sejm started.
   Domenici acknowledged he has gotten some ribbing for wanting to
share abroad the expertise of Congress, which is not exactly noted
at home for its own efficiency. But he said there will be no
courses on how to avoid meeting budget targets, or how to cut
pork-barrel deals.
   ``I know some might look at how we conduct our business and say,
`We sure don't want to pass that over to Poland.' But when you look
at this brand-new democracy that has such tremendous respect for
the United States of America ... it seems to me that this is a rare
opportunity to at least say we care.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
