<FIRST>u a PM-SFQuake-Hoarding     10-27 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Hoarding,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stockpiling of Relief Goods Triggers Voucher System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATSONVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hoarding of disaster relief food,
clothing and other supplies prompted officials at a relief center
to require the needy to obtain vouchers from an agency four miles
away.
   Until Wednesday's crackdown, the donated items were passed out
to anyone who asked at the Salvation Army's downtown relief center.
The system angered some volunteers.
   ``I can't believe it. This is absurd,'' said Antoinette Pilz, a
volunteer from the Church of the Highlands in South San Francisco.
``You've got to trust people. There is enough food in Watsonville
to feed the entire city for two months.''
   But officials said the system will continue, with the needy
required to go to the Federal Emergency Management Agency
headquarters in the northern section of town for the vouchers.
   ``We will continue to do vouchers now,'' said Lt. Clayton
Gardner of the Salvation Army's downtown relief center. ``We are
concerned we will go down to Salinas this weekend and find half our
stuff being sold at the flea market.''
   Gardner and others complained that some residents had loaded up
on much more donated clothing and other items than they could
possibly use. The display of greed prompted the security crackdown,
making it difficult for the people the agencies are trying to serve.
   City Councilman Dennis Osmer said there was undoubtedly some
stockpiling of relief goods.
   ``We do have a lot of hoarding, but if people are hoarding and
we give out four times what they need, we have four times what they
need. Let's give it to them,'' Osmer said.
   Some people were turned away at the downtown relief center
Thursday morning if they didn't have the proper papers.
   ``We realize a lot of these people won't go to the disaster
assistance center because they are illegal aliens, but we want
these people to see the wealth of services available to them and
getting them there is the only way to do it,'' said Gardner, who
conceded the system had caused hardship.
   A Spanish-speaking woman, carrying two young children, asked a
volunteer for a toy and was told she needed a voucher.
   ``It was a giveaway. It got to the point where the Red Cross and
the military started to control that and now people that really
need it are given the runaround and given a hard time,'' said Jose
Luis Fernandez, division director at California Employment Training
here.
   Volunteer Ed Vasquez said the city no longer wanted quake
refugees living in tents. The city estimates 1,200 people were left
homeless by the quake, while the Salvation Army claims there are
closer to 4,000 or 5,000 living oudoors.
   ``The idea is getting them to go to FEMA to find out what's
available,'' said Vasquez. ``We recognize many are going to be
intimidated by going to a federal agency. We are just trying to
make a human effort to get them back in some kind of shelter.''
   One of the unauthorized migrant camps that have sprung up since
the quake is at Callaghan Park, where 250 people are living in
tents and being cared for by Salude Para La Gente, a state and
federally funded Hispanic outreach group.
   At the park, mattresses are set up on wooden pallets to keep
rainwater from soaking people or belongings. The spicy scent of
chili peppers wafted from barbeques. A large green millitary tent
stored the community's supply of food.
   Democratic state Sens. Henry Melo of Watsonville and Art Torres
of Los Angeles toured the Callaghan camp Thursday and assured
residents there would be no check on citizenship.
   FEMA and other relief agenies ``are here to provide humanitarian
aid and are not interested in asking about citizenship status,''
Melo said.
</TEXT>
