<FIRST>r w PM-Markets-Brady     10-27 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets-Brady,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Secretary Contradicts SEC Chairman</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady is
disputing the new Securities and Exchange Commission chief's
contention that the SEC doesn't need the power to halt trading in
stock market emergencies.
   Testifying before a Senate panel in support of proposed market
reform legislation, Brady said Thursday taht the Bush
administration supports giving the SEC emergency powers to suspend
or halt trading for up to 24 hours.
   One day earlier, SEC Chairman Richard C. Breeden told a House
panel he neither wanted nor needed the emergency power, one of four
changes originally proposed by the SEC in the wake of the 1987
stock market crash.
   Brady declined to comment further on his testimony after the
hearing before the Senate Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs
Committee.
   Breeden, on the job just two weeks, said through a spokeswoman
late Thursday that he had no comment.
   On Wednesday, Breeden said safety mechanisms called
circuit-breakers _ automatic, temporary trading halts in times of
market volatility _ have eliminated much of the need for officials
to halt trading.
   Breeden told the telecommunications and finance subcommittee of
the House Energy and Commerce Committee that he believed the
possibility of arbitrary halts could cause uncertainty and
volatility in the markets. The power to make such a decision should
remain where it is now _ with the president, he contended.
   Brady, in a letter accompanying his testimony, said, however,
that he believed the change is needed.
   The initial governmental response to market emergencies should
come ``from a regulator with expertise and proximity to the
markets,'' Brady said.
   Brady noted that the proposed legislation still gives the
president power to terminate SEC emergency actions and would
require presidential approval for any trading halt longer than 24
hours.
   In other testimony, Brady backed away from a recommendation made
by a commission he headed that investigated the 1987 crash when the
Dow Jones industrial average, a key market indicator, dropped more
than 500 points in one day. Brady said his crash study may have
``overreacted'' in calling for a super-regulator to oversee all the
financial markets.
   In his first testimony to Congress since the 190-point plunge in
the Dow Jones industrial average Oct. 13, Brady said the turmoil
had not altered his belief in the soundness of the U.S. economy.
But it did point out the need for further changes in market
regulation, he said.
   Brady suggested giving the SEC authority to request reports on
large securities and options trades, as well as rules for assessing
the financial soundness of the parent holding companies of
broker-dealers.
   Legislation making such changes, with minor variations, is
before the House.
   A January 1988 report on the previous October's 508-point stock
market crash, the presidential Task Force on Market Mechanisms _
headed by Brady _ recommended that one agency should coordinate all
the financial markets. That recommendation was one of several never
acted upon by the Reagan administration.
   Given the different political constituencies of the various
market regulators _ the SEC, the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission and the Federal Reserve Board _ ``I don't believe that's
a practical possibility,'' said Brady.
</TEXT>
