<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0124EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SFQuake-Julio Bjt   10-27 1072</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Julio, Bjt,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tale Of Motherless Quake Survivors Pulls At Nation's Heart _ And
Purse</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `cot' is as card was written in 20th graf, `I'm sorry...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Earthquake survivor Julio Berumen has
been flooded with donations, toys and get-well cards, but the
6-year-old boy still cries out for the one thing no one can give
him _ his mother.
   She died within inches of him when the upper deck of the Nimitz
freeway slammed down on their car in last week's earthquake.
   Rescuers had to amputate Julio's right leg to free him from the
wreckage. And while doctors believe that Julio and his 8-year-old
sister, Cathy, will survive their injuries, friends of the
close-knit family are hoping the quake did not kill the children's
bright spirits.
   When Julio's first-grade teacher brought a toy to him at the
hospital this week, ``he started crying,'' said the teacher,
Manuela Knight.
   ``He was probably wondering, `Why is my teacher coming to see me
and not my mother?' '' Knight said Thursday.
   She said Julio was ``everybody's friend'' in her class _ spunky,
confident, and obviously the product of a warm and supportive
family.
   ``I saw him Tuesday and he's not the same little boy, but I hope
his spirit comes back,'' she said.
   When the quake struck, Julio and Cathy were riding home from the
orthodontist with their mother, Petra Berumen, and a family friend,
Yolanda Orozco. The Berumens' red Ford was crushed by a concrete
pillar when the double-decked Interstate 880 collapsed, trapping
dozens of cars.
   Mrs. Berumen and Orozco were killed. Cathy escaped with head
injuries. But Julio was trapped alive, his legs pinned in the
crumpled car.
   Rescuers used a chainsaw to cut the body of Orozco in half,
allowing a doctor to slide in and amputate Julio's right leg at the
knee to free him.
   Previous reports said the body of the boy's mother had been cut
by rescue workers working to free him, but Joseph Blackwell, a
deputy coroner investigator in the Alameda County coroner's office,
said Thursday that it was Orozco's body.
   Her body was recovered Oct. 19, Blackwell said, and Berumen's
body had to be cut Oct. 20 to free it from the wreckage.
   Julio has been in surgery three times since the quake, and his
sister underwent an eight-hour operation Wednesday for fractures in
her skull and facial bones, said Steve Tiger, spokesman at
Children's Hospital in Oakland.
   Cathy's condition was listed as serious Thursday, but only
because she was recovering from surgery. Otherwise, both children
are in good condition, Tiger said.
   ``They're sturdy little kids,'' said hospital spokeswoman Diane
Lazzari. They'll have plenty of support in their recovery. Their
father, Pastor, has kept a vigil by their bedsides, aided by aunts
and uncles.
   Friends and teachers at San Pablo's Downer Elementary School are
planning a fund-raising spaghetti dinner and raffle when the
year-round school resumes Nov. 7 after a 15-day vacation. An
Oakland elementary school class sent $100 that the children had
raised for a field trip to a pumpkin patch.
   And strangers from around the country have sent Julio and Cathy
cash, checks, cards, toys, and ``more stuffed animals than they
would ever be able to use in a lifetime,'' Tiger said.
   By Thursday, the Julio and Cathy Berumen Relief Fund set up at
Oakland's Summit Bank had collected nearly $48,000.
   The largest contribution was $3,000 from a couple in South
Pasadena, Calif. One of the smallest was from Nissa Kauppila, 7, of
Ferrysburg, Vt., who sent $2.10 and two little pins _ a bunny and a
frog _ for Cathy and Julio.
   ``I'm sorry you got cot in the earthquake,''' Nissa printed in
crooked block letters. ``I hope you feel well soon.''
   A grandmother in Tampa, Fla., who lost her own grandson at age 6
sent $100. A Los Angeles woman whose daughter lost her leg sent
$25. Residents of an apartment complex in St. Petersburg, Fla., got
together and sent $220.
   ``Although I don't know you, our hearts have certainly been
touched,'' Anna Berrier of Huntersville, N.C., wrote to Pastor
Berumen. ``I'm praying the children and you will get through.''
   The letters and donations pour in, hundreds each day. ``I'm
having a hard time keeping my composure, opening these and reading
them,'' said bank worker Cindy Kyte.
   Another fund was set up at Donner School to help the family meet
day-to-day expenses such as mortgage payments, said Principal
Catherine Syverson.
   The Berumens, a proud couple born in Mexico, bought their first
home _ a small one-story house a few blocks from the school _ just
2{ months ago. Friends say their lives revolved around their
children.
   Mrs. Berumen dropped the kids off at school in the mornings and
picked them up in the afternoons, and she was one of a handful of
mothers who was actively involved in school affairs, said Manuela
Knight.
   Even with the death of his wife, the first concern of Pastor
Berumen, a construction worker, is Julio and Cathy.
   ``At the moment he has to concentrate all his energy on his
children. He doesn't even have time to deal with his wife's death
yet,'' Tiger said. ``He does want to get out a thank you to
everyone who has helped. But his concentration is elsewhere right
now.''
   Teachers regard Cathy as one of the brightest children at her
school. Polite and a little shy, she is a protective big sister who
occasionally came into Knight's classroom to check on her brother.
   Julio was an enthusiastic kickball player and possessed
irrepressible energy at an age when many kids are shy, Knight said.
Confident and cheerful, he was proceeding well in his bilingual
studies in English and Spanish.
   ``A little while ago, I told his mother in a parent-teacher
conference, `You don't have to worry about Julio, he's going to be
fine,' '' Knight said.
   ``I think I still feel that way. With support, I expect Julio to
have a full and wonderful life. If we all work to help him and his
father, then there's no reason why he can't.''
   --- 
   Editors: Contributions to the Julio and Cathy Berumen Relief
Fund can be sent care of Summit Bank, 2969 Broadway, Oakland, Calif.
   Contributions to the family fund set up by Downer Elementary
School can be sent to Mechanics Bank, 3170 Hilltop Mall Road,
Richmond, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
