<FIRST>u a PM-SFQuake-Stress     10-27 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SFQuake-Stress,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expert Says More Than Baseball Needed to Ease Quake Stress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's more to getting past the killer
earthquake that hit this area Oct. 17 than going to the World
Series and telling victims to ``go back to normal,'' an expert on
stress says.
   Government agencies dealing with earthquake victims must be
especially careful and use ``common sense and wisdom,'' added Dr.
Yael Danieli, president of the International Society for Traumatic
Stress Studies.
   ``Take your time,'' she advised local, state and federal
agencies. ``These are people whose lives are in shambles right in
front of their eyes.''
   ``Just to have an understanding attitude in itself would already
make people feel different,'' said Dr. Danieli. ``Wisdom seems to
be the casualty of bureaucratic stressful response.''
   Dr. Danieli, a clinical psychologist who has done extensive
research on Holocaust victims, said there are big differences
between man-made and natural disasters.
   ``But what victims in general potentially have in common ... is
a conspiracy of silence,'' she said. ``That is, victims are allowed
to be victims for a little while. Then you're supposed to go back
to normal, whatever that means.''
   ``After extraordinary events `normal' changes its meaning,'' she
said. ``But then the instruction, spoken or unspoken, is, `Shut up
already, go back to normal, the past is the past, bygones are
bygones, get down to business, go on with the business of living,
go to the baseball game, continue with the World Series, you
survived, what do you have to complain about?'''
   The problem with that is the continuing impact of ``the grief
and the rage and the fear and the nightmares and the worry about
the next day,'' she said.
   ``That's tough to bear alone, and victims potentially very often
wind up feeling very isolated, very alienated and in fact made to
feel crazy because how come they're still afraid, how come they
still want to cry, how come they're still afraid to feel? And this
all victims share in common.''
   Dr. Danieli said talk, of the sort scheduled at her
organization's meeting here, is valuable because ``the more you
talk, the more you don't need to re-experience without words.''
   ``The more you talk means the more you have people around you.
You don't feel as lonely and you don't feel as scared,'' she said.
``We believe in talking, we believe in the value of talking and
sharing.''
   Some 500 visiting psychologists, psychiatrists and other experts
in stress are attending the society's annual meeting here, and the
agenda was quickly changed to allow for an open forum to discuss
the quake and its impact on people.
   A local newspaper poll has sugested that three out of five San
Francisco Bay area residents are having emotional difficulties
because of the earthquake, including sleeplessness, nervousness,
irritability, difficulty in concentration and depression.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
