<FIRST>r w PM-Justice-Porn     10-27 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Justice-Porn,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Seems to be Focusing on Child Porn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal obscenity prosecution statistics
suggest that the Justice Department is focusing more of its
anti-smut efforts on child pornography rather than on material that
involves adults.
   The figures show a sharp drop in the last two years in the
number of federal indictments for violations of federal obscenity
laws, while child-pornography charges soared during the same time
period.
   Indictments for federal obscenity violations dropped from 66 in
1987 to 37 last year, according to figures compiled by the
department's National Obscenity Enforcement Unit.
   The figures may not be complete because U.S. attorneys are not
required to report obscenity prosecutions, said spokesman Joseph
Krovisky.
   But FBI figures reflect a similar trend.
   The number of obscenity cases pending at the bureau dropped from
355 in 1987 to 302 in 1988 and to 194 in the first nine months of
the 1989 fiscal year, which ended Sept. 30.
   Federal child-pornography prosecutions, meanwhile, jumped from
281 in 1987 to 406 last year, according to the obscenity unit's
figures.
   In a speech to the Religious Alliance Against Pornography on
Thursday, Attorney General Dick Thornburgh pledged to attack all
forms of illegal pornography, including material depicting sexual
acts by adults.
   But the attorney general repeatedly emphasized he considered
child pornography ``the most offensive of all'' and cautioned that
officials must be sensitive to First Amendment protections.
   ``Pornography to me is degrading to human dignity in every form,
but it is most degrading to the human dignity of those who are
innocent and defenseless and who are preyed upon by criminal
actors,'' Thornburgh said.
   ``We must be attentive to the preservation of First Amendment
rights just as we are attentive to the enforcement of laws that
attack those practices that lie outside the area of First Amendment
protection.''
   When the obscenity unit was created in 1987 by Thornburgh's
predecessor, Edwin Meese III, civil libertarians complained that
its prosecutions would infringe on constitutional rights.
   Before the unit was organized, there were very few obscenity
prosecutions against distributors or makers of hard-core adult
pornography, said John Weston, a Los Angeles attorney who
represents distributors of X-rated material.
   Law enforcement officials say that prosecutions of obscenity
cases are sensitive because of the constitutional claims.
   Thornburgh noted difficulties in making obscenity charges stick.
A federal judge in Los Angeles this year dismissed eight obscenity
counts against an accused pornographer because he couldn't identify
a prevailing community standard in the city.
   But the defendant, Rubin Gottesman, was convicted of a
child-pornography violation because a minor appeared as an actress
in many of the videos he distributed, Thornburgh said.
   Gottesman was sentenced last week to a year in prison and fined
$100,000.
   Thornburgh told the conference that he had asked Congress for
more money to increase the size of the obscenity unit. Spokesman
David Runkel said later that Thornburgh had requested Congress add
one person to the 20-member unit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
