<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0317EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Voyager-Outage     10-27 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Voyager-Outage,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Restores Signal From Voyager 1 After Partial Loss of Contact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA restored full contact with Voyager
1 after the space probe stopped sending data to Earth this week _
the first such malfunction since it was launched in 1977 to explore
Jupiter and Saturn.
   ``We're relieved, of course. But now there's the question of why
did it happen and is it going to happen again?'' John Tullius,
senior mission controller for Voyagers 1 and 2 at the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration's Jet Propulsion Laboratory,
said Thursday.
   But flight engineering manager Lanny Miller said the partial
loss of contact ``wasn't too worrisome'' because engineers were
confident of their ability to correct the malfunction.
   The Voyagers were launched from Florida in 1977. They explored
Jupiter in 1979. Voyager 1 explored Saturn in 1980, followed in
1981 by Voyager 2, which went on to study Uranus in 1986 and
Neptune in August. The twin spacecraft learned so much that
scientists have been forced to revise astronomy textbooks.
   Both probes are continuing their mission, searching for the edge
of the solar system, where solar wind yields to interstellar wind,
and returning data about magnetic fields and electrically charged
particles in space. Barring any unforeseen failure, they are
expected to send information back to Earth until 2015 or 2020.
   Controllers never lost Voyager 1's ``carrier signal,'' a single
tone that allows them to track the probe's location, which is now
above the plane of the solar system some 3.7 billion miles from
Earth.
   But sometime between 6 a.m. and 4 p.m. PDT Monday, Voyager 1
stopped sending its ``telemetry signal,'' which transmits
scientific data collected by the probe and information about how
the spacecraft is functioning, Tullius said.
   At noon Tuesday, engineers sent commands to reset Voyager 1's
``telemetry modulation unit,'' ordering it to start working again.
   Even at the 186,000-mile-per-second speed of light, the commands
took 5{ hours to reach the spacecraft. It took the same amount of
time for Voyager to confirm the commands worked, so it was after 11
p.m. Tuesday when engineers knew full contact was restored, Tullius
said.
   Until then, ``there was concern we'd only have one spacecraft
left out of the two,'' Tullius said. ``Voyager 1 is very dear to us
too.''
   Although engineers at times have shut off Voyager telemetry
signals intentionally, this week's partial loss of contact was the
first time it has happened accidentally, he added.
   The cause is under investigation, but Tullius said a cosmic ray
may have hit the telemetry unit, or a circuit simply malfunctioned
because of age.
   A radio station sends out a single tone, but modulates it to
transmit music of different tones, Miller said. Voyager 1's
telemetry modulator adds or subtracts voltage to the probe's
single-tone carrier signal to produce different tones that carry
information, he explained.
   When the modulator malfunctioned, ``What we were receiving was
the equivalent of a single tone or static, when what we wanted to
hear was Beethoven's Fifth Symphony,'' Miller said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891027-0039 </DOCNO>
