<FIRST>r w PM-DeathPenalty     10-27 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Death Penalty,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Penalty for Terrorists in Overseas Killings OK'd By Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American courts could impose the death penalty
on terrorists convicted of murdering U.S. citizens under
legislation that has won overwhelming Senate approval.
   Capital punishment is needed for ``the kinds of offenses that
are an affront to humanity,'' Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said
Thursday as the Senate approved the measure 79-20.
   Under the bill, which goes to the House, courts would remain
free to impose prison sentences rather than capital punishment on
the small number of terrorists who are convicted in U.S. courts of
overseas murder.
   A court would not be able to impose the death penalty unless the
attorney general certified that the motive for the killing was to
coerce, intimidate or retaliate against a government or civilian
population.
   The Bush administration has not taken a position on the narrowly
drawn, one-page bill, but it does support a proposal that
prescribes capital punishment for an array of federal crimes.
   The Senate plans to vote on that measure later as part of a
wide-ranging anti-crime package.
   The Senate rejected, 70-29, a move to replace the death penalty
for such terrorist murders with life in prison.
   Specter said courts should have the option of imposing the death
penalty on terrorists such as those who planted the bomb aboard the
Pan American jetliner that exploded over Scotland in December,
killing 259 people.
   Opponents said easing the maximum penalty to life in prison
actually makes the legislation stronger than Specter's proposal,
which they said would allow courts to impose comparatively short
sentences or even fines.
   ``You have a possibility in there which is repugnant, which is
that a person convicted of murdering an American citizen in the
course of a terrorist act will be given a term of years,'' said
Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich.
   ``If you want to see the people who murdered Leon Klinghoffer
get a term of years, you vote for the Specter bill,'' Levin said,
referring to an American tourist in a wheelchair who was shot on a
cruise ship and thrown into the Mediterranean.
   Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., said executing terrorists would
provide them ``with the publicity they so ravenously seek and give
them martyrdom as reward.'' He urged the Senate not to succumb to
``a lust for revenge.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
