<DOCNO> AP891027-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0727EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MidwestDrought     10-27 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Midwest Drought,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers Battle Persistent Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG COUGHLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts say this year's drought isn't as
bad as last year's, but that's little consolation for farmers like
Verdun Schauer.
   ``I've never seen a failure two years in a row, but there are no
rules against it, I guess,'' said Schauer, 49, who abandoned about
half the 1,500 acres of barley and wheat this year on his farm east
of Bismarck.
   Although this year's drought is less widespread than last
year's, its effects are more devastating as it reaches deeper into
the soil.
   ``We need a lot of moisture to recharge,'' Schauer said.
``There's no subsoil moisture at all.''
   This year's drought stretches from parts of Illinois through the
Dakotas and parts of Kansas and Nebraska, said Norton Strommen,
chief meteorologist for the U.S. Agriculture Department.
   The soil is so dry in the most severely stricken areas of
northern Iowa, south-central Minnesota and the upper Plains that it
would take 4 to 10 inches of rain to bring moisture to normal
levels, he said.
   ``It's not as bad this year,'' Strommen said. ``This year we got
very timely rains ... and yields are up. But it was only because of
the timing and the distribution of the rains, combined with the
temperature patterns that allowed us to get good crops.''
   Nationwide, producers are seeing yield increases of up to 30
percent over last year, Strommen said. Farmers also planted more
acreage than in 1988.
   Still, parts or all of about a dozen states have requested
disaster asistance. The final loss figures have yet to be compiled,
but states like Nebraska and North Dakota expect to lose about a
third of their cash crops.
   Schauer said he lost almost all his crop in 1988, but had enough
carryover feed to sustain his livestock. This year he has no
carryover and will have to sell cattle.
   ``The second year of a disaster is always worse because you
don't have the cushion to get you through that you had the first
year,'' said economist Dwight Aakre at North Dakota State
University.
   In Iowa, the situation has improved, ``but not in all cases by
any means,'' said Harry Hillaker, state climatologist.
   Officials in Missouri, Montana and Wisconsin say more farmers
have healthy crops. But fall has been unseasonably dry, and some
rivers are at all-time lows.
   ``There were places I walked where you had to swim before,''
said Marshall Ruegger, a forestry official in Madison, Wis. He said
reservoirs on the Wisconsin River were at 20 percent of of capacity
rather than the normal 50 percent at this time of year.
   In Coleharbor, N.D., recharge ponds that held the city's water
supply were so depleted the Army Corps of Engineers agreed to pump
water 3{ miles from Lake Sakakawea on the Missouri River.
   ``We had approximately a month left before we ran out of
water,'' said Clayton Boots, auditor for the town of about 150.
   Twenty of Nebraska's 73 counties find the second year of drought
even more painful than the first.
   Nebraska fared well last year because of a large irrigated corn
crop, said Lynn Lutgen, a University of Nebraska-Lincoln
agriculture economist.
   The 90-day weather forecast calls for near-normal precipitation
and temperatures over much of the nation's heartland.
   ``But that probably won't make it up,'' said Ken Kunkel,
director of the Midwest Climate Center in Champaign, Ill. ``That
would require a couple months of above-normal precipitation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
