<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0325EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Senate-Poland     10-27 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senate-Poland,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Stalling Aid to Poland with Capital Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate's attempt to speed aid to Poland
and Hungary is stalled by a Republican bid to advance an unrelated
and controversial issue _ the capital gains tax cut.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell made clear Thursday that
he would not permit a Republican amendment containing a
capital-gains measure to come to a vote, a decision that threw the
fate of the Poland-Hungary authorization bill into doubt.
   Aides said the Maine Democrat would temporarily shelve the aid
bill and take up a series of appropriations measures, forcing a
delay likely to postpone consideration of the aid bill for at least
several days.
   The Senate on Thursday managed to approve a separate resolution
that will send a team of congressional experts to Warsaw to learn
what the newly elected Polish legislature needs in terms of
training, organization, computers and other office equipment.
   The team then will seek donations from U.S. manufacturers to
provide basic hardware to help the parliament organize, said Sen.
Pete Domenici, R-N.M., the measure's chief sponsor.
   Mitchell denounced the GOP's action in injecting the capital
gains controversy into the Eastern European aid package, calling it
irresponsible in light of Poland's severe economic problems.
   But Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas and other GOP members
said delaying the passage of the aid bill won't affect the flow of
aid to Eastern Europe.
   ``All of this wringing of hands is pure politics,'' Dole said.
``It's the old Democratic game of crying wolf.''
   Domenici said ``no one in Poland should be concerned'' by the
delay because the aid program will be funded only by actual
appropriations, not authorizations that set maximum levels of aid
and spell out policy guidelines.
   In fact, Domenici said, $100 million in food aid for Poland has
already been appropriated and is en route to Poland.
   ``The principal ingredients are either already funded, or will
be funded,'' Domenici said.
   The authorization bill features competing Democratic and
Republican spending levels. Democrats seek $989 million over three
years; Republicans want a leaner, $585 million package.
   Bush's insistence on a capital-gains cut and the Democratic
leadership's opposition to it have overshadowed consideration of
budget issues since June.
   The fight has delayed action on a deficit-reduction bill until
Nov. 1 at the earliest, a full month after the opening of the 1990
budget year. It threatens to delay a bill to raise the government's
borrowing authority past Oct. 31.
   The House voted a capital-gains tax cut as part of its
deficit-reduction plan. The cut being pushed by Senate Republicans
is considerably different from the House plan and includes an
expansion of Individual Retirement Accounts.
   If action on the Poland-Hungary aid bill is delayed past this
week, as appears likely, Republican senators likely will try to add
their capital-gains reduction to legislation boosting government
borrowing authority. Democrats would try to talk the GOP effort to
death, and the borrowing bill would be caught in the crossfire.
   Unless the borrowing authority is raised next week, the
government might be forced into several drastic actions, including
delaying Social Security checks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
