<FIRST>r a PM-FastestTapper     10-27 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fastest Tapper,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicagoan Dances Into Guinness Book With 28 Taps Per Second</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto CX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Flatley knew he had fast feet, but didn't
think about seeking official recognition for his tap-dancing
prowess until Sen. Ted Kennedy suggested he try for a spot in the
``Guinness Book of World Records.''
   Then it became a quest for the 31-year old hoofer, who made it
into the new edition of the record book with a 28-tap-per-second
performance.
   ``I really believed I was the best in the world, and I'm saying
this as modestly as I can, it seemed to me to be a good way to
prove I was the best,'' he said in a recent interview.
   ``Tap dancing, for me, is a very powerful, masculine thing,'' he
said. ``That's how I approach it.''
   His feet are enshrined in the Guinness edition that arrived in
bookstores this week. Heel-and-toeing it for a tape recorder and
Guinness judges in a suburban dance studio in May, he beat the
previous record of 24 taps per second, set by Roy Castle on Jan.
14, 1973, on a BBC-TV program.
   Flatley, a native of southwest Chicago, developed his
nimble-legged style through years of Irish step dancing, and won
the world step dancing championship in Dublin in 1975.
   People had suggested he try for a tap record before, but it was
at a performance for the Massachusetts Democrat last year that
Flatley's mind was made up.
   ``Ted Kennedy said, `Your feet should be in the Guinness Book of
World Records,'' Flatley recalled. ``I became obsessed with it. I
had no idea it was going to be that difficult.''
   Since Flatley's training comes from step dancing _ done with
arms rigidly held at the side of the body _ he has his detractors
among purists of dance.
   ``Well, he made 28 sounds with his feet,'' said Lane Alexander,
a noted tap teacher and performer in Chicago. ``That doesn't make
him a tap dancer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
