<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0341EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DelayedDiplomas     10-27 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Delayed Diplomas,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Americans to Get High School Diplomas 47 Years Late</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In June 1942, Hayao Shishino waited for his
diploma with hundreds of other Japanese-American high school
seniors attending graduation ceremonies at an internment camp.
   His wait lasted 47 years.
   Shishino's name, and those of 14 fellow Japanese-American
seniors from Los Angeles High School, were never called.
   Because they were among 120,000 Japanese-Americans forced into
camps after war broke out with Japan, the students couldn't afford
caps and gowns or graduation parties, but they were looking forward
to getting the diplomas.
   ``We waited until the last to hear our names,'' Shishino
recalled this week. ``We waited to hear our school. But we waited
for nothing.''
   On Saturday, a special ceremony will be held at Los Angeles High
in an attempt to redress, at least in part, what today's Los
Angeles Unified School Board members believe was a historical wrong.
   Shishino and 10 of the 15 other former students will finally get
their sheepskins. They will be dated June 26, 1942, but will be
signed by members of the current school board.
   One of the 15 has since died and three others cannot attend the
ceremony, Shishino said.
   Other Japanese-American students imprisoned in the camp at Santa
Anita Racetrack before the end of their senior year in 1942 got
their diplomas at that original ceremony. Shishino blames wartime
anti-Japanese hysteria and the attitudes of the late Paul Webb,
principal of Los Angeles High, for his being left out.
   Webb, who died in 1982, refused to issue the students' diplomas
even though the School Board ordered that all graduating
Japanese-American seniors in good standing be given diplomas,
Shishino said.
   ``He told me flat to my face that I didn't deserve one,''
recalled Shishino, now 64 and a retired cook living in the Los
Angeles suburb of Cerritos. ``He was just prejudiced against
Japanese-Americans.''
   The new ceremony grew out of a letter Shishino wrote earlier
this year to Warren Furutani, a Los Angeles Unified School Board
member and a Japanese-American whose mother-in-law was among the
students who were denied diplomas.
   Furutani had district employees search old records to document
Shishino's claims. Shishino and the other former students received
letters last week announcin gthe ceremony.
   ``It was time to set the record straight,'' said Furutani.
   More important than the diplomas will be the chance to educate
Americans about the injustices suffered by Japanese-Americans
during World War II, said Furutani's mother-in-law, Aiko Yoshinaga.
   ``Some people just don't believe there were such things as
concentration camps in this country,'' said Mrs. Yoshinaga, who
planned to fly out from her Virginia home for the ceremony.
   ``Many young people still don't know the Japanese-Americans were
treated as enemy aliens,'' said Shishino, who was born in Los
Angeles.
   Although upset about being left out of the communal graduation
ceremony, ``getting my diploma was the least of my worries in those
days,'' he said.
   ``Just surviving and thinking about the future were more
important. You see we had lost everything _ our apartment, our
furniture, our cars, my father's flower business,'' said Shishino.
``My parents were just given two weeks to take the most important
things we owned and pack it into one suitcase.''
   The U.S. House voted Thursday to begin making $1.2 billion in
reparation payments next year to the 60,000 surviving
Japanese-Americans confined to camps during World War II. The bill
now moves to the Senate.
   But Shishino says it's more than a matter of money.
   ``Money alone can never repay the injustice we've suffered,'' he
said. ``We were Americans and we were treated like we were spies.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
