<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief 640   10-27 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief, 640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gingrich Labels New Ethics Charges Baseless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich is calling
new ethics charges filed against him by an Arkansas Democrat
baseless and politically motivated.
   Gingrich said Thursday that the latest ethics complaint by Rep.
Bill Alexander is the product of ``a deeply troubled and desperate
man'' trying to generate publicity.
   Alexander filed his new complaint, along with 670 pages of
supporting documents, late Wednesday, a week after the outside
counsel hired by the House ethics committee to evaluate his first
complaint against Gingrich concluded there was no reason for the
panel to investigate the Georgia Republican.
   The committee will meet Tuesday.
   Gingrich rose to prominence in the House after filing the ethics
complaint that led to the resignation in June of Jim Wright, a
Texas Democrat who was Speaker of the House.
   Gingrich denied several of the allegations, including
Alexander's contention that he funneled $12,000 in advertising and
$20,000 in contributions to the 1986 re-election campaign of
then-Sen. Mack Mattingly, R-Ga., and didn't report either as
required by federal election law.
   Alexander's initial complaint alleged that Gingrich violated
House rules and federal campaign finance laws by getting 21
supporters to invest $5,000 each in a limited partnership to
promote his 1984 book, ``Window of Opportunity.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Community Colleges Failing to Help Students Transfer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study says community colleges are failing to
motivate poor and minority students to go beyond their two-year
programs.
   ``The transfer function of community colleges is in crisis,''
said the Academy for Educational Development report, funded by the
Ford Foundation and published by the College Board.
   Researchers Fred Pincus and Elayne Archer said two-year colleges
are a critical part of the educational system and have an important
role to play because they have taken ``on the awesome task of
working to salvage hope for so many who have been given up on by
others.''
   But they said it is equally important that community colleges
work to ``provide paths of upward mobility'' by helping students
transfer to four-year colleges.
   The report, ``Bridges to Opportunity,'' said a small percentage
of community college students transfer to four-year schools and
fewer yet actually get bachelor's degrees. It said the transfer
rates are smaller for black, Hispanic, and Indian students than for
white and Asian-American students.
   Pincus said studies show that one-third to one-half of students
say they enrolled in a community college to prepare for transfer to
a four-year school.
   But he said the current transfer rate is 15 percent to 25
percent of all community college students and 20 percent to 30
percent of those students who say they want to transfer. Only 10
percent to 15 percent of all community college students receive a
bachelor's degree, he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Average Private Contract Wage Gains Put at 3.1 Percent Annually</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Department reports that
private-sector workers who got new contracts through collective
bargaining from January through September won average annual wage
increases of 3.1 percent.
   That compared with average gains of 2.4 percent in their prior
contracts, the department said Thursday.
   The data covers contracts for 1.3 million workers negotiated in
the first nine months of the year.
   If the trend continues for the final three months, 1989 would be
the first year since 1981 in which new contracts provide workers
with better pay raises, on average, than their prior contracts, the
department said.
   The rebound in wage gains was attributed to the restoration of
prior concessions in several industries that were slumping earlier
in the decade, particularly the U.S. steel industry.
   Also, the Labor Department said wage increases given workers in
the health care sector, particularly nurses, were outpacing the
gains provided in prior contracts. Competition for skilled workers
in that sector has pushed wages higher.
</TEXT>
