<FIRST>r a PM-HeadInjuries     10-27 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Head Injuries,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Head Injury Deaths Caused by Motor Vehicles, Firearms and Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Head injuries caused 2 percent of all deaths in
the United States in a recent seven-year period, and the most
common causes were auto crashes, guns and falls, according to
doctors who studied such deaths.
   The death rate for Americans with head injuries was 16.9 per
100,000 people from 1979 through 1986, said Dr. Daniel M. Sosin and
his colleagues at the Division of Injury Epidemiology and Control
of the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta.
   They reported in today's edition of the Journal of the American
Medical Association that they identified 315,328 deaths associated
with head injuries.
   Of those injuries, 57 percent were suffered in motor vehicle
accidents, most commonly among people younger than 35, the
physicians said.
   Whites ages 15 to 24 had a death rate of 22.7 per 100,000 from
head injuries suffered in motor vehicle accidents, the researchers
said. Blacks of the same age group had a death rate of 9.2 per
100,000 from vehicle accidents.
   Another 14 percent of the fatal head injuries were caused by
guns.
   Among blacks ages 25 to 34, homicides by firearm caused 4.2
deaths per 100,000 _ more than five times the rate for whites in
the same age group.
   The death rate for head injuries from suicidal gunshot wounds,
however, was much higher for whites of all ages _ 1.64 per 100,000
_ than it was for blacks, with a rate of 0.65 per 100,000.
   Falls were the third most common cause of fatal head injuries,
accounting for 12 percent of the total, the physicians found. They
also found that the death rate for falls rose with the age of the
populace.
   The sharpest rise came after age 75, Sosin said, with 20.6
deaths per 100,000 for males in the oldest age group, and 11.3 per
100,000 for women.
</TEXT>
