<FIRST>u a AM-PrisonDisturbance 10thLd-Writethru a0499 10-27 1206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison Disturbance, 10th Ld - Writethru, a0499,1232</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Violence Breaks Out at Pennsylvania Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `State police ...' to UPDATE with total injured
in two nights and SUBS 14th graf, `At least ...' with total injured in
second day alone to conform. ^LaserPhoto HX4, HX5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID MORRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMP HILL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 state prison inmates
rioted for a second night Thursday, taking eight hostages and
igniting numerous fires and explosions that shrouded the prison in
thick black smoke, authorities said.
   State police and firefighters struggled to regain control of the
Camp Hill medium-security prison early Friday with three cell
blocks and four other housing units ablaze. At least 84 people have
been injured in two days of rioting, but no fatalities were
reported.
   Flames from a huge fire just inside the main gate shot 50 to 100
feet into the air and several explosions were heard. The incident,
which began during a lockdown, started shortly after 7 p.m.
Thursday.
   ``It's total chaos. They lost control,'' said a guard who was in
one of the cell blocks when Thursday's disturbance began. ``The
officers were told to lock the doors and leave. We had to get out.
... They said they were going to kill us.
   ``Last night was a riot. Tonight was war,'' said the guard, a
six-year staff member. He refused to give his name.
   Another guard said an explosion was ignited in the prison's
furniture factory. The force rattled windows up to about a mile
away. Inmates threw rocks at firefighters as they battled the main
gate fire.
   At about 1:30 a.m., there was a large explosion in an area about
300 yards from the inferno. One building inside the complex
collapsed, said Sgt. Alan Taylor of the Mechanicsburg police.
   ``Basically the prison is a total loss. All the buildings are
destroyed,'' said Cpl. David Steffen of the Northern York County
Regional police, who were called in to assist.
   John Palakovich, assistant to the prison superintendent, said
one hostage, a guard, had been released shortly after midnight. He
gave no details.
   Inmates holding the hostages were demanding to talk to Gov.
Robert P. Casey and the human rights group Amnesty International,
said state police Cpl. Raul Ramos, who said negotiations were
taking place by phone. Casey said earlier in the day he would not
talk with the inmates.
   State police, who had about 500 troopers at the scene, began to
retake the prison after midnight, Palakovich said.
   ``It is under way,'' he said. Four cellblocks had been regained
and 700 of the prison's 2,600 inmates were under control, he said.
   Earlier, Palakovich said ``there are more inmates involved at
this point than there were last night,'' when 1,200 prisoners went
on a rampage. A total of nine fires were set Thursday, causing more
extensive damage than the previous night's riot, he said.
   At least 37 eople were injured in the second night of rioting,
most of them firefighters, Palakovich said. Local hospitals
reported treating 20 people. Others were treated at the scene about
4 miles west of Harrisburg, the state capital.
   Palakovich said he couldn't say whether the seven remaining
hostages were guards or support staff and he believed they were
being held in two separate cell blocks. He said there was some
contact between inmates and prison negotiators.
   Inmates had gotten into prison tools, such as screwdrivers,
hammers and saws, Palakovich said. He had no reports that prisoners
had any weapons.
   Inmates milled around the prison yard as flames leaped from at
least two buildings and a police helicopter hovered overhead. Other
police fired warning shots in the air. A firetruck was inside the
prison fence pouring water on one of the fires.
   Just before midnight, five officers on horseback were sent into
the prison.
   Earlier, prison authorities said inmates had been locked in
their cells and a state of emergency was in effect following
Wednesday's rampage, during which four buildings were torched.
   Palakovich said the latest incident started during a feeding
period, but he could not explain how prisoners got out of their
locked cells while being served meals. He said some inmates got
keys and let other inmates out of their cells.
   ``There was a bunch of little fires at first, but they started
putting mattresses on the windows,'' said Steve Tobias of nearby
Lemoyne, who was passing the prison as the new outbreak began.
   He said ``a whole bunch of (inmates) were running toward the
fence. But when they heard the shots, they went back the other
way.''
   Palakovich said fires were burning in three of 10 cell blocks
and four modular housing units _ trailer-like buildings used to
ease overcrowding _ and the education building. Earlier in the day,
Prison Superintendent Robert Freeman said Wednesday's seven-hour
riot may have been caused by overcrowding and inmates' anger over
policy changes.
   During that uprising, eight guards were held hostage for up to
four hours and some guards were beaten. Four guards and one inmate
were still hospitalized Thursday.
   Before Thursday night's eruption, Freeman met for an hour with
six of the inmates who had helped negotiate an end to the siege the
day before. He said inmates were upset by changes in the prison's
medical care policy and over a decision not to allow families to
bring in food during extended family-day visits.
   Overcrowded conditions and a shortage of guards may also have
contributed to the disturbance, he said. Camp Hill, with 2,600
inmates, is about 45 percent over capacity and the entire state
prison system is about 48 percent over capacity.
   Attorney General Ernie Preate Jr. said the disturbance at Camp
Hill and a smaller uprising at Huntingdon state prison on Monday
were ``the predictable result of a prison crowding crisis that has
been allowed to fester for too long.''
   Freeman said he did not make any promises during the meeting. He
also said no decision has been made on whether to file charges.
   The new medical policy actually improves access to care, but
inmates viewed the change as an attempt to restrict health care,
Freeman said, adding that the staff could have done a better job
explaining the changes. The change involved assigning routine
examinations to certain days.
   Freeman said that food could no longer be brought in because it
could be used to bring in drugs, cash and other contraband.
   Thirty-five prison guards or staff, nine inmates, two state
police troopers and a firefighter were injured in Wednesday's riot,
said Ken Robinson, a spokesman for the state Department of
Corrections.
   One of the guards, Glenn L. Koons, 63, of Hershey, was in
serious condition in intensive care at Community General
Osteopathic Hospital in Harrisburg with multiple fractures. The
condition of the others ranged from fair to good, hospital
officials said.
   Freeman said six of the 10 cellblocks were damaged extensively
and the commissary was destroyed in Wednesday's riot.
   This week's uprisings were the latest in a series of problems
within Pennsylvania's prison system. A federal judge in August
ordered the state to close part of the Western Penitentiary in
Pittsburgh because of unsafe and ``unconstitutional conditions.''
The state is challenging that ruling and the prison remains open.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
