<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0520EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WarrenMemorial     10-27 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Warren Memorial,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Robert Penn Warren Remembered As Great Writer, Great American</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Old friends of the late Robert Penn
Warren remembered him for his personal warmth instead of ``his
great mound of medals'' his poems and novels won.
   ``Though he was frail he was always willing to give of
himself,'' said Alex Szogyi, a student of Warren's at Yale
University in the 1950s. ``That a great writer should have been a
great man is a rarity indeed and Red Warren was one of the rarest
of the great.''
   Nearly 150 people, including authors Ralph Ellison and William
Styron, joined members of Warren's family for a memorial service
Thursday in a faculty room at Connecticut Hall on Yale's campus.
   Warren died Sept. 15 at his summer home in Stratton, Vt., at age
84.
   Born in Guthrie, Ky., in 1905, he grew up hearing stories of the
Civil War from his two grandfathers _ both Confederate soldiers _
and went on to spin his own tales of the Old South. He lived the
last three decades of his life in New England.
   He was the only person to win Pulitzer Prizes for both fiction
and poetry. His novel ``All The King's Men,'' inspired by the
populist governor of Louisiana, Huey Long, won the Pulitzer in
1947. His poetry prizes came in 1957 for ``Promises: Poems
1954-1956,'' and in 1979 for ``Now and Then: Poems 1976-1978.''
   He taught at Yale for 22 years, retiring in 1973. In 1986, he
became the nation's first official poet laureate.
   Ellison; Yale President Benno C. Schmidt, who studied under
Warren as a student at Yale; Warren's editor at Random Books,
Albert Erskine; and historian C. Vann Woodward, a friend since the
1940s, also reminisced about the author.
   Two Yale freshmen recited his poems ``Heart of Autumn'' and
``Bearded Oaks.'' They did so from memory _ as Warren always
preferred his students to do.
   ``He was a great Southerner, but he was a great American,'' said
Cleanth Brooks, his friend and collaborator.
   He said he wanted to speak of Warren the man in an attempt to
``rescue him from his great mound of medals.''
   Warren loved America and ``rejoiced in it for he knew its
failings as he knew the failings of his own section. It was a great
thing to know something so well that you loved it,'' Brooks said.
   Warren's widow, author Eleanor Clark, his son, Gabriel, and his
daughter, Rosanna, attended the service and a reception afterward.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
