<DOCNO> AP891027-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0605EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Missiles     10-27 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Missiles,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Announce Destruction of Last Shorter-Range Missile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union today destroyed the 957th and
last of its shorter-range nuclear missiles in keeping with a
superpower treaty banning them, the official Tass news agency
announced.
   Tass said the missile, known in the West as an SS-23, was
destroyed at the Saryozek test range in the Soviet Central Asian
republic of Kazakhstan at 9 a.m. Moscow time (1 a.m. EDT). It said
U.S. inspectors were present.
   The missile, designated OTR-23 by the Soviets, had a range of
310 miles and was put into service in the early 1980s, Tass said.
It was among the medium- and shorter-range nuclear missiles banned
by the treaty signed at the December 1987 superpower summit in
Washington.
   ``A whole class of nuclear weapons _ shorter-range missiles _
ceased to exist in the Soviet Union today,'' Tass quoted Col. Gen.
Bronislav Omelichev, first deputy chief of the Soviet general
staff, as saying.
   Elimination of the SS-23s began at Saryozek in August 1988, he
said.
   The U.S.-Soviet treaty also mandates the scrapping of the
superpowers' medium-range nuclear missiles, including the American
Pershing 2 and the Soviet SS-20.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
