<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0615EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChainedInmates     10-27 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chained Inmates,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmates Chained to Walls in Baltimore Police Stations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prisoners are kept chained to the walls of
local police lockups for as long as three days at a time because of
overcrowding in regular jail cells, police said.
   Overcrowding at the Baltimore County Detention Center has forced
police to house hundreds of prisoners in nine precinct stations,
which lack the facilities or staff to keep prisoners under constant
observation while in their cells, authorities said.
   The prisoners are chained to horseshoe-shaped bars fastened to a
wall near the booking area of each precinct, where desk supervisors
can watch them, said Stephen R. Doarnberger, a police spokesman.
   Their legs are shackled at the ankles and one arm is attached to
the bar with leg irons to give them enough mobility to sit or
stand, he said.
   At night, the prisoners are given a small mattress and a
blanket, Doarnberger said. They eat in the hallway, but are
released to use the restroom.
   The other prisoners are kept together in a single cell with one
toilet. Most sleep on the floor, with mattresses provided each
night.
   Mark A. Levine, the county undersheriff, said the county
Detention Center, which can properly handle 410 prisoners,
currently houses 697 inmates.
   An annex that will add 228 beds is not expected to be ready for
another three years.
   ``That leaves us between a rock and a hard place,'' said Col.
Michael D. Gambrill, who is in charge of the lockups. ``We are not
really supposed to be in the prison business, but we are.''
   Gambrill said one reason for the added vigilance was to guard
against suicide attempts. Earlier this year, a federal jury awarded
$185,000 to the family of a man who killed himself at a precinct
station in 1987.
   Thirteen prisoners attempted suicide in the lockups this year,
police said, and 33 tried to kill themselves last year, all
unsuccessfully. In 1987, there were 13 attempted suicides in the
lockups and two suicides.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
