<FIRST>r a PM-CocaineTrial     10-27 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine Trial,0507</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Two Acquitted, Three Convicted In Drug Case ^By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Americans face prison terms of
10 years to life after being convicted of conspiring with Colombian
drug kingpin Carlos Lehder Rivas to smuggle cocaine into the United
States.
   Two others were acquitted, by a federal jury.
   The so-called ``Son of Lehder'' case grew out of testimony in
last year's trial of of the Medellin cartel boss, who was convicted
and is serving a life term.
   Jack Carlton Reed, 59, who was convicted with Lehder last year
on drug conspiracy charges and sentenced to 15 years in prison, was
found guilty Thursday of conspiracy to distribute cocaine and
operating a continuing criminal enterprise.
   Barry Kane, 52, a Hyannis, Mass., attorney, and Donald Lady, 41,
of Pomona, Calif., were both convicted of conspiracy to import
cocaine, but were found innocent of conspiracy to distribute it.
   The defendants face prison terms of from 10 years to life.
Sentencing was scheduled for Jan. 12.
   Kane collapsed after U.S. District Judge John H. Moore II
pronounced him guilty. He was quickly revived and wasn't
hospitalized.
   Kane, Lady and Reed were ordered held pending sentencing,
although Moore said he would consider a motion from Kane's attorney
that his client be freed on bond.
   Acquitted were Thomas H. Herington, 35, of Mill Valley, Calif.,
and Samuel T. Stewart, 53, of Anaheim, Calif.
   After the verdicts, a federal prosecutor said he's ready to try
the top leaders of Colombia's Medellin cartel here if they can be
caught. They were charged under the same indictment, but are
fugitives.
   ``It is our hope we can get Pablo Escobar, Gonzalo Rodriguez
Gacha, Jorge Ochoa, Fabio Ochoa and Gonzalo Mejia. We feel we have
the best case against them,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Ernst
Mueller.
   The prosecutor said Jorge Mario de la Cuesta, who is named in
the indictment, has been arrested in Colombia and may be extradited
to Jacksonville to stand trial. He has been identified as Escobar's
private pilot.
   Thursday's verdicts came after 18 hours of deliberation over
three days.
   The five were accused of conspiring with Lehder either to
smuggle cocaine into the United States or distribute it once it got
here.
   Lehder, 40, is reputed to be a co-founder of Colombia's Medellin
cartel, which is believed responsible for 80 percent of the cocaine
that enters the United States.
   ``Justice prevailed,'' said Stewart as he left the courthouse
following the 7-week-long trial. ``If it is any consolation, I was
innocent.''
   Kevin Sanders, who represented Stewart, said his client's
health, air-charter business and reputation had suffered as a
result of the trial.
   ``He's just very happy. He was truly innocent,'' he said.
   Herington, a student in engineering physics, refused to comment,
but his attorney, Patrick Hallinan, said, ``It's a great pleasure.
He's very, very happy. He faced the prospect of spending the rest
of his life in prison.''
</TEXT>
