<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Helm     10-27 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Helm,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banners and Poster Celebrate New Town Hero _ Buck Helm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEAVERVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banners and posters celebrate this
tiny town's newest legend _ earthquake survivor Buck Helm.
   ``This One's for You, Buck,'' says a sign in the window of the
New York Saloon. ``Our Thoughts Are With You, Buck and Bay Area,''
reads a banner on the courthouse.
   On the marquee of the Trinity Theater, Helm shares billing with
this week's movie. ``God Bless Family Helm. Cheeta and Friends,''
the sign reads.
   Helm, trapped in his car in the collapse of the double-decked
I-880 freeway during the Oct. 17 quake, survived to be rescued four
days later.
   The 57-year-old longshoreman's clerk, who works the docks in
Oakland and commutes 250 miles on weekends to visit his family
here, remained hospitalized with a fractured skull, three broken
ribs, nerve damage to his leg and kidney problems due to
dehydration.
   Along Main Street, with its covered sidewalks and historic
buildings, shopkeepers have posted handwritten signs in their
windows to congratulate Helm _ and indulge in a little
self-promotion.
   On Thursday, the Chamber of Commerce, the Red Cross and local
officials held a news conference seeking donations for victims of
the quake and predicting that Helm's fame would bring new visitors
to this town of about 3,500 people.
   ``Any recognition doesn't hurt,'' said Trinity County Supervisor
Dee Potter.
   Many local businessmen and officials are pleased with all the
attention Weaverville has gotten because of Helm, a survivor's
story in the 7.1-magnitude quake that killed over 60 people,
injured more than 3,000 and left over 14,000 homeless throughout
Northern California.
   But some townsfolk who moved here for the isolation, aren't
thrilled with efforts to capitalize on Helm's sudden fame.
   ``It's bringing the town a lot of publicity,'' said Nola
Brimhall, a teller at North Valley Bank. ``I'm not sure we want the
word to get too far out there.''
</TEXT>
