<SECOND>PM-Head Lice,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Girl Burned With Gasoline Used to Treat Head Lice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENDLETON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-year-old girl whose mother tried to
treat her head lice with gasoline was in critical condition today
after the gas fumes were ignited by the pilot light in a stove.
   Crystal Kilgore was burned on her head, hands, neck, back and
arms in the accident Wednesday night, police said. She was in
critical condition at Humana Burn Center in Augusta.
   The mother put gasoline on the girl's head, then took her
through the kitchen to rinse her hair in the sink. On the way, the
child got close to the gas stove and her hair caught fire.
   The mother burned her hands trying to put out the fire. Her
boyfriend managed to smother the fire with a blanket, police said.
   Pendleton Police Chief James Cleveland said the incident was
under investigation, although he doubted officers would file
charges.
   ``Gasoline is not a recommended way to get rid of head lice,''
said Janie King, child health nurse with the Appalachia Health
District. ``It's an old wive's tale which is extremely dangerous.''
   Several over-the-counter medications and prescriptions are
available to kill head lice, she said.
