<FIRST>r p PM-HoustonMayoral     10-27 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Houston Mayoral,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whitmire Seeks Fifth Term as Houston Mayor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to correct category code.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Incumbent Kathy Whitmire is banking on her
leadership during the lean years of the oil bust to carry her to a
record-tying fifth consecutive term as mayor of Houston.
   Polls give her a large lead over former two-term mayor Fred
Hofheinz, her main opponent among six challengers in the Nov. 7
election.
   Mrs. Whitmire, a 43-year-old accountant, won her first two-year
term in 1978. A recent Houston Chronicle poll showed Mrs. Whitmire
with a lead of nearly 20 percent over Hofheinz.
   ``It seems like this is going to be a very difficult race for
Mr. Hofheinz to turn around _ very difficult,'' said Bob Stein, a
Rice University political scientist. ``At this point I can't
identify an issue that he can do that with.
   ``The issue he has chosen to campaign on _ drugs _ he is losing.
He is not seen as more capable to fight the war on drugs.''
   Hofheinz contends that ``the current administration has run out
of gas.'' He added that if eight years are enough for a president,
it should be more than enough for Mrs. Whitmire.
   In her 1985 campaign, Mrs. Whitmire easily whipped former Mayor
Louie Welch, whose 1964-1973 tenure set a longevity record she is
trying to match. The city's longest-serving chief executive, Oscar
Holcombe, held office for 22 years, but not consecutively, between
1921 and 1958.
   Mrs. Whitmire said she looks forward to leading the nation's
fourth-largest city into the 1990s.
   She has pledged to make the fight on illegal drugs her highest
priority. ``We need to make this city the least attractive to crack
dealers,'' she said.
   Hofheinz argues that the drug war cannot be won without the
Houston Police Department's support. Two major police unions,
bitterly at odds with Mrs. Whitmire, have endorsed Hofheinz,
although they opposed him when he was in office from 1974 to 1977.
   Hofheinz, 51, an attorney with a doctorate in economics,
attributes low police morale to Mrs. Whitmire's administration.
Until the first police cadet class of 70 began this month, some 500
officers had left the department in the past three years and none
were replaced.
   With city revenues down because of the oil bust, police and
other city workers took a 3 percent pay cut in 1986. Only recently
was the cut restored.
   Mrs. Whitmire took office at the height of the oil boom. When
the bubble burst, unemployment reached almost 13 percent, prominent
businesses filed for bankruptcy, skyscrapers sat empty and the
housing market came to a standstill.
   Mrs. Whitmire said she has steered the city through the tough
times and boasts that unemployment has been lowered to about 5
percent.
   ``Now that Houston is enjoying economic recovery, it is no
surprise that others relish the thought of serving as mayor,'' Mrs.
Whitmire said.
   Another change Houstonians have seen during the mayor's tenure
is with the mayor herself.
   Gone are the dowdy days of dark suits with bow ties, large-frame
glasses and shoulder-length locks that had local wits comparing her
to the female impersonator Dustin Hoffman portrayed in ``Tootsie.''
   The mayor has switched to brighter, fashionable dresses and
suits, contact lenses, and a modified bob haircut.
</TEXT>
