<FIRST>u i PM-EastGermany 1stLd-Writethru a0452 10-27 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Germany, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0452,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massive Rallies For Reform As Authorities Meet with Opposition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with amnesty for jailed would-be escapees;
no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany's new leadership today declared an
amnesty for all citizens accused of illegally trying to escape from
the communist nation, a move expected to free several thousand
people from prison.
   The amnesty also would allow tens of thousands of East Germans
who have fled to West Germany through Hungary, Czechoslovakia and
Poland in recent months to return home without facing criminal
prosecution.
   The announcement came a day after more than 100,000 people
rallied in Dresden and other East German cities for democratic
reform, and a Politburo member began talks with a leading
opposition group.
   The amnesty, which also covers those who took part in illegal
street protests, is the firmest step toward reform since Egon Krenz
replaced long-time leader Erich Honecker as Communist Party chief
on Oct. 18.
   It was announced by the official news agency ADN, which said all
prisoners affected would be freed by Nov. 30. Although East Germany
does not release information on inmate numbers, Western sources
said the measure would affect thousands.
   ADN said the amnesty covered all people accused of border
violations through today.
   Also today, the nation's legendary former intelligence chief,
Markus Wolf, called for greater openness and expressed some
sympathy for the refugees who headed West.
   In an interview with party newspaper Neues Deutschland, Wolf
said, ``the recovery of trust is demanded before we can develop
further,'' indicating Krenz may be open to loosening some
constraints on the media and free expression.
   Late Thursday, the state-run ADN news agency reported the huge
rally in Dresden and said 15,000 people also marched in Erfurt,
25,000 in Rostock and 5,000 more in Gera.
   Earlier, East Berlin Communist Party chief Guenter Schabowski
talked for two hours with scientists Jens Reich and Sebastian
Pflugbeil, founding members of the group New Forum. It was the
first time a member of the ruling Polituro met with the group, the
largest of the new organizations pushing for reform.
   Communist authorities banned New Forum in September but have
tolerated the group anyway.
   Reich described the talks as ``open and constructive. We
presented New Forum's concepts and ideas.''
   He said Schabowski ``told us he wanted to begin a new political
course and wanted to learn about the whole political spectrum
here.''
   Reich, a molecular biologist at East Berlin's Academy of
Sciences, said Schabowski assured him the government's interest in
talks to solve the nation's problems ``was a real change and not a
tactical move.''
   Reich and other New Forum leaders later addressed several
hundred people in an East Berlin church to explain the group's aims
and their talks with Schabowski.
   East German television broadcast a special program on the church
meeting. The television and ADN reports both marked a radical
change from previous practice, when state-controlled media limited
themselves to reporting only official party policy.
   In staging rallies Thursday, demonstrators ignored an earlier
appeal by Communist authorities for citizens not to protest in the
streets.
   In Dresden, however, the demonstration appeared to have the
official blessing of local Communist authorities.
   At the open-air rally in the southern industrial city,
opposition leaders and local Communist Party officials addressed
the crowd from a podium equipped with loudspeakers, ADN said.
   Hans Modrow, the local party chief long believed to be a strong
supporter of reform, told the crowd a process had begun that would
lead to ``revolutionary change,'' ADN said.
   East Berlin's mayor, Erhard Krack, on Thursday invited
``citizens interested in dialogue'' to a discussion at City Hall
and at the capital city's convention center on Sunday, ADN said.
   East Germany's Federation of Lawyers called on the government to
allow multi-candidate elections and demanded reform of the nation's
legal system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891027-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0836EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Major     10-27 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Major,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Chancellor of Exchequer a Thatcher Loyalist</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Politics, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Major, who went from welfare recipient to
economic overlord, is a trapeze artist's son whose own climb to
lofty heights has been nothing short of meteoric.
   The former foreign secretary was chosen by Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher on Thursday to become chancellor of the
exchequer, replacing Nigel Lawson in the top treasury post.
   Rising from humble origins, the 46-year-old Major is regarded as
a prime example of the ambitious and successful Tories who have
thrived during the Thatcher decade.
   Major is widely regarded as an orthodox monetarist and a
Thatcher loyalist. Political analysts said his appointment likely
won't mark significant changes in British economic policy.
   Major quickly issued a statement in which he vowed to continue
the government's fight against inflation and maintain a tight
monetary stance.
   The appointment came just three months after Major was pushed
into the limelight and made foreign secretary. He had been chief
secretary to the Treasury.
   His appointment as foreign secretary in July, replacing Sir
Geoffrey Howe, was part of one of Mrs. Thatcher's boldest political
strokes. Howe now serves as deputy prime minister.
   But as one of Mrs. Thatcher's current favorites, Major has been
satirized by opposition Labor Party members as her ``poodle.''
   When Major was a child, his father, a circus stuntman who
performed on both tightrope and trapeze, was declared bankrupt.
   Major was brought up in a couple of rooms in Brixton, a tough
south London neighborhood.
   In his teens, he was a soapbox Tory, and after high school, he
joined an accounting firm as a trainee.
   He left to become a construction laborer because, he said,
``there was more money in it.''
   Major is the only Cabinet member to have been on ``the dole,''
or welfare, for eight months.
   He did volunteer work in Nigeria during the civil war there and
survived a car crash over a cliff with only a smashed leg.
   In the hospital, he decided to go into politics.
   ``I came to the conclusion that I wanted to be inside the
goldfish bowl, rather than outside longingly looking in,'' Major
has said.
   Before making his bid for the House of Commons, however, he
established a career at the Standard Chartered Bank.
   He won a seat in Parliament in 1979, and his rise since has been
one of the fastest in recent political history.
   His manner is gentle and conscientious, and he has a reputation
for quickly grasping figures and detail.
   Major's wife Norma has written a biography of opera singer Joan
Sutherland. The Majors have a son and a daughter.
   The family lives in Huntingdon, 59 miles north of London, but
likely will move to 11 Downing St., next door to the prime
minister's residence, where the chancellor traditionally resides.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891027-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0841EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChineseOfficers     10-27 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chinese Officers,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Military Officers Ordered Off Joint Arms Project Back to
Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese military officers ordered off a joint
arms project with the United States after the Beijing crackdown on
pro-democracy protesters were allowed back to work this month, a
newspaper reported today.
   The 42 officers are assigned to Project Peace Pearl, a $500
million program to upgrade Chinese F-8 fighter planes, with China
expected to ultimately buy enhanced aviation electronic technology.
   They were taken off the project at Grumman Corp. in Bethpage,
N.Y., and Wright-Patterson Air Force Base near Dayton, Ohio, when
President Bush banned high-level contacts with China after the
Chinese army attacked demonstrators in June, killing hundreds and
perhaps thousands in Beijing.
   But early this month the Bush administration quietly lifted the
suspension, the Los Angeles Times reported in today's editions.
Seven of the Chinese officers who stayed in the United States
returned to work Oct. 2, and 18 returned from China to begin work
this week.
   ``It was determined by the U.S. government that they are
needed,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Edward Lundquist, a Pentagon spokesman.
``You can assume that the decision was fully coordinated by the
Defense Department, the State Department, the White House and
National Security Council.''
   Project Peace Pearl, which will sell advanced avionics equipment
to the Chinese for the F-8s, is still in the development stage. The
scheduled shipment to China of $500 million in equipment is not due
until 1992, but it is undetermined if the sale will go through.
   In June, Bush announced a $600 million freeze against China
would include the avionics sale, and another $100 million shipment
of military equipment.
   On June 5, immediately after Bush proposed the freeze, Grumman
officials told the 40 Chinese nationals not to return to work, but
kept 250 Americans assigned to the project on the job, said Mariam
Reid, a Grumman spokeswoman.
   Two Chinese military officers working on the project at
Wright-Patterson were not kicked off the base, but told to stay
away from the project office.
   The Air Force oversees the project, which will continue despite
uncertainty about the sale, Lundquist said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
