<FIRST>r a BC-Theater 2ndLd-Writethru a0526 10-27 0722</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0526,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>`The Secret Rapture,' A Play by David Hare, Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `In London...', to DELETE incorrect reference
to play appearing in London's West End. No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Isobel and Marion are sisters. Isobel believes
in doing the right thing. Marion believes in doing what she thinks
is right.
   Their differences are the foundation of ``The Secret Rapture,''
David Hare's fascinating drama about public and private greed that
opened Thursday at Broadway's Ethel Barrymore Theatre. It's
impressive theater, directed by the playwright himself in a spare,
no-nonsense style.
   What Hare, the author of ``Plenty,'' ``A Map of the World'' and
``Pravda,'' has written is a striking morality play in which the
line between good and evil is fudged, distorted by those domestic
entanglements called ``family.''
   The two sisters are brought together at their father's funeral.
Not only must they come to terms with his death, they must deal
with their young, alcoholic stepmother, Katherine.
   In London, where the play enjoyed a great success at the
National Theatre, ``The Secret Rapture'' was taken by many critics
to be an indictment of Margaret Thatcher's England.
   Marion is a junior minister in the Conservative government. Her
husband, Tom, is president of Christians in Business. ``We try to
do business the way Jesus would have done it,'' he says. Husband
and wife have sanctified success, in business and in politics.
   But the play is more than a political tract, primarily because
of Hare's treatment of Isobel. The woman, who runs a graphic design
business, is a restless, romantic heroine, a do-gooder with doubts.
She hires her stepmother against the advice of Irwin, her boyfriend
and employee. And then she reluctantly agrees to have her company
purchased by Tom's conglomerate, only to learn that Irwin already
has defected to her brother-in-law.
   These decisions have disastrous consequences, both
professionally and personally, for Isobel. She willingly enters
into the agreements; she's not a pushover, coerced into action. But
what makes Isobel different from the other characters is that she
has qualms about what she does.
   Marion has another side, too. She's ruthless and self-pitying
but you can sympathize with her feelings when she complains that
Isobel makes her feel as if she's always wrong. ``We can't all be
perfect,'' Marion snaps. ``We do try.''
   Hare's dialogue is literate, witty and, at times, moving. There
is a sadness around the edges of the play that never really comes
to the forefront until the final curtain. By then, it's devastating.
   Designer Santo Loquasto captures this melancholy in his striking
sets, particularly a red autumnal backdrop, lighted by Richard
Nelson.
   Hare has written three smashing roles for women, and his
challenge is ably met in this production. In the central role of
Isobel, Blair Brown radiates a goodness that is believable, a
goodness rooted more in honesty than in saintliness.
   Frances Conroy, her hair swirled tightly around her head, looks
like a cross between Mrs. Thatcher and Princess Anne. Her wonderful
portrait of the ambitious Marion is cold, astringent and deadly
accurate. And Mary Beth Hurt excels as the devious, acid-tongued
Katherine, who wants sympathy but rarely offers any of her own.
   There is strong support in secondary roles from Stephen Vinovich
as Tom, the smug Christian businessman who's building a swimming
pool in his back yard to baptize converts, Michael Wincott as
Isobel's distraught boyfriend and Jennifer Van Dyck as Marion's
predatory assistant.
   After a swift burst of violence, ``The Secret Rapture'' ends
enigmatically with one of the sisters left alone on stage. It
amounts to a reconciliation of sorts, although the playwright never
settles who was right and who was wrong. But then, that's real
life, and maybe one of the reasons ``The Secret Rapture'' is such a
rich and satisfying play.
   The play opened to mostly unfavorable reviews, with critics
lamenting a loss between the British and U.S. productions. The New
York Post said what in London was poetic, on Broadway is
``obscurantist, pretentious, and annoying.''
   New York Newsday called it a ``flawed'' but ``fascinating''
drama, while the Daily News said the play was ``too calculated, too
schematic.'' The New York Times said, ``The passion and wit that
reside in his (Hare's) script ... are left unrealized in this
production.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
