<FIRST>u i PM-Kenya-Murder     10-27 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kenya-Murder,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules That British Tourist Was Murdered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court ruled today that a British tourist
who died last year in a game reserve was murdered, rejecting the
government's contention that she was devoured by animals.
   ``I think the animals are innocent,'' said Chief Magistrate
Joseph Mango, ruling in the case of 28-year-old Julie Ward.
   Ms. Ward's partly charred lower left leg and lower jaw were
found Sept. 13, 1988, in the sprawling Masai Mara Game Reserve, a
week after she reportedly left the park.
   Her partly burned personal belongings and ashes also were found
near the remains, 5 miles from her abandoned vehicle.
   ``There is ample and substantial evidence that Julie Ward died
of foul play by a person or persons unknown,'' Mango concluded.
   But he said he ``saw no reason'' to direct the attorney
general's office to further investigate her death and rejected
claims by Ms. Ward's family that the state engaged in a massive
coverup either to protect her assassin or Kenya's lucrative tourist
industry.
   ``There has been a strong attack on the quality of the
investigations ... And allegations of a coverup,'' said Mango. ``Of
course the state does not admit this.''
   He further denied that Simon Makallah, the Masai Mara's chief
game warden, is a principle suspect in Ms. Ward's slaying.
   Ms. Ward's father, John Ward, and his attorney, Byron
Georgiadis, pointed to Makallah as a suspect. They allege she was
killed by someone who knew the game park well, who had freedom of
movement there and who could have ordered or inspired a coverup of
the circumstances surrounding her disappeareance.
   Makallah found Ms. Ward's remains within hours after her vehicle
was located. Georgiadis alleged he was able to do that only because
he already knew where they were.
   Mango said, however, there was no evidence to suggest Makallah
and Ms. Ward ever met before her death and that he found her
remains ``does not cast suspicion on Makallah.''
   Instead, he said investigators should consider as prime suspects
two men Ms. Ward spent time with in the game park, neither of whom
appeared as witnesses during the inquest.
   The ruling ended an inquiry that began in mid-August and ran
intermittently until Oct. 6.
   The inquest largely was the result of pressure from Ms. Ward's
father who has spent tens of thousands of dollars and hundreds of
hours trying to prove his daughter was murdered.
   Ward, a wealthy hotelier from Suffolk, England, said:``It is a
credit to Kenya that they came up with this verdict.'' Ward
maintained, however, there was a coverup.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
