<FIRST>r i PM-Havel     10-27 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Havel,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Playwright Havel Reported Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident playwright Vaclav Havel
was hospitalized after being forced from his sick bed by police and
taken to a police station, a friend said today.
   Vladimir Hanzel said police entered Havel's apartment in Prague
on Thursday evening as he lay in bed suffering from a high
temperature and forced him to accompany them to a police station.
   Havel, 53, insisted that an ambulance be called and he was taken
to the Na Frantisku hospital in central Prague, where doctors
decided he required hospitalization for a bronchial illness, Hanzel
said.
   Havel has suffered from the lung complaint since serving a jail
sentence from 1979 to early 1983.
   Hospital sources who asked not to be identified said Havel was
suffering from a bronchial inflammation and had a temperature of
99.7.
   Eva Kanturkova, another outlawed writer who like Havel was among
the first to sign the Charter 77 human rights document 12 years
ago, also was detained Thursday by police, fellow dissident Vaclav
Benda said.
   It was not known if any more activists were arrested.
   Security forces routinely detain prominent dissidents in advance
of banned demonstrations. Such a protest is scheduled Saturday to
mark the 71st anniversary of the founding of Czechoslovakia.
   Last year, about 5,000 people gathered to mark the anniversary
and were dispersed by riot police using batons, tear gas, dogs and
water cannons. At least 87 people were arrested.
   The authorities have said anybody defying the ban on this year's
demonstration faces prosecution. They scheduled a military ceremony
on the same square a few hours before Saturday's planned protest.
</TEXT>
