<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Sex     10-27 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Sex,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Postal Inspectors Probing Pornographic Mailings to Congress Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Postal inspectors are investigating the use of
apparently stolen congressional envelopes in which pornographic
materials were mailed to House and Senate members at taxpayer
expense, according to published reports.
   Former Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., whose official signature was
imprinted on the envelopes, said he also has asked the Justice
Department to investigate, according to Roll Call, a newspaper
about happenings in Congress.
   The Washington Times today quoted Robert Rota, the House
postmaster, as saying the envelopes apparently were stolen.
   Enclosed in the envelopes which began arriving in congressional
offices on Tuesday were green, dollar-sized coupons imprinted with
obscenities and offering bearers a $1 discount on sexual acts.
   ``Describe them?'' the Times quoted Coelho as saying. ``It's too
gross for that.''
   One of the letters ended up in the hands of Coelho's wife,
Phyllis, a secretary for Rep. Andy Jacobs, D-Ind. ``I got really
angry,'' she said.
   The Times said most of the envelopes addressed to senators were
confiscated Thursday by Senate Postmaster Gayle Cory, who had been
alerted that they might be arriving.
   Coelho resigned from the House in June rather than face a
prolonged investigation into his investments.
</TEXT>
