<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0936EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland     10-27 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mazowiecki Tells Warsaw Pact to Focus on Less Guns, More Butter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki told
Warsaw Pact diplomats today that they should put less emphasis on
their alliance's military role and improve economic ties to reflect
the great changes in the East bloc.
   Mazowiecki, the first non-Communist leader of a Soviet bloc
nation, also sought to assure his Communist allies that the
democratic changes taking place in Poland posed no danger to their
alliance.
   Mazowiecki made the comments during a toast at a dinner for
foreign ministers and foreign trade ministers attending a two-day
Warsaw Pact meeting in the capital.
   He called for ``radically'' restructuring Comecon, the
organization that coordinates economic relations among the seven
pact countries, and stressed the need to respect the internal
sovereignty of pact nations.
   ``These principles take on particular significance at the
present time of changes going on in many of our countries,'' he
said, apparently referring to reforms in Hungary and the Soviet
Union and the beginnings of reform in East Germany.
   The gathering is the first Warsaw Pact meeting to be held in
Poland since Solidarity took control of the government in August.
Other members of the Warsaw Pact are Bulgaria, Romania and
Czechoslovakia.
   ``Our reforms pose no threat to anybody and violate nobody's
interests,'' he said. ``On the contrary, the changes that are going
on in Poland now lead to normalizing the internal situation, and
thus indirectly to stability of European relations.
   ``Poland is true to her commitments as an ally and fulfills her
duties stemming from this.''
   Poland wants to expand and improve political and defense
cooperation in the Warsaw Pact, as well as economic, scientific and
technical cooperation in Comecon, Mazowiecki said.
   But at the same time, Europe should be less divided, he said.
   ``A return to the unity of Europe means not only the common
heritage of culture and civilization, but also the need for joint
development of conditions of detente and peace,'' Mazowiecki said.
   Urging changes within the pact itself, he said, ``The Warsaw
Treaty cannot lag behind the current of transformations. We must
not lose sight of the vision of a world free from opposed military
blocs.''
   He said that system should be replaced by ``by an efficient
system of collective security _ a vision that was outlined in the
U.N. Charter'' in 1945.
   ``Today it is important to put emphasis on the political instead
of the military roles of the treaties.''
   Giving the answering toast was Foreign Minister Ioan Totu of
Romania, a country whose leaders tried unsuccessfully to rally
Warsaw Pact nations in August to prevent Solidarity's government
takeover.
   Totu stressed the need for ``non-interference in the internal
affairs of other countries.''
   Apparently referring to repeated Western calls for human rights
improvements in some East bloc countries, particularly Romania, he
said: ``Imperialist, reactionary circles resort to actions and
attempts at interference in the affairs of socialist states and
their destabilization.
   ``It is necessary to reject actions of this kind as flagrantly
discordant'' with the 1975 Helsinki Accords and the U.N. Charter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
