<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0938EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China     10-27 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paper Accuses Zhao Aide Of Blocking Deng's Books</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading newspaper said today that a top adviser
to ousted Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang blocked publication of
a collection of speeches and sayings by senior leader Deng Xiaoping.
   The collection, ``Deng Xiaoping on Literature and the Arts,''
was issued Thursday at a ceremony at the Great Hall of the People
and acclaimed by the new culture minister, He Jingzi, as a ``great
event in cultural and publishing circles.''
   A top party official, Li Ruihuan, said the books would be of
great help in eradicating the influence of Western liberal ideas,
and he urged artists and writers to study them to ``unify
thinking.''
   In a front-page editorial, the Guangming Daily said the
collection was put together two years ago.
   ``Because of obstruction from Bao Tong, who grasped some power
then, it could not be published then,'' it said.
   Bao was a key adviser to Zhao and director of the party's
Research Center for the Reform of the Political Structure. He is
believed to be under arrest.
   If Deng had personally wanted the collection to be published
earlier, it is highly unlikely Bao would have been able to stop it.
   Zhao was ousted from his party posts in June after losing a
power struggle triggered by student pro-democracy protests. Other
party officials accused him of supporting the protests and
splitting the party. He has not been seen in public since.
   The publication of the collection is part of an effort since the
protests to lionize Deng as a wise leader on a par with
revolutionary leader Mao Tse-tung.
   The collection's title echoes that of a famous 1942 speech by
Mao, ``On Literature and the Arts,'' which codified party policy
that the arts must serve socialism.
   The Guangming Daily said, ``Deng Xiaoping's important
composition on literature and the arts is the guiding principle to
prosper and develop socialist literature and the arts.''
   It said the writings criticized extreme individualism, nihilism,
anarchism, abstract humanitarianism, theories of alienation under
socialism, money-worship, pornography and ``all kinds of corrupted
thought and capitalist lifestyles.''
   Under former Culture Minister Wang Meng, a writer who lost his
post in September, the government had stressed the need for
artistic freedom.
   In contrast, a recent People's Daily editorial said Chinese
literature in recent years has become ``wilder than ever before''
as writers imitate ``Western bourgeois literary phenomena such as
black humor, symbolism, expressionism, surrealism, the fantasy
school, stream of consciousness, imagism and so on.''
   It said writers have a lofty mission to write about socialist
realities and the ``beauty of human nature.''
</TEXT>
