<FIRST>r a PM-PreschoolMolest     10-27 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Preschool Molest,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Ends Closing Arguments in McMartin Pre-School Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for two people whose trial on child
molestation charges is the longest in U.S. history has finally
completed his case, pleading with the jury not to believe the
sexually graphic testimony of youngsters.
   ``You can still love children and still want to believe them,
but in a courtroom you can't rely on them,'' attorney Danny Davis
said Thursday as he finished his closing argument.
   Davis represents Raymond Buckey, 30, and his mother, Peggy
McMartin Buckey, 62. Both are charged with 65 counts of molestation
and conspiracy involving 11 children at the now-defunct McMartin
Pre-School in Manhattan Beach.
   The first arrests in the case came six years ago. The trial of
Buckey and his mother has lasted about 2{ years, the longest trial
in U.S. history. Charges against five others eventually were
dismissed.
   Nine children testified about alleged sexual abuse. Davis called
them ``lovely, rehearsed children'' who were led to believe they
were molested when nothing really happened.
   Davis said the children memorized their testimony after
interviews by therapists and coaching by prosecutors.
   He also questioned the testimony of George Freeman, an admitted
perjurer and jailhouse informant who said Buckey confessed to child
molestations while the two shared a cell.
   ``You should not reward people who bring in perjurers and shaped
children,'' Davis said. ``Did Ray Buckey have to prove his
innocence because the evidence the (prosecutors) looked for to
prove otherwise was not there? He's entitled to the benefit of the
doubt.''
   Superior Court Judge William Pounders imposed a limit of 6{ days
for each side to give closing arguments to expedite the case and
reduce the possibility of a mistrial.
   The defense took all its time for closing arguments after three
days of closing statements from the prosecution. Prosecutors saved
3{ days and will now use the time to rebut Davis.
</TEXT>
