<FIRST>u i PM-Taiwan-Crash 1stLd-Writethru a0490 10-27 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan-Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0490,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescuers Find 31 Bodies in China Airlines Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with search being suspended for
the night, new quote from official on dim hope of finding survivors; picks
up 6th graf, `The so-called ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers located 31 badly burned bodies
amid the wreckage of a China Airlines jet today, a day after the
plane crashed in a remote valley with 54 people on board, officials
and news reports said.
   An air and land search for survivors was suspended tonight
because of darkness, and officials said the search would resume
Saturday. A Los Angeles man was believed to have been the only
foreigner aboard.
   ``The plane was broken into many pieces. It is hard to imagine
anyone could have survived,' said Communications Minister Clement
Chang, who toured the crash site by helicopter.
   The Boeing 737-200, belonging to Taiwan's national flag carrier,
slammed into a mountain and burst into flames five minutes after
taking off Thursday from Hualien, a popular tourist resort on the
island's east coast.
   The jet was en route from Hualien to Taipei, about 90 miles
northeast.
   The official Broadcasting Corporation of China said rescuers
found 31 bodies strewn in deep grass in the highlands valley and
began the arduous task of carrying them on the three-hour walk down
the mountain to Hualien. Rescuers also found limbs and other body
parts, the radio said.
   The so-called ``black box,'' which records cockpit conversations
between the pilot and control tower, was recovered from the crash
site, the radio report said.
   China Airlines spokeman Lodge Lo said the company was looking
into any possible ``mechanical or crew'' error that might have
caused the crash of the 3-year-old plane.
   Hualien control tower officials said they instructed the plane
to turn east and fly over the sea after takeoff, but it turned west
toward land. No explanation was given.
   President Lee Teng-hui and Premier Lee Huan both ordered an
investigation into the crash.
   The radio broadcast quoted rescuers as saying they located a
wing and other fragments of the plane, indicating the aircraft
exploded after it crashed. Bits of the plane were strewn over 75
yards, it said.
   ``Small fragments were everywhere. There was hardly a large
chunk in the wreckage,'' rescuer Wang Teh was quoted as saying.
   Television footage showed weeping relatives crowding a Hualien
police station. Monks read Buddhist scriptures, believed to help
the dead in the afterlife, airline officials said.
   A radio report from the crash site said most bodies were burned
beyond recognition. Rescuers were able immediately to identify only
the body of J. Wayne Phillips, 46, vice president of the Universal
Paint Corp. of Los Angeles.
   The airline said Phillips was the only foreigner on the flight.
A Paint Corp. secretary said Phillips was in Taiwan on business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
