<DOCNO> AP891027-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1017EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Gorbachev     10-27 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Visits Northern Finland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OULU, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finns cheered and applauded today as Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev arrived in this city near the Arctic
Circle to see technological marvels that could help his country's
failing economy.
   At least 5,000 people gathered outside City Hall and hundreds
lined the road from the airport waving Soviet and Finnish flags to
greet Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, after they flew in from
Helsinki, 400 miles away.
   The couple waded into the crowd to shake hands as residents
applauded and cheered.
   ``What a lot of people!'' Mrs. Gorbachev exclaimed.
   School was closed for the day in Oulu, a Baltic Sea city of
100,000 people 140 miles south of the Arctic Circle.
   ``This is such a little town no one ever comes,'' Johanna
Harkonen, 16, told reporters.
   The Gorbachevs, on the last day of a three-day trip to Finland,
headed for the University of Oulu, which features a modern computer
center and an electron optics department; and for Oulu Technology
Park, where companies research electronics and communications.
   Before leaving Helsinki, Gorbachev, who presides over sessions
of the Supreme Soviet legislature in Moscow, tried out the gavel
and electronic voting system at the Finnish Parliament.
   In a speech Thursday, the Soviet leader recognized Finland's
neutrality and announced plans to cut Moscow's nuclear forces in
the Baltic Sea.
   The Kremlin chief also said the Soviet Union has removed all
tactical nuclear missiles that could strike the Baltic region and
would take certain types of sea-launched nuclear weapons out of the
Baltic Sea.
</TEXT>
