<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Miners     10-27 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Miners,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ukrainian Miners to Meet Next Week for Strike Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ukrainian miners will meet next week to decide
whether to go on strike to protest what they say is the
government's failure to abide by promises made during strikes last
summer, a representative said today.
   The Ukraine's Donetsk basin, the Soviet Union's largest
coal-producing area, and other coal regions were paralyzed by the
summer strikes. Miners went back to work after the Kremlin promised
to meet virtually all their demands for better working conditions,
improved supplies of consumer goods and more financial independence.
   But Ukrainian miners' representatives say those promises have
not been kept. They voted Thursday against immediately resuming the
giant strike but decided to poll workers to see how much support
there was for renewing it.
   Alexander Nikolaevich Tupikin, a member of the Donetsk strike
committee, said by telephone that the decisions of all individual
mines and work shifts should be known by Tuesday.
   On that day, a council representing workers from throughout the
region will meet, ``sum up all the opinions and decide what the
next step should be,'' he said.
   Soviet officials have said a renewed round of miners' strikes
could force a rationing of heat and light as the winter sets in
because of a reduction of coal.
   Earlier this month, the Supreme Soviet legislature passed a law
banning strikes in such vital areas as energy, defense and
transport.
   The law didn't stop 18,000 miners in the northern region of
Vorkuta from holding a one-day strike Thursday to demand the
Kremlin make good on the promised benefits, as well as end the
Communist Party's monopoly on power.
   The strikers decided to return to work at all but one mine after
hearings on the illegal strike began in regional court, Vorkuta
strike committee member Sergei Masolovich said by telephone.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev said Thursday ``strong
administrative measures through the prosecutor and the court''
might be taken to discourage wildcat strikes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
