<SECOND>PM-South Africa Missiles, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0559,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Africa, Israel Cooperate on Missile Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts new 10th graf, Prime Minister, with Shamir comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa and Israel are cooperating on
several programs to develop ballistic missiles, including one with
nuclear weapon potential, a U.S. official says.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
intelligence reports indicated that South Africa last summer tested
a modified version of the Israeli-made Jericho II medium-range
missile at Armaston on the Indian Ocean coast near Capetown.
   Israel test-fired its own Jericho II missile over the
Mediterranean last year, he said. Both missiles have a 900-mile
range.
   The two countries, which have had an extensive defense
relationship since the 1960s, also are cooperating in the
development of a long-range missile that could be used to launch
reconnaissance satellites into space, the official said.
   A long-range version of the Jericho _ known as the Shavit, which
is Hebrew for comet _ was used to launch an Israeli
photo-reconnaissance satellite earlier this year from the Negev
Desert, the official said. Media reports then described the rocket
as a multistage missile having a 2,000-mile range.
   Responding to reports about the nuclear cooperation, the State
Department urged Israel to sign the international Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty, which it has refused to do for fear of
opening its facilities to international inspection.
   ``We have repeatedly urged Israel and other non-signatories'' to
join the pact, the department said in statement issued late
Thursday. ``We reiterate that call.''
   Both Israel and South Africa have denied they are sharing such
technology.
   ``I bear no knowledge whatsoever of such cooperation,'' said
South African Foreign Minister Pik Botha.
   In Jerusalem today, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said the
reports of Israeli-South African nuclear cooperation were designed
to ``tear the fabric'' of U.S.-Israeli relations at a time when
Israel was trying to bridge differences with Secretary of State
James A. Baker III about peace talks with Palestinians.
   Under intense U.S. pressure, Israel announced in 1987 that it
would not sign any new defense contracts with South Africa but
would honor existing ones.
   The State Department and the Pentagon refused to discuss the
matter.
   ``We do not comment on intelligence matters. The U.S. policy of
opposition to the proliferation of missiles and nuclear weapons is
well known,'' said State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler.
   Ms. Tutwiler said the U.S. ambassador in Israel had brought up
similar reports of nuclear proliferation with Israel in the past.
Israel turned down the protest of former ambassador Thomas
Pickering, The Washington Post reported in today's editions.
   And when a senior State Department official brought up the issue
with a visiting Israeli delegation last spring, ``he was stiffed,
just absolutely stiffed on it,'' the Post quoted an unidentified
source as saying.
   Israel and South Africa reportedly also are cooperating on
development of a South African jet fighter known as the Cheetah. It
is a modified version of the Israeli Lavi fighter that was scrapped
under strong U.S. pressure in the final stages of its development
two years ago.
   The assistant secretary of state for African affairs, Herman
Cohen, indirectly confirmed recently that there had been some
cooperation between the two countries on intermediate-range
missiles.
   Israel has pledged to phase out its defense ties with South
Africa, Cohen said in a television interview, but added, ``I am
assuming cooperation of intermediate range ballistic missiles comes
under existing contracts.''
   NBC-TV reported that South Africa was providing Israel with
enriched uranium for its own nuclear warheads. Neither country has
admitted having nuclear weapons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
