<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     10-27 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Blocks Bishops From Delivering Food</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army blocked three
Christian bishops from delivering truckloads of food today to a
Christian Arab town closed by military order because of its boycott
of Israeli taxes.
   The bishops and two other high-ranking religious leaders also
abandoned plans to visit the town of Beit Sahour _ minus the food
trucks _ when army officers insisted a military escort had to
accompany them.
   Beit Sahour, near Bethlehem, has been the scene of a major
confrontation between Israeli authorities and residents boycotting
Israeli taxes as part of the 22-month uprising against the
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The town, with a mostly Christian population of 10,000, has been
closed to outsiders much of the time since Sept. 20, when the
government began confiscating property in raids aimed at breaking
the tax boycott.
   The religious leaders included the Jerusalem patriarchs, or
bishops, of the Roman Catholic, Greek Orthodox and Armenian
churches. Accompanying them were representatives of the Greek
Catholic sect and the Franciscan religious order.
   The churchmen had hoped to pray in Beit Sahour and meet with the
mayor, said Roman Catholic Patriarch Michel Sabbah.
   ``They (the soldiers) did not let us do our humanitarian
duties,'' Sabbah complained.
   Greek Orthodox Patriarch Diodoros I called the incident ``an
insult to our ranks and our rights through the ages'' to worship in
the Holy Land, the spokesman for the group said.
   An Army spokesman said the three trucks of sugar, rice, flour
and cooking oil were blocked because the town is a ``closed
military area'' where non-residents cannot enter. While the town is
believed to have some shortages, there is no threat of starvation.
   Army officials also said officers felt the religious leaders and
their aides, totaling about 20 people, could provoke an incident in
Beit Sahour.
   The three bishops rejected an army offer to allow them to enter
the Christian town with a military escort for their own safety.
   ``(The bishops) said `God will protect us.' But the commander of
the area responsible for their safety felt it would be unwise,''
said the army spokesman, who is not identified under military
regulations.
   When told they would not be allowed into the town, the religious
leaders went to the Church of Nativity in Bethlehem and prayed for
Beit Sahour. The church bells were rung to show solidarity with the
nearby town.
   The prayers at the church that is regarded by tradition as the
birthplace of Christ represented a rare show of unity since
Christian sects often squabble over their rights to the church and
other religious sites.
   Meanwhile, police said they were investigating the fatal
shooting Thursday of an 18-year-old Bethlehem youth, Naeem Karim
Daamseh.
   Daamseh was shot in the neck by a policeman after he ignored a
police order to stop, struck a policeman with his car and was
pursued by a police van, police officials said.
   Police spokesman Mordechai Bareket denied a Palestinian witness'
charge that police pistol whipped Daamseh and shot him at close
range.
   Israelis have killed 605 Palestinians since the uprising began
in December 1987. Fellow Arabs have slain an additional 136
Palestinians, most on suspicion of collaborating with Israel. Forty
Israelis also have died.
</TEXT>
