<SECOND>PM-South Korea,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Students Burn U.S. Flags, Battle Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students burning U.S. flags,
carrying a mock coffin of the South Korean president and hurling
firebombs battled riot police today in Seoul.
   One group of 300 students hurled rocks and firebombs at police
after a campus rally in front of Seoul National University. Police
fired tear gas and dispersed the protesters in 90 minutes.
   The other group, consisting of 700 students from a rival group,
held a campus rally at Korea University almost simultaneously to
launch what they called a stepped-up anti-government and anti-U.S.
campaign.
   No arrests or injuries were reported in the protests.
   The protest at Korea University turned violent as students tried
to march off campus. The students fought police near the school's
main gate, throwing rocks and firebombs. About 500 police hurled
tear gas back over the school gate, which was locked by school
authorities.
   ``Down with Roh Tae-woo!'' and ``Yankee go home!'' the students
shouted.
   The students brought a mock coffin of President Roh Taw-woo and
two large U.S. flags to the gate and torched them. They cheered as
thick smoke rose into the sky.
   The students shouted slogans accusing the Roh government of
suppression and demanded the release of a radical student arrested
for making an illegal trip to communist North Korea in July.
   ``Release Im Su-kyong, flower of unification!'' they shouted,
raising clenched fists into the sky.
   Ms. Im was charged with violating the country's tough national
security law by making an unauthorized trip to the North to attend
a world youth festival there. She was arrested after returning home
in August.
   South Koreans are barred from visiting North Korea, an enemy
country, without government permission.
   South and North Korea have been bitter enemies since their
peninsula was divided in 1945. They fought the Korean War in
1950-53.
   Radicals say the 43,000 U.S. troops stationed in South Korea
hamper reunification of the peninsula. They are a small but vocal
minority on college campuses.
</TEXT>
