<FIRST>u i PM-UN-Refugees     10-27 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Refugees,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hocke Says Resignation Was His Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. official who resigned amid allegations of
financial impropriety denied any wrongdoing today and said he
stepped down because repeated attacks had made his job increasingly
difficult.
   ``It is quite clear that the function of the high commissioner
requires a total commitment and availability to act, to convince
and to galvanize,'' said Jean-Pierre Hocke, who resigned Thursday
as U.N. high commissioner for refugees.
   Such commitment had been ``reduced by repeated and irresponsible
attacks,'' he said. ``These were the considerations that led to my
resignation which should not be seen as a withdrawal in the middle
of the storm.''
   Hocke's resignation was announced in New York after U.N.
Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar ordered a broadened
inquiry into allegations that Hocke misused agency funds to
subsidize first-class air travel.
   Calling a news conference only hours after his return from New
York, Hocke read a handwritten statement saying his resignation
does ``not reflect any sentiment of culpability on my part
concerning any of my doings.''
   He said the agency would face a ``formidable challenge in the
next few months when refugee protection and assistance will be more
difficult than ever.''
   Such tasks, he said, could be tackled only with an open mind
which he said he may no longer have because of the ``destructive
intentions of some people here and elsewhere.'' He did not
elaborate.
   Switching between French and English in answering questions, he
said he did ``not feel to have been pressured.''
   The high commissioner is responsible for at least 12 million
refugees worldwide, although there are many more than that. A
separate U.N. agency helps Palestinian refugees.
   Hocke's latest problems began in September, when Swiss
Television reported that internal documents showed he had drawn
$300,000 since 1987 from a special ``educational fund'' set up by
Sweden and Denmark to fly first class instead of business class.
   Hocke admitted he had flown first class, a right reserved only
for Perez de Cuellar under stringent U.N. austerity measures, but
denied any impropriety.
</TEXT>
