<SECOND>PM-Colombia, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0561,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Kills Five Policemen On Bus</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with bomb deactivated, shooting
in Medellin; picks up 3rd pvs, `No one...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded on a street in Medellin
as a bus carrying policemen passed by, killing five officers and
wounding 16, police said.
   Three more bombs exploded Thursday night and early today in the
capital of Bogota, wounding one person, and another bomb in Bogota
was deactivated Thursday night at a bank, police said.
   Also Thursday, two policemen assigned as guards to the
Ecuadorian consulate in Medellin were shot and killed as they tried
to help another policeman make an arrest, police in the city said.
They blamed street thugs and said the killers escaped.
   No one claimed responsibility for the bus attack late Thursday,
but police blamed drug barons angered by the government's refusal
to negotiate its policy of extraditing traffickers to the United
States.
   ``The traffickers are the only criminals with the means and the
desire to carry out an attack of this size,'' said a police
spokesman in Medellin, the center of Colombia's drug trade.
   In the two months since the government declared a war on
traffickers and the drug lords responded with violent attacks, 169
bombings attributed to the traffickers have killed 21 people and
injured 219.
   The latest attacks came a day after the country suffered its
worst rebel violence in two years, with guerrillas storming two
northeastern towns and slaying at least six people, according to
army reports.
   The bomb in Medellin, packing over 60 pounds of dynamite, was
placed on a curb and detonated as the bus passed. National RCN
radio said 44 officers were on the bus at the time.
   The driver and four others died in the explosion, which severely
damaged the bus and sent it reeling out of control, the police
spokesman said on condition of anonymity. Many of the 16 injured
were in critical condition, he said.
   The bus finally stopped when it smashed into a parked taxi, the
spokesman said. The right side of the bus was riddled with shrapnel
from the bomb, a Medellin police spokeswoman said.
   The bomb was connected with electrical cable to a plunger two
blocks away, the spokeswoman said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The vehicle was carrying police officers to their posts for
night duty. The attack stirred panic in Medellin's residential
neighborhood of Bello Horizonte.
   ``The terrorists fired automatic rifles as they fled, and people
panicked because they thought the neighborhood was under attack,''
a police spokesman said.
   In Bogota, police said three terrorists threw a bomb packing 10
pounds of dynamite at a telephone office from a passing car. One
person was injured in the blast, which broke the windows of houses
a block away.
   Hours later, unidentifed assailants in a taxi placed a 40-pound
bomb outside a bank in southern Bogota. The blast damaged the bank,
but caused no injuries.
   And shortly after midnight this morning a third bomb exploded at
another Bogota bank, a communique from the national police said.
   The attacks appeared to be in retaliation for the government's
extradition policy. The Supreme Court this week reaffirmed an
earlier ruling that extradition was constitutional, and President
Virgilio Barco pledged to continue.
   Barco has said the government will not negotiate with
traffickers, who until the crackdown received relative impunity by
intimidating or paying off judges.
   The government has extradited four drug suspects since it began
a crackdown against the traffickers Aug. 19, a day after drug lords
assassinated leading presidential candidate Luis Carlos Galan. Nine
alleged traffickers are awaiting extradition.
   Colombia's so-called Medellin and Cali drug cartels are thought
responsible for supplying 80 percent of the cocaine sold in the
United States.
   The army blamed Wednesday's rebel violence on the National
Liberation Army, a shadowy pro-Cuban organization.
   The attacks were the bloodiest since 1987, when more than 50
people were killed during one month of fighting.
</TEXT>
