<FIRST>u w PM-SovietTrip 1stLd-Writethru a0478 10-27 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Trip, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0478,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Says Legislature Will Share Foreign Policy Power With Gorbachev</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 11 grafs new material from Primakov speech, picks
up with 5th graf pvs, bgng, Baker underscored ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading member of the Soviet parliament said
today new legislation is being drafted to limit the power of
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to send the Red Army into conflicts
in other countries.
   Referring to the 1979 invasion of Afghanistan, the new chairman
of the Supreme Soviet`s Council of Union, Yevgeny M. Primakov, said
``there can be no decision of that sort without the involvement''
of the legislative body.
   He said the invasion was executed by a small group of officials
without the participation of the Supreme Soviet. ``There can be no
repetition,'' Primakov said in answering questions after a speech
at the Brookings Institution, a private research facility.
   The chairman of the Council of Union, the legislative upper and
dominant house, is visiting Washington as head of a Soviet
delegation at the invitation of Sens. George Mitchell of Maine and
Bob Dole of Kansas, the Democratic and Republican leaders of the
Senate.
   ``All international activity will have to go through the Supreme
Soviet,'' Primakov said in his speech.
   He likened the legislation in prepartion to the U.S. War Powers
Act, which restricts American presidents in sending troops abroad _
while providing considerable leeway in the event of self-declared
emergencies.
   Earlier this week, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze acknowledged in a Moscow speech that the invasion was
a mistake. The last of some 100,000 Soviet troops, who fought
alongside the Afghan army of Marxist President Najibullah against
U.S.-armed rebels, left the country last February.
   Soviet weapons are still being provided to the Kabul government
while the United States has continued to back the rebels in a
regional dispute with Moscow that runs counter to a general
improvement in superpower relations.
   On another foreign policy issue, Primakov said East Germans,
like people everywhere, have the ``right of free choice'' in
shaping their government.
   However, he was skeptical of recent U.S. statements of support
for reunification with West Germany as unlikely to contribute to
``international stability.''
   The Soviet delegation met for 40 minutes Thursday with Secretary
of State James A. Baker III and other State Department officials.
The parliament is the first chosen in competitive elections in 70
years under new rules engineered by Gorbachev.
   Baker underscored U.S. interest in the ``institutionalization of
respect for human rights'' through enactment of new laws by the
Supreme Soviet, the State Department said in a statement after the
meeting.
   He stressed particular interest in a new Soviet emigration law
that could lead to a waiver of export restrictions under the
Jackson-Vanick amendment, the statement said.
   Mitchell also said the delegation had asked him about ``the
possibility of granting a temporary waiver'' of restrictions on
Soviet exports to the United States. The Soviet Union is barred
from receiving most-favored-nation trading status, and the lower
tariffs that come with it, because of its past restrictive
emigration policies.
   Primakov said the emigration law is being considered by the
Supreme Soviet, but that enactment could be delayed by ``other
pressing business.''
   Baker reaffirmed U.S. support for reconstruction of the Soviet
economy, ``and our readiness to provide technical advice'' as
Soviets try to introduce a more market-oriented economy as part of
its perestroika reforms.
   Primakov told Baker that the Soviets welcomed U.S. support and
were ``seeking to borrow from our experience'' in such areas as
taxation, inflation and antitrust.
   Separate meetings held on economic reform, the political
situation in Moscow and environmental and scientific issues.
   When the delegation appeared on the Senate floor, Mitchell spoke
of the common legislative problems that face both the Soviet
lawmakers and their U.S. counterparts.
   The visiting lawmakers arrived in the midst of Congress' annual
tussle over money bills, featuring hot debates on abortion, taxes,
the death penalty and aid to Poland and Hungary, two East-bloc
countries that are emerging from under Soviet domination.
   ``You will witness ... strong differences of opinion and
vigorous debate between our parties and among our members,'' Dole
said in a welcoming statement. ``It is glasnost, American style.''
   After two days of meetings in Washington, the group was to go to
Maine on Saturday where it was to visit Bangor, Portland, and the
L.L. Bean clothing store in Freeport.
   On Sunday, the delegation was to see tourist attractions in
Dodge City, Kan., and attend a town meeting. Next week will include
a tour of the world's largest grain elevator at Hutchinson, Kan., a
trip to a cattle and wheat farm in Haven, Kan., and visits to Los
Angeles, Pittsburgh and New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
