<FIRST>u i PM-Refugees     10-27 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugees,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans Leave Prague Embassy For West</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAIDHAUS, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 141 East German
refugees who had been holed up in Bonn's embassy in Prague arrived
in West Germany today, officials said.
   The refugees were taken in two double-decker buses to the West
German border accompanied by West Germany's ambassador, Herman
Huber. An additional 38 East Germans remained in the embassy and
were expected to leave for the West soon, embassy officials said.
   On Thursday, the East German Embassy issued papers to the
refugees allowing them to travel to a third country and formally
revoked their East German citizenship, the East German state news
agency ADN reported. They were given 24 hours to leave the country
and the exodus began at about 8:30 a.m. Thursday.
   Stripping them of their citizenship in Prague allowed the
refugees to travel straight to West Germany, without having to pass
through their communist homeland.
   On two previous occasions, several thousand East Germans in West
Germany's Prague embassy were allowed to leave but were taken by
train through East German territory so that they could be formally
expelled. However, this led to near riots by East Germans at home
wanting to join the exodus.
   About 15,000 East Germans have been allowed to leave after
seeking asylum in the West German embassies in Prague and Warsaw,
Poland.
   West German government sources said about 1,800 East Germans
remained in Warsaw and were awaiting similar arrangements to leave
for West Germany.
   An estimated 60,000 East Germans fleeing political repression in
their homeland have arrived in West Germany in the past six weeks
via Czechoslovakia, Poland and Hungary, which opened its borders to
East Germans on Sept. 10.
</TEXT>
