<FIRST>u a PM-CDC--Cancer 1stLd-Writethru a0497 10-27 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC--Cancer, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0497,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Puzzled at Pattern of Colorectal Cancer Death Rates</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Nationwide, the ...' to CORRECT 23.1 to per
100,000, sted percent. Picks up 4th graf: `The District ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death rate from colon and rectal cancer is
highest along an arc from Maine to Iowa, say government researchers
who are puzzled by the finding.
   The national Centers for Disease Control said Thursday the
highest mortality rates from colorectal cancer in 1986 occurred in
the Northeast and the eastern north-central states _ in virtually
every state from Maine, with a death rate of 25.8 per 100,000
people; south to Maryland, with 27.2; and across to Iowa, with 24.8.
   Nationwide, the death rate from colorectal cancer in 1986 was
23.1 per 100,000 people.
   The District of Columbia had the nation's highest mortality
rate, 32.1. Wyoming had the lowest rate at 16.2, the Atlanta-based
CDC reported.
   In the Northeast, only Connecticut, at 24.5, Delaware, at 23.8,
and Vermont, at 22.4, had colorectal cancer death rates below 25
per 100,000. Other high rates were recorded in New Hampshire, 26.1;
Massachusetts, 26.3; New York, 27.3; New Jersey, 27.1; Rhode
Island, 28.7; Pennsylvania, 26.6; Ohio, 26.4; Indiana, 25.9; and
Illinois, 25.6. No other state exceeded 24.
   ``We don't know enough about the risk factors or their
distribution to say why that region is one with the highest
rates,'' said Dr. Robert A. Hahn, a CDC cancer specialist. ``We
doubt it's just a matter of physical environment, but we just don't
know.''
   Although few risk factors for colorectal cancer have been firmly
established, the CDC said, evidence points to high-fat diets as
risky and suggests that eating fruits and vegetables may help
protect against the disease.
   Obesity and a high-calorie diet also may increase the risk, and
exercise may lower it, the CDC said.
   An estimated 145,000 colorectal cancer cases are diagnosed in
the United States each year, Hahn said.
   In 1986, 55,811 Americans died of the disease, accounting for 12
percent of all cancer deaths.
   Hahn said incidence of the disease has risen somewhat in recent
years, from a rate of 49.3 cases per 100,000 Americans in 1979 to
50.5 in 1986. But mortality has dropped, from 24.8 deaths per
100,000 in 1979 to 23.1 in 1986.
   ``Detection of disease at an earlier stage might account for
some of the increase in survival,'' the CDC said.
   Stool blood screening, a relatively cheap technique, is useful
for detecting the disease in its early stages, the CDC said.
   The case rate in 1986 was 61 per 100,000 for men, compared with
43 per 100,000 for women.
   The median age at which the disease is diagnosed, from 1982 to
1986, was 71 years for cancer of the colon and 69 for rectal cancer.
   Just three in 100,000 30- to 34-year-olds developed colorectal
cancer, compared to 532 in 100,000 in the 85-and-older category.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
