<FIRST>u w PM-IowaBlast 1stLd-Writethru a0491 10-27 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iowa Blast, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0491,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Stands By Conclusion on Iowa Explosion</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 10 grafs new to update with FBI and Pentagon comments. Picks
up 7th graf pvs, The FBI's lab.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI scientists were unable to find conclusive
evidence that the explosion that killed 47 sailors aboard the USS
Iowa was deliberate, a bureau spokesman said today. But the Navy
stood by its conclusion that the explosion was ignited by a bomb.
   ``We didn't find anything that would lead us to conclude that a
device was used to prematurely detonate the charge,'' said FBI
spokesman Mike Kortan.
   ``That's not to say something wasn't there,'' he added. ``Our
findings were inconclusive.''
   Cmdr. Mark Baker, a Navy spokesman, said the service ``is
convinced that foreign material'' was found in a band of the gun's
projectile.
   ``We are confident about the sophistication of our equipment and
the expertise of our technical personnel'' who conducted the
thousands of tests for the study, Baker said.
   Earlier this month the Navy said the explosion was ``most
probably'' caused by a checmically ignited explosive device that
detonated powder bags in the breech of one of the battleship's
16-inch guns.
   But on Thursday Rep. Nicholas Mavroules, D-Mass., chairman of
the House Armed Services Investigative subcommittee, said, ``I
seriously question the conclusion that it was a wrongful,
intentional act.''
   The Navy said Gunner's Mate Clayton Hartwig was most likely
responsible for the April explosion. The Navy said Hartwig was a
loner who was upset about the breakup of a friendship with another
sailor.
   A ``foreign material'' was found in a ring inside the barrel of
the gun, according to the Navy investigation.
   Mavroules wrote in a letter to Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio,
that the FBI's investigation did not turn up the same evidence.
   ``The FBI's lab report has been described by some as
inconclusive,'' Mavroules wrote. ``I do not see it that way. It
clearly says that they did not find elements that the Navy
technicians said they found. Why is there this discrepancy?''
   Lt. Melody Bock, a Navy spokeswoman, also said the service
stands by its report.
   ``We can't comment on the FBI's equipment or technology,'' she
said. ``We trust our investigators. We trust that what they found
is correct.''
   Oakar, who represents Hartwig's hometown of Cleveland, has
called for a congressional investigation of the explosion, saying
the Navy relied on circumstantial evidence and an FBI psychological
profile that Hartwig ``took his own life and hoped it looked like
an accident.''
   In addition, other published reports, relying on unidentified
sources, said Hartwig was a homosexual distraught over another
sailor's rejection of his advances.
   Mavroules wrote that he doubts both the suicide and homosexual
angles.
   ``Probably as many people said he was not depressed and not
suicidal as said he had suicidal tendencies,'' Mavroules wrote.
   ``Only a handful of individuals of the hundreds interviewed
avowed any knowledge of Hartwig's homosexuality,'' he wrote. ``No
one had any firsthand knowledge.''
</TEXT>
