<FIRST>u w PM-MarijuanaRaids 2ndLd-Writethru a0590 10-27 0879</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marijuana Raids, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0590,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Agents Raid Stores, Indoor Marijuana-Growing Sites</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf pvs, By early, to update with
biggest busts of growing operations.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal drug officials say they have names and
addresses of thousands of people believed to be growing marijuana
indoors, and they are going after the growers and their illicit
crops.
   ``We are trying to send the message to all those people in the
United States who have been cultivating marijuana that they are
violating the law, they will be caught, they will be prosecuted
and, if found guilty, they will serve time,'' said Drug Enforcement
Administration spokesman Frank Shults.
   More than 100 people in 46 states, along with 65 stores in 22
states believed to sell equipment intended for use in indoor
marijuana cultivation, were targeted for raids Thursday by the DEA.
   By early today, officials had served 26 stores with search
warrants, of which eight were boarded up as a result, 73 indoor
grove operations containing 7,635 marijuana plants had been seized
and 129 people arrested, according to a federal enforcement
official close to the investigation.
   The biggest bust of an indoor growing operation took place in
Wichita, Kan., where 1,440 marijuana plants were seized, followed
by a raid of a store in San Diego where an owner with 600 growing
plants was arrested, according to the source.
   The source said not all the offices conducting raids had
reported their actions to DEA headquarters this morning, and he
expected the final numbers to be even higher.
   ``The difference between today's marijuana and 1960s marijuana
is like comparing near beer to 190 proof alcohol,'' the source said
in explaining why marijuana growers were being targeted. ``It's so
much more potent, you can't imagine.''
   Asked why the potency has increased so much, he said, ``Because
Americans are the best farmers in the world. They grow the best
marijuana in the world, hands down.''
   Doug McVay of the National Organization for the Reform of
Marijuana Laws, said the raids on stores were ``a publicity stunt,
a largely ineffective one,'' and ``silly, really silly.''
   A DEA statement said the agency has obtained ``the names and
addresses of thousands of individuals who are suspected of being
involved in the indoor cultivation of marijuana.''
   In the previous month, the investigation code-named Operation
Green Merchant had resulted in the arrests of 112 people on charges
of cultivating marijuana at 94 indoor growing locations containing
17,000 plants, Shults said.
   U.S. marijuana growers _ who produce about 25 percent of the
supply _ increasingly have been moving their plants indoors because
of extensive aerial surveillance that enables officials to spot
drugs grown outside.
   The stores raided ``specialize in the sale of these otherwise
legitimate products with the knowledge that they will be used to
cultivate marijuana,'' Shults said.
   The DEA used undercover agents in every store targeted for raids
Thursday to determine whether the operators knew the equipment _
such as lighting, irrigation and ventilation apparatus _ was being
used for indoor marijuana cultivation, said the source, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   The stores raided ``range from mom-and-pop to something
equivalent to a K-mart,'' the source said. ``Some of them have
fairly large warehouses. These are all stores targeting the
marijuana subculture in the United States as their customers'' and
do little advertising in mainstream publications.
   ``We have established through the advertising and other means
that these stores do sell the indoor cultivation apparatus and give
advice about its use for the cultivation of marijuana,'' Shults
said. ``They openly do it.''
   It was not immediately clear where the DEA got the names and
addresses of the thousands of people suspected of growing marijuana
indoors.
   Steve Hager, the editor of New York City-based High Times
magazine, stressed that law enforcement did not get the
publication's mailing list.
   However, he said, ``I believe that they subpoenaed the UPS
(United Parcel Service) shipping records of our advertisers and
have been using that information to build a conspiracy case of some
kind.''
   UPS spokesman Al Winnik said he knew nothing of such subpoenas.
``There's no word here of any subpoenas by DEA ... or any agency of
that type.''
   The DEA would not comment except to say there was an ``ongoing
investigation.''
   Shults said no publications such as High Times magazine were
targets of Thursday's raids.
   ``I can understand the DEA's frustration,'' McVay said. ``It's
true, some of this equipment is being used for (indoor marijuana)
cultivation. On the other hand, dirt is used for indoor
cultivation. I don't think we're going to stop people from selling
dirt.''
   Legitimate manufacturers such as General Electric and Sylvania
sell lights used for growing plants indoors, and Rubbermaid sells a
kit of indoor gardening equipment, McVay said.
   ``These stores and this technology was around way before people
thought about growing pot indoors,'' he said.
   The stores targeted for raids Thursday were located in Alaska,
Arizona, California, Colorado, Georgia, Illinois, Kentucky,
Massachusetts, Michigan, Minnesota, Missouri, New York, North
Carolina, Ohio, Oklahoma, Oregon, Pennsylvania, South Carolina,
Texas, Virginia, Washington and Wisconsin.
   Raids on indoor cultivation sites were planned for all states
except Hawaii, Nebraska, North Dakota and West Virginia, according
to the Justice Department.
</TEXT>
