<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Alfange     10-27 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Alfange,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dean Alfange, Liberal Party Organizer, Dies at 91</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dean Alfange, who was instrumental in forming
the Liberal Party, a once potent force in New York's city and state
politics, has died of cancer. He was 91.
   Alfange, a lawyer who also ran for governor of New York on the
American Labor Party ticket in 1942, died Tuesday at his home in
Manhattan.
   Alfange also ran unsuccessfully as a Democrat for a
congressional seat in 1941. He placed third in the 1942
gubernatorial race.
   After leading the American Labor Party for several years, he
broke ranks with it over pro- and anti-communist factions, and
helped form the Liberal Party in 1944.
   Born in Istanbul, Turkey, to Greek parents, Alfange was brought
to the United States as an infant and was raised in upstate New
York.
   He was active in ethnic organizations and was a past president
of Ahepa, a Greek-American civic group.
   Alfange is survived by his wife, Thalia, and a son, Dean Jr., of
Leverett, Mass.
</TEXT>
