<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1209EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-HUD-Pierce 4thLd-Writethru a0605-a0608-aCarrierCommendedforSavingLife
10-27 0884</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Pierce, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0605-a0608-a0588,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pierce Again Refuses To Testify; Investigation Nears End</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs, editing throughout to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce today
declared ``I committed no illegal or wrongful acts'' while in
office, but he again refused to answer questions from Congress
about scandals in federal housing programs during his tenure.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., said his subcommittee's HUD
investigation would end after several scheduled hearings and he
would not offer immunity to two former Pierce aides who refused to
testify.
   The subcommittee hearings have ``demonstrated a colossal
scandal'' at HUD, Lantos declared, and two panel members said they
are seeking a special prosecutor to investigate Pierce.
   The former housing secretary said he was invoking his Fifth
Amendment protections against self-incrimination because he
believed he had unfairly been made a target of the subcommittee
investigation of influence-peddling, fraud and mismanagement at the
Department of Housing and Urban Development.
   ``I believe I committed no illegal or wrongful acts,'' Pierce
said in a statement he read to the subcommittee before refusing to
answer substantive questions. ``I look forward to the time when
innuendo and rumors to the contrary are put to rest.''
   The panel has heard scores of developers and consultants detail
political favoritism and mismanagement at HUD during Pierce's
tenure but has heard little from former top agency officials of
that period.
   Pierce, who headed HUD during the entire eight years of the
Reagan administration, said he hoped he would soon be able to
defend himself against allegations he mismanaged agency programs
and was involved in political favoritism.
   ``I look forward to the day when I can tell my story, and I
assure you I have a story to tell,'' Pierce said. But he refused to
do so today, contending several members of the subcommittee had
already judged him guilty of ``lies and dishonesty.''
   ``I am constrained to conclude that an atmosphere has been
created in which I have become a target'' of the panel's
investigation, he said. ``I have been unfairly accused.''
   Reps. Charles Schumer of New York and Bruce Morrison of
Connecticut, both Democrats, said they were asking the House
Judiciary Committee to formally request the Justice Department to
appoint a special prosecutor to investigate Pierce.
   ``Now it's clear Sam Pierce is stonewalling,'' Schumer said.
``If we're going to get to the bottom of this, Justice will have to
appoint a special prosecutor.''
   Pierce appeared before the House Government Operations
subcommittee on employment and housing voluntarily in May, but his
appearances today and last month, when he first refused to answer
questions, were forced by subpoenas issued by the panel.
   He also has been subpoenaed to appear again a week from today,
but Lantos said he would cancel that hearing because of Pierce's
continued refusal to answer questions.
   Pierce rejected an offer from Lantos to cancel the hearings
today and next week and vacate the subpoenas in exchange for a
pledge that the former Cabinet member would testify voluntarily
before Thanksgiving.
   Pierce said he was snubbing the offer at the advice of his
attorneys.
   At the beginning of today's hearing, Lantos disclosed that
Pierce had asked the government to pay his legal fees, but that HUD
has rejected the request.
   ``The scandals at HUD during the Pierce years have already cost
the American people billions of dollars,'' Lantos said. He praised
new HUD Secretary Jack Kemp for ``rejecting the request that Mr.
Pierce's legal fees at a congressional hearing be paid for by the
American taxpayer.''
   Lantos also said he believed the subcommittee had legal grounds
to force Pierce to testify, because by answering questions in May,
Pierce waived his right to refuse later to testify about related
subjects.
   However, Lantos said the subcommittee would not challenge
Pierce's refusal to answer questions, a battle that would
inevitably end up in court.
   Pierce's continued refusal to answer questions leaves the
six-month House investigation at a crossroads. Three former
deputies to Pierce also have refused to testify, leaving the
subcommittee with scores of accounts from those who did business
with HUD but scant details from those in power.
   Lantos has mulled giving immunity to two of the former Pierce
assistants, including former top aide Deborah Gore Dean, but most
other panel members oppose any immunity grants.
   After Pierce said today that he would not answer questions about
his conduct at HUD, Lantos and the handful of congressmen present
tried anyway. The chairman asked several questions and the other
lawmakers one each.
   Each time Pierce said that on the advice of counsel he was
invoking his rights under the Fifth Amendment.
   Pierce had tried Thursday to get the committee to cancel today's
hearing but was told he would have to appear and assert his rights
in person.
   In a letter to the subcommittee, Pierce's attorneys said the
circumstances surrounding the hearings had not changed from last
month, when he first refused to answer questions.
   ``Mr. Pierce is concerned that there continues to be an
atmosphere wherein he remains a target of the subcommittee's
hearings,'' the attorneys said. ``It is our hope that sometime in
the near future the present level of tension may be reduced such
that Mr. Pierce ca reconsider his present position and testify
under fair and mutually agreeable circumstances.''
