<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1223EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-MayoralPolls     10-27 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mayoral Polls,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dinkins Lead Smaller in New Polls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayoral nominee David Dinkins holds a
slimmed-down lead over Rudolph W. Giuliani in three new opinion
polls, indicating the damage inflicted in a difficult week for the
Democratic frontrunner.
   Dinkins maintained a double-digit lead in two of the surveys,
although the third put the race tighter, with a 5-point Dinkins
edge. The closer poll pushed undecided voters to make a choice and
did not reject unlikely voters.
   Dinkins also held double-digit leads in two polls conducted
earlier and released this week. Additionally, a one-day Daily
News-WABC-TV poll Sunday put the race at its closest: Dinkins ahead
by 45-41 percent.
   One-day polls are sensitive to recent events, such as Dinkins'
struggle last week to answer questions about his personal and
campaign finances. Other differences in method can account for
differences in poll results.
   Dinkins was ahead 49-35 percent in one of the new polls,
conducted among 658 likely voters Monday and Tuesday by the Marist
Institute for Public Opinion. A poll Saturday and Sunday for the
Teamsters union, which backs Dinkins, gave him a 49-34 percent lead
among 600 likely voters.
   A New York Post-WNBC poll conducted Sunday through Tuesday put
the race at 47-42 percent. It had fewer undecided voters,
indicating that those who were uncertain tended to pick Giuliani
when pressed for a choice.
   That poll questioned 600 registered voters, while the Marist and
Teamster polls were conducted among the subset of voters who
appeared most likely to turn out.
   ``You're dealing with a somewhat closer, more competitive race,
but one that still finds Dinkins with a good lead with less than
two weeks to go,'' said Lee Miringoff, head of the Marist Institute
in Poughkeepsie.
   ``He came through what clearly was a low point last week and
seems to have been able to absorb the fallout,'' Miringoff said.
``Dinkins maintains at worst case an edge and at best case a fairly
sizable lead.''
   Dinkins, who would be the city's first black mayor, commanded 95
percent support from blacks, who made up nearly a quarter of the
respondents in the Marist survey. Whites overall favored Giuliani,
51-26 percent, but 21 percent were undecided.
   In the Post-WNBC poll, Dinkins had the support of 91 percent of
black voters, a lower figure than in the Marist poll, and 60
percent of the whites, a considerably higher figure than in the
Marist poll.
</TEXT>
