<HEAD>Renewed Ethnic Violence in Bhagalpur</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven people were killed in continuing
Hindu-Moslem clashes Friday in the eastern town of Bhagalpur,
bringing the death toll to more than 90 this week, news reports
said.
   Press Trust of India said at least 109 people suffered injuries
in the violence, which began Tuesday.
   Clashes in the Bihar state town of 300,000 people coincided with
processions by Hindu militants who were collecting bricks to build
a temple at Ayodhya, in neighboring Uttar Pradesh state. Both
Hindus and Moslems lay claim to the same religious site.
   The army was called out in Bhagalpur and given shoot-on-sight
orders Wednesday when arson and looting broke out despite a curfew.
   Police have arrested 200 rioters, the news agency said.
   Bhagalpur, on the Ganges River which is sacred to Hindus, is
about 110 miles east of Patna and 220 miles northwest of Calcutta.
