<FIRST>u w PM-DCBudgetVeto     10-27 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC Budget Veto,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Vetoes D.C. Budget Because of Abortion Provision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush vetoed the District of
Columbia's $3.4 annual spending package today because it permitted
use of city tax dollars for Medicaid-funded abortions.
   Bush's veto, which had been widely expected, was announced by
the White House when the president arrived in Costa Rica for a
two-day visit.
   The veto came two days after the House sustained Bush's veto of
a labor, health and education spending bill that also permitted use
of Medicaid funds for abortions for poor women made pregnant
through rape or incest.
   The veto came despite protests from city officials that the
district's anti-drug efforts would be imperiled unless the spending
package was approved.
   Included in the bill was $32 million in extra federal money to
pay for the hiring of 700 extra police officers, extra judges and a
variety of school-based drug education and prevention programs.
   Congress approved the anti-crime package to help the capital
battle its record homicide rate and drug-related crime wave. The
bill also included a payment of $435 million, to make up for local
tax revenue lost on federally owned property.
   Abortion-rights advocates and local government officials also
complained that if Bush vetoed the bill, he would be exerting
unfair influence over the city's legislative affairs.
   The abortion debate began in July, when the House voted to allow
the district to use its own tax money to pay for Medicaid-funded
abortions. At the time, lawmakers said the city was given the right
because of last summer's Supreme Court ruling that granted states
great latitude in regulating abortions.
   The city traditionally has funded abortions for low-income women.
   In last year's budget, anti-abortion forces in Congress
succeeded in barring the city from using its own taxes for any type
of abortion.
   City officials said earlier this week that they do not expect
Congress to muster the two-thirds vote necessary to override Bush's
veto in both the House and Senate.
</TEXT>
