<DOCNO> AP891027-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1251EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-PrisonDisturbance 6thLd-Writethru a0593 10-27 1052</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prison Disturbance, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0593,1083</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Regain Control of Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with five hostages, sted four,
number of injured over 100, 60 injured today. Picks up 8th graf, `A 24-year-old
...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos HX2, HX6, LaserColor HX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BLOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMP HILL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police stormed an overcrowded state prison
this morning to regain control from inmates who seized hostages and
set fires in a two-night riot that left more than 100 people
injured, authorities said.
   Officers fired shots and tear gas in a kitchen building,
wounding one inmate, in the assault that led to retaking of control
less than two hours later at 9:35 a.m., said Ken Robinson, state
Corrections Department spokesman.
   Hospital officials said that at some point a guard and two
prisoners were critically injured.
   Police in riot gear and wielding shotguns pushed surrendering or
captured prisoners to the ground, holding them face-down in the
grass.
   Rioters among about 1,900 inmates who remained loose in their
cellblocks this morning were taken to a holding area at the rear of
the prison grounds, Robinson said.
   There was continuing confusion about the numbers of rioters,
injuries and hostages in the rampages that started Wednesday night.
   Officials initially said there were eight hostages. Later it was
reported there were four and that all were released safely
throughout the night and this morning. But a fifth hostage was
found after order was restored, officials said.
   More than 100 people were injured, including 60 Thursday night
and this morning, Robinson said. He said there were no deaths and
``all employees are accounted for.''
   A 24-year-old inmate was hospitalized in critical condition,
suffering from a gunshot wound to the abdomen, said Deborah Saline,
spokeswoman at Milton S. Hershey Medical Center. A guard, 41, was
in critical condition with multiple stab wounds to the back, she
said.
   An 18-year-old prisoner was in critical condition from a gunshot
wound at Polyclinic Hospital, said spokesman Jim Mulay.
   One of the hostages, a prison guard, was released Thursday night
as a ``good faith'' gesture, and state police freed a second
hostage from a cellblock this morning, Robinson said.
   ``They literally pulled him out of there,'' Robinson said.
   ``At one point, all inmates were out of all the cellblocks,''
said Robinson, though not all inmates were actively involved in the
rioting.
   About 500 state troopers, with local police and firefighters,
moved in early today to retake the 2,600-inmate, medium-security
prison.
   The officers entered through gates in prison walls, at first
occupying areas that weren't held by the prisoners and avoiding
clashes with hostage-holding inmates.
   At the time, Robinson said prisoners were negotiating with
authorities. He said their demands shifted through the night.
   At one point the hostage holders demanded to talk to Gov. Robert
P. Casey and officials of the human rights group Amnesty
International, said a state police negotiator, Cpl. Raul Ramos.
Casey did not comply.
   Earlier, a huge fire in the education building sent flames
rising 100 feet in the air and an explosion at or near a prison
furniture factory rattled windows up to a mile away.
   Inmates pelted firefighters with rocks.
   Officials said 12 of 31 prison buildings were destroyed in the
fires, including two commissaries. Officials had to bring in a
portable National Guard kitchen to provide meals for prisoners not
involved in the rampage. Prison officials also said eight temporary
housing units used to ease overcrowding were destroyed and three of
the 10 cellblocks were damaged by the blazes.
   ``It's total chaos. They lost control,'' said a guard who was in
one of the cellblocks when Thursday's disturbance began as meals
were being served at 7 p.m. ``The officers were told to lock the
doors and leave. We had to get out. ... They said they were going
to kill us.
   ``Last night was a riot. Tonight was war,'' said the guard, a
six-year staffer who refused to give his name.
   The prison had been locked down early Thursday after violence
Wednesday night that caused severe damage to six cellblocks.
   Prison officials had difficulty explaining how the prisoners had
managed to free themselves and erupt in new violence.
   ``There was a bunch of little fires at first, but they started
putting mattresses on the windows,'' said Steve Tobias, a resident
of nearby Lemoyne, who was passing the prison as the new outbreak
began.``A whole bunch of (inmates) were running toward the fence.
But when they heard the shots, they went back the other way.''
   Officials said lock mechanisms on some cells may have been
damaged in Wednesday's riots, and a guard at one cellblock said the
inmates may have stolen some keys during the melee.
   Prison spokesman John Palakovich said most of those injured were
firefighters, but he wouldn't characterize their injuries.
   Inmates had gotten into prison tools, such as screwdrivers,
hammers and saws, Palakovich said. He had no reports of prisoners
with guns.
   Palakovich said state police fired warning shots in the prison
in the early stages of the disturbance. A television view at one
point showed a police officer on top of a firetruck firing a gun
into the air.
   On Wednesday, 47 people were injured during a seven-hour siege
that prison officials estimated involved 1,200 inmates. Palakovich
said even more inmates were involved in Thursday's melee.
   Prison Superintendent Robert Freeman said Wednesday's riot may
have been caused by overcrowding and inmates' resentment over
policy changes.
   Inmates were upset by a decision not to allow families to bring
in food during extended family-day visits. Officials said the food
could be used to conceal drugs, cash and other contraband.
   A new medical policy that prisoners objected to actually
improves access to care, but inmates viewed the change as an
attempt to restrict health care, Freeman said, adding that the
staff could have done a better job explaining the changes. The
change involved assigning routine examinations to certain days.
   Camp Hill is about 45 percent over capacity and the entire state
prison system is about 48 percent over capacity.
   Attorney General Ernie Preate Jr. said the disturbance at Camp
Hill, 4 miles west of Harrisburg, and a smaller uprising at
Huntingdon state prison on Monday were ``the predictable result of
a prison crowding crisis that has been allowed to fester for too
long.''
</TEXT>
