<FIRST>u w PM-Congress-Housing     10-27 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Housing,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Legislation Raising Federally Insured Mortgage Ceiling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate today approved and sent to
President Bush legislation raising to $124,875 the ceiling on home
mortgages insured by the federal government in high-cost housing
markets.
   The measure, part of a $67 billion spending bill for housing,
veterans, environmental and space programs, was approved by an 84-6
vote. The House approved the same bill Wednesday.
   Voting against the bill were Sens. William Armstrong, R-Colo.;
Alan J. Dixon, D-Ill.; Jesse Helms, R-N.C.; Gordon Humphrey,
R-N.H.; Steve Symms, R-Idaho, and William V. Roth, R-Del.
   Currently, the ceiling on mortgages insured by the Federal
Housing Administration is $101,250, an amount below the median
price of homes in 18 states and the District of Columbia.
   Proponents said raising the FHA mortgage ceiling will help tens
of thousands of young families cope with higher real estate prices.
   Opponents, however, contended the higher ceiling will only
deepen the exposure of the FHA to losses that will have to be made
up by taxpayers if a large number of the loans turn sour. The FHA
lost $4.2 billion last year in loan defaults.
   The bill provides $12.4 billion for the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration, including $1.8 billion for the planned space
station, in fiscal 1990, which began Oct. 1.
   It also makes available $5.6 billion for the Environmental
Protection Agency, $11.4 billion for veterans' medical care, and
$15.1 billion for housing programs.
</TEXT>
