<FIRST>u a AM-SF-Quake-QuakeShow     10-27 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF-Quake-Quake Show,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hard Times for Show that Simulates 1906 Quake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The audience at a tourist attraction that
recreates the 1906 earthquake and fire _ complete with shaking and
smoke _ sat through last week's 7.1 temblor, thinking it was just
part of the act, the show's manager said.
   Employees of ``The San Francisco Experience,'' where the motto
is ``Feel the Earth Shake,'' had to persuade people to leave on
Oct. 17, manager Craig Patterson said.
   ``I was scared when things outside the theater started to fall
and I didn't know what I'd find when I went into the show,'' said
cashier Shirley Hobson-Jackson, the first worker to alert the
audience of 26 people.
   What she found was ``people just sitting there quietly in the
dark.''
   Power was out, but the theater had already been darkened for the
show.
   ``I told them we just had an earthquake and some said they
thought it was part of the show,'' she said.
   The last thing the show needed was competition from the real
thing, Patterson said Thursday, while only three people watched the
show in the 220-seat theater near Fisherman's Wharf.
   On the day before the earthquake 420 people saw ``The San
Francisco Experience,'' he said. Since it re-opened Oct. 19, the
28-minute show has drawn an average of 80 a day.
   Patterson doesn't blame the show's realism, with shaking caused
by blasting bass speakers _ for scaring off customers. He cites a
lack of tourists and the closures of the Bay Bridge and the freeway
near the waterfront.
   The 1906 quake, in which more than 700 people died, hasn't
always been the big draw of ``The San Francisco Experience'' _
brainchild of the late Bing Crosby _ that opened in 1971.
   The seven screens and 32 speakers at the attraction also feature
the Gold Rush, Chinatown, cable cars, the Golden Gate and Alcatraz.
``Feel the Earth Shake'' was added at the suggestion of
consultants, Patterson said.
   Patterson is convinced there's still plenty of drawing power
left in earthquake simulation. So much so, he said, that he's going
to add footage about the quake of 1989.
</TEXT>
