<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan-China     10-27 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-China,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Stopping Arms to Guerrillas, Officials Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China, one of the major supporters of
the Afghan rebels, has cut its arms supplies to the group and is
slowly normalizing relations with the Soviet-backed government,
Asian diplomats said.
   A Kabul-based Chinese diplomat said Beijing has begun trade ties
with the Afghan government and generally supported President
Najib's attempts to unite the country, torn by an 11-year-old civil
war.
   ``We would like to see a broad-based coalition of forces unite
in this country,'' said the diplomat, who spoke on condition of
anomymity. ``We don't care who is in power. That is the internal
affairs of Afghanistan.''
   Asian diplomats said the change in policy began this year
following the withdrawal in February of Soviet troops from
Afghanistan.
   In June, a China-Soviet summit in Beijing _ the first in 30
years _ quickened the pace. Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
apparently was assured that China would stop arming the Moslem
guerrillas, who are fighting to establish an Islamic republic in
Afghanistan.
   ``The Soviets have withdrawn from Afghanistan,'' said the
Chinese official. ``That was our main goal. We see no need to
continue our support of the guerrillas.''
   Diplomats said they were not sure how the end of China's support
would affect the guerrillas' ability to fight.
   China began supplying the rebel forces soon after the Soviet
Union intervened in Afghanistan a decade ago. Chinese-made AK-47
automatic weapons, along with Chinese mortars, small rockets,
grenades and other light arms, were the weapons of choice for many
of the rebel bands, diplomats said.
   Chinese support never reached the level of American assistance,
which hovers at an estimated $600 million a year. Asian diplomats
predicted that rebel forces would continue to be supplied with
Chinese arms but that they would be purchased on the international
arms market.
   One high-ranking Asian diplomat, whose country has good
relations with Afghanistan, said his embassy believed Chinese arms
supplies stopped sometime this summer.
   ``Everything in the pipeline was delivered,'' he said, ``but
they made no new commitments.''
   He said the policy shift was in line with recent changes in
China's foreign policy.
   Now that China and the Soviet Union are normalizing relations
and China's ties are also improving with India, Beijing does not
see the need to encourage a civil war in Afghanistan, he said.
   In addition, he said, since the crackdown on the pro-democracy
movement in Beijing, Chinese foreign policy has taken on a more
cautious air.
   ``They are very concerned again with their relations with other
socialist countries,'' he said. ``We perceive this as part of the
Chinese leadership's renewed emphasis on politics.''
   The Chinese diplomat said trade relations have begun with
Afghanistan. China is selling canned goods and some light
industrial products. He also noted the Afghan government has
stopped criticizing China's policy toward the war.
   Indeed, the foreign ministry no longer mentions China when it
discusses the supporters of the guerrillas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
