<SECOND>PM-Boy Abducted, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0477,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Searchers for Abducted Boy Hope Nationwide Callers Can Help</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with plan to call out National
Guard, CLARIFY when reward expires and add parents' TV appearance this
morning; picks up: 9th graf, `FBI spokesman ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MP1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA BAENEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. JOSEPH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governor is calling out 100
National Guard troops to expand the search for an 11-year-old boy
abducted at gunpoint five days ago by a masked man, officials said
today.
   Gov. Rudy Perpich decided to activate the troops after he
visited the parents of the boy, Jacob Wetterling, on Thursday
night, said Guard spokeswoman Maj. Lucy Kender.
   The guardsmen, based in St. Cloud, would be deployed Saturday
morning, said Lt. Col. Ron Deppa.
   Stearns County Sheriff Charlie Grafft asked for additional state
help Thursday night, citing the large area the search had to cover.
   Jacob was abducted by a man dressed in black Sunday night on a
rural road less than a mile from his home in this central Minnesota
town of 2,200.
   Authorities said an earlier lead that the kidnapper may have
been driving a small red car turned out to be bogus.
   An art student who owns such a car called authorities to say he
had been driving in the area in search of good material to sketch,
and probably was spotted by several residents who thought the
driver was suspicious.
   ``We believe that was the vehicle we had been looking for,''
said Jim Kostreba, chief deputy sheriff of Stearns County.
   The Fox network's ``A Current Affair'' aired a segment on the
abduction Thursday night, and Kostreba said telephones at search
headquarters began ringing almost continuously as soon as the phone
number was shown.
   ``We had to hook up additional phones,'' he said. ``We're
getting calls from all up and down the East Coast'' from people
volunteering information about similar cases.
   A group of anonymous Twin Cities business leaders Thursday night
offered a $100,000 cash reward for Jacob's return unharmed within
72 hours. The offer ends at 11 p.m. Sunday. St. Joseph community
organizers are offering a reward of up to $25,000 for information
leading to Jacob's safe return.
   Jacob's parents, Jerry and Patty Wetterling, appeared on ``CBS
This Morning'' today to tell their story to a national TV audience.
   FBI spokesman Byron Gigler said 20 agents have been assigned to
the case.
   Jacob was riding bikes after dark with his 10-year-old brother,
Trevor, and an 11-year-old friend in this central Minnesota town of
2,200 people. The trip to a convenience store to rent a videotape
was the boy's first trip out by himself at night, said his father,
Jerry Wetterling.
   On the way back to the Wetterlings' house, the boys were
accosted by a man who had what appeared to be pantyhose pulled over
his head to distort his facial features.
   The two boys who escaped told police the man pulled a gun and
asked them their ages, then ordered them to run away and threatened
to shoot them.
   Jerry Wetterling said he and his wife, Patty, a substitute
school teacher, had warned their four children to be wary of
strangers.
   ``My advice would be to take time to sit down and instruct
children that there are sick people in the world,'' said
Wetterling, a chiropractor and president of the St. Cloud chapter
of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   The couple described Jacob as an all-around student who loved to
study math and play goalie on a youth-league hockey team.
   Wetterling said they had received no ransom demands and doubted
his civil rights activism was a factor in his son's abduction.
``It's an abnormal situation,'' he said.
   In Washington, D.C., Sen. Dave Durenberger, R-Minn., told Senate
colleagues of the abduction and St. Joseph.
   ``It's a little town, guided principally by family values, where
people work together, go to church together, and care deeply for
each other,'' said Durenberger, a native of nearby St. Cloud.
   ``It is a town that symbolizes the best virtues of America's
small towns. Crime as we've come to know it here in Washington,
D.C., is non-existent.''
</TEXT>
