<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     10-27 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Animal protection groups want to make sure
that black cats don't cross the wrong paths this Halloween.
   Several of the groups have asked Florida animal shelters to
prohibit adoption of black cats until after the holiday. Their fear
is that the animals may fall prey to satanic worshippers and evil
pranksters.
   ``It's simply because you get a lot of Halloween parties,'' said
Martha Lentz, acting director of the Humane Society of Orlando.
   ``People want to adopt them for the wrong reasons. There are a
lot of satanic rituals. ... We don't want to be responsible for the
abuse of an animal.''
   ``If somebody wants to be a witch for Halloween, she'll just
call up and ask, `Do you have any in stock?' '' said Lisa Gonzalez,
telephone operator for a Miami shelter. ``When they say `in stock,'
I just tell them `no way.' That does it.''
   Last year, the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals
in St. Petersburg protested when it learned that a local bar tried
to entice customers by offering free drinks to anyone who brought
in a black cat.
   ``We nipped that in the bud,'' said society spokeswoman Beth
Dall.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CROWN POINT, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerald Alan Yoho knew a name change was
in order when he wanted to open up his own retail jewelry business.
   ``You cannot have `Yoho Jewelers,''' the Crown Point businessman
said recently discussing the change three years ago. ``You've got a
lady sitting at home, and her husband looks her in the eye and
says, `Let me get this straight. You left your $3,000 diamond ring
at Yoho Jewelers?'''
   Yoho's trip to Lake Circuit Court allowed him to flip-flop his
middle name and surname, legally becoming Jer Yoho Alan and opening
Alan Jewelers on Main Street shortly after.
   Alan was one of 110 people who petitioned for a name change in
Lake and Porter counties in 1986. Some, like Alan, simply sought a
less awkward moniker.
   Some had something a little more poetic in mind. Wayne P.
Thornburg, for example, went to court in Crown Point recently to
become Nicolo Vincenzo Antonio Lore.
   ``The law is that anybody can be known by any name they want to
be,'' said Porter Circuit Judge Raymond Kickbush. ``So you can come
in and say you want to be known as Bugs Bunny, and I can say,
`Fine. I'm gonna grant that.'
   ``I recall one case where I had a person come in with a common
first name, a middle initial, and a very long and involved last
name. I said, `Well, what do you want?' The person wanted the
initial changed,'' Kickbush said.
   The former Mr. Yoho says it was no big hassle.
   ``The judge called me into his chambers. He just wanted to make
sure that I wasn't doing it for some devious reason,'' Alan said.
   ``In fact, I did a couple of appraisals on his jewelry while we
were standing there, so he could find out whether or not I really
was a jeweler.''
</TEXT>
