<FIRST>r w AM-Dickinson     10-27 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dickinson,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Asks Dickinson to Explain Deal With Contractor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The senior Republican on the House Armed
Services Committee has been asked by the House ethics committee to
explain his dealings with a defense contractor who gave him a
one-third interest in a $300,000 investment.
   Rep. Bill Dickinson, R-Ala., received a letter from the
committee this week asking for an explanation of his investment
deal with Ben Collier, a Montgomery businessman whose companies did
$50 million in government defense work in the last two years.
   ``He's very happy to explain it,'' Clay Swanzy, Dickinson's
administrative assistant, said Friday. ``He welcomes the
opportunity.''
   In an interview earlier this month, Dickinson acknowledged that
he approached Collier in 1986 with ``what I thought was a good
business opportunity.'' He said Collier agreed to put $300,000 into
a joint venture, with one-third of the profits or losses going to
Dickinson.
   The congressman said he provided the ``contacts'' for the
venture, which became known as the Montgomery Investment Club. He
insisted that there was ``nothing illegal, immoral or unethical''
about the deal.
   House rules prohibit members from accepting gifts of more than
$100 from any individual with a direct interest in legislation
before Congress. Dickinson contends Collier is not affected by that
rule, and he said Coller has ``never asked me to vote any way.''
   Dickinson said he has promoted Collier's businesses to major
defense contractors, just as he has helped other companies in his
district that are interested in defense subcontracting work. He has
denied any relationship between his promotion of Collier's
businesses and the investment deal.
   Swanzy said the letter to Dickinson from Ralph L. Lotkin, chief
counsel for the ethics committee, was ``fully expected and
welcome.'' He said Dickinson is preparing a response that will
include documents to support his contention that he has not
violated House rules.
   Dickinson did not make any money from the investment venture.
The entire $300,000 was invested with Steven A. Streit of
Huntsville, who was promising investors huge profits through stock
market trading.
   Dickinson had invested some of his own money with Streit before
approaching Collier, but shortly after the $300,000 was turned over
to Streit, the Huntsville man was arrested and charged with
securities fraud. He later pled guilty and was sentenced to 10
years in prison.
   Streit's assets were frozen in early 1987, and Dickinson and
Collier have received about 90 percent of the $300,000 from the
bankruptcy clerk who is serving Streit's creditors.
   Dickinson has said he expects to pay one-third of the losses
from the investment if the final settlement by the bankruptcy court
does not recover the full $300,000.
</TEXT>
