<FIRST>u i PM-CostaRicaMeeting 8thLd-Writethru a0652 10-27 1231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Costa Rica Meeting, 8th Ld-Writethru, a0652,1,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Joins Hemispheric Leaders at Costa Rica Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS new graf after pvs 3rd graf bgng, Bush did not, with
start of leaders' meeting and revising number of participants to 17 instead
18; SUBS pvs 4th graf bgng, Costa Rican, to reword for transition; SUBS
pvs 8th graf bgng, The 18 heads, to delete number; SUBS last graf to delete
Andres Rodriguez of Paraguay, who did not attend.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush joined Latin-American
leaders today for talks about drug trafficking, foreign debt and
political strife, and hailed ``the sweep of democracy through the
hemisphere.''
   Even before Bush's arrival from Washington for a two-day
celebration of Costa Rica's 100 years of democracy, Panama's
military government was sniping at the United States from afar and
Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega was castigating Bush for
refusing to meet with him.
   Bush did not mention either Panama or Nicaragua when he stepped
off his plane, but won applause at a welcoming ceremony when he
declared: ``I believe we can create here in the Americas the
world's first completely democratic hemisphere.''
   Ortega sat at least a half-dozen seats away from Bush when the
17 hemispheric leaders began their first working session this
afternoon at a resort hotel outside San Jose. Each was introduced
to rounds of applause, and their deliberations at a long table were
broadcast live on national television.
   At the airport, Costa Rican President Oscar Arias announced a
tentative agreement that will allow his country to reduce its $4.5
billion foreign debt burden by $1 billion. He said the agreement
would reduce debt service by two-thirds.
   Arias gave no further details, but profusely thanked the United
States for its help in achieving ``the best gift we could possibly
make to future generations of Costa Ricans.''
   Bush and Arias shook hands and then embraced each other with
hearty hugs. Waving at a group of youngsters in the crowd, Bush
paid tribute to Costa Rica's tradition of greeting foreign visitors
``not with the guns of military salutes but with the cheers of
those school children.''
   From the airport, Bush rode through heavily guarded streets to
the Cariari Hotel and Country Club, a resort complex about five
miles outside the capital, for the first of two meetings with
hemispheric leaders lasting more than four hours this afternoon.
   The heads of state, sitting around a long table stretching the
length of a room, were to have lunch together between the two
working sessions, and to attend a black-tie dinner tonight at the
downtown National Theater.
   Bush offered other hemispheric nations ``a new partnership of
mutual respect and mutual responsibility,'' and urged them to join
the United States to ``defeat the new slayers of the democratic
dream, the narco traffickers who poison our children, murder
elected officials and wage war on civil society.''
   Arriving ahead of Bush, Ortega told reporters he hoped the
meeting will be the first step toward talks between North and South
America. ``Without confronting the problems of the economy,
commerce and the rights of nations to live in peace, democracy is
at risk throughout Central America,'' Ortega said.
   Questioned during a photo session with Arias, Bush said he wants
Nicaragua to have free, fair elections resulting in a democratic
government. Asked if he would tell this to Ortega, the president
replied: ``You all are looking for some kind of fight. I'm here to
celebrate democracy.''
   Security was tight as presidents and prime ministers arrived
under cloudy skies. Downtown San Jose was sealed off and patrolled
by 4,000 policemen, and the U.S. Secret Service supervised
installation of a two-inch-thick, 75-foot long sheet of bulletproof
glass in front of the National Museum for Saturday's inauguration
of Democracy Plaza.
   Officials said the 4.5-ton security shield was intended
primarily to protect Bush and President Virgilio Barco of Colombia,
who has been marked for death by drug cartel leaders for his recent
crackdown.
   Nicaragua's Marxist leader said he wasn't surprised that Bush
refused to meet with him. ``That's been Bush's policy,'' Ortega
said. ``He's always trying to trample on Nicaragua.''
   But he added: ``We'll all be sitting down together. There we'll
talk.''
   Panamanian leader Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega wasn't invited to
the summit. But in advertisements placed in San Jose's major
newspapers, provisional Panamanian President Francisco Ramirez told
the leaders that democracy in Panama couldn't be considered without
also discussing U.S. economic and political pressure.
   Guillermo Endara, Panama's opposition leader who is here as an
observer, shrugged off a report that Noriega's government was
filing legal charges against him. Endara said he would like to see
Noriega wearing ``wooden pajamas'' _ a coffin _ by the end of the
year.
   Bush regards Ortega's communist-backed Sandinista government as
a threat to U.S. national security. Nevertheless, Arias said
earlier, ``there will be a dialogue among all of us around a
table'' with a common agenda, even though Bush refuses to talk
directly to Ortega.
   Before he left Andrews Air Force Base, Md., aboard Air Force
One, Bush made no direct mention of Ortega. Instead, he said he was
flying to Costa Rica to ``salute the traditions of a nation and a
people that, in many ways, represents the model for our entire
hemisphere.''
   Costa Rica ``is no longer one of the few lonely democracies'' in
the Western Hemisphere, the president said in his departure
statement. ``Indeed today there are only a few lonely holdouts
against the sweep of democracy through the hemisphere.''
   ``I believe history will show that this hemisphere's democratic
resurgence helped set the stage for today's electrifying changes in
the communist world,'' Bush said.
   Arias excluded the governments of Panama, Cuba, Haiti and Chile
_ from the centennial celebration because they were not chosen in
popular elections. But he invited opposition leaders of both
Nicaragua and Panama as observers, including Violeta Chamorro, who
is running against Ortega in Nicaragua's presidential elections
Feb. 25.
   Bush said he would bring up the problems of a fair election in
Nicaragua and arms shipments to El Salvador's leftist guerrillas
``every chance I get.''
   There was no fixed agenda, however, and plans to issue even a
general communique on democracy were scrapped when Bush let it be
known he would not sign a document that had Ortega's name on it.
   Arias said he was not disappointed because ``the communique is
usually put in a drawer and forgotten. What we are trying to get
out of this is a new dialogue, an exchange of opinions.''
   Ortega said the scrapping of the communique was no surprise.
``That's a reflection of Latin-American reality, that there is
always bad feeling among our countries because of the way the
United States behaves, and because of Bush's bad political and
economic policy,'' he said.
   Bush planned to meet with Mrs. Chamorro and Endara, whom the
United States considers the legitimate president of Panama because
of his victory in the May 7 elections, which were annulled.
   Also scheduled to attend were Michael Manley of Jamaica, Brian
Mulroney of Canada, Jose Sarney of Brazil, Jose Azcona Hoyo of
Honduras, Carlos Saul Menem of Argentina, Carlos Andres Perez of
Venezuela, Julio Maria Sanguinnetti of Uruguay, Lynden Pindling of
the Bahamas, George Price of Belize, Rodrigo Borja of Ecuador,
Desmond Hoyt of Guyana, Arthur Robinson of Trinidad and Tobago, and
Rafael Hernandez, governor of Puerto Rico.
</TEXT>
