<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1441EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-SheriffAmendment Bjt   10-27 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sheriff Amendment, Bjt,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheriffs Seek Protection From Personal Liability</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several years ago, Otsego County Sheriff
Martin Ralph put his house, his car and everything else he had in
his wife's name. He wants New York's voters to do something about
that on Election Day.
   ``If she runs away tomorrow, I'm homeless,'' said Ralph. ``It
shouldn't have to be that way.''
   Ralph isn't having a fight with his wife and doesn't expect her
to leave him. Instead he's battling to have what he believes is an
onerous and antiquated provision of the state constitution
eliminated.
   That provision holds Ralph and other state sheriffs personally
liable for the acts of their departments and employees. They are
the only public officials in the state who face such potential
personal liability for official acts.
   When the state's voters enter the ballot booth Nov. 7, they'll
be able to decide on the fate of the provision with ``Proposal
Number One, An Amendment.''
   Should the amendment be approved, residents can still sue the
sheriff, but they won't be able to get his home and car, only money
from the county.
   Peter Kehoe, executive director of the New York State Sheriffs'
Association, said earlier this month there once was good reason for
having the sheriffs held personally liable.
   Until the 1930s, New York state's sheriffs were unsalaried
officials who got to keep all the fees collected by their offices.
   ``The sheriff was essentially a private businessman,'' said
Kehoe.
   Those fees could be substantial. When a sheriff sold property to
satisfy a court judgment, he kept 5 percent of the selling price.
When he served a summons, he got a fee.
   ``They could become very wealthy,'' said Kehoe.
   The job was so profitable that Democrat Al Smith gave up his
state Assembly seat in 1915 to run for New York County sheriff.
   Having salted away between $50,000 and $80,000 in his two-year
term as sheriff, according to a later biographer, Smith ran for and
won the governorship in 1918. He later ran unsuccessfully for
president.
   The state law was later changed to make each sheriff a salaried
employee of the county and to give the county all the fees.
Salaries for sheriffs now range from $85,000 a year in both
Westchester and Monroe counties to the $25,000 paid in rural
Schuyler County.
   What wasn't changed was the constitutional provision making the
sheriffs personally liable for official acts of their departments.
   ``It's a sword of Damocles hanging over the sheriffs' heads,''
said Kehoe. ``Fortunately, the sword hasn't fallen.''
   So far the sheriffs have been lucky enough to have claims
against them covered by the liability insurance that's carried by
the counties, Kehoe said. But insurance companies are questioning
that coverage, he said.
   Another problem, said Kehoe, is the switch by many counties to
self-insurance, a situation that could leave them without the legal
authority to cover judgments against their sheriffs. About
one-third of counties have already become self-insured, he said.
   ``It's not a comfortable situation,'' said Kehoe. ``The sheriffs
are all worried about their families.''
   Putnam County Sheriff Robert Thoubboron said that while he
hasn't put his assets in his wife's name, the liability problem is
a concern.
   ``My predecessor (Raymond Weizenecker) died in office in
February 1985,'' Thoubboron said. ``His estate was tied up in
litigation as a result of a lawsuit brought against him while he
was sheriff. It took three years before that was finally resolved.''
   Such concerns prompted the sheriffs' association to ask the
state Legislature to approve the proposed constitutional amendment
and send it to the voters. Both houses approved the proposed
amendment unanimously.
   ``They were quick to recognize that we were in jeopardy and were
very sympathetic,'' Thoubboron said. ``One of them said to me, `My
God, I don't know how you could take that kind of a job with such a
risk.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
