<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1454EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     10-27 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Islamic Groups Reject Baker Plan, Urge Escalation in Uprising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Islamic fundamentalist groups called Friday for
an escalation of the Palestinian uprising in the occupied lands and
rejected U.S.-mediated Middle East peace efforts.
   Also Friday, three Christian bishops abandoned efforts to visit
the Christian Arab town of Beit Sahour in the occupied West Bank
after being told they could go only with an army escort.
   Soldiers also blocked Jerusalem's Roman Catholic, Greek Orthodox
and Armenian bishops and two other church leaders from delivering
three truckloads of sugar, rice, flour and cooking oil to Beit
Sahour, saying it was a ``closed military zone.''
   The town near Bethlehem has been declared closed to outsiders
because of its boycott of Israeli taxes, part of the 22-month-old
uprsing against Israeli occupation.
   Repeated tax raids since Sept. 20 have stripped many houses and
shops of furniture, merchandise and machinery.
   Beit Sahour residents pledged Friday to continue the tax revolt.
   ``We will continue using non-violent resistance as a means of
awakening the Israeli people to their need, as well as ours, to
live together in a just peace, two peoples in two free and secure
states,'' said a statement.
   Two Palestinians were reported shot and wounded by Israeli
soldiers in the occupied Gaza Strip, including a 14-year-old boy
from the Jabaliya refugee camp who was in critical condition with a
bullet in the stomach, Arab hospitals reported.
   Since the uprising began in December 1987, 605 Palestinians have
been killed by Israelis. An additional 136 Palestinians have been
slain by fellow Arabs, most on suspicion of collaborating with
Israel. Forty Israelis have died.
   On Friday, Mohammed Zalaat, 22, of the Tulkarem refugee camp in
the West Bank died of injuries sustained a day earlier when he fell
while jumping from roof to roof to elude soldiers, doctors at
Ramallah hospital said. The army confirmed the incident.
   The calls for escalating the uprising were in leaflets issued by
the Moslem fundammentalist groups Hamas, or Zeal, and Hezbollah.
Both are opposed to compromise with Israel.
   Hamas called for finding ways to escalate the uprising and said
the group ``rejects all peaceful settlements, including Baker's
initiative.''
   It was a reference to the five-point plan put forward by
Secretary of State James A. Baker III to try to get a
Palestinian-Israeli dialogue under way.
   Hezbollah called for ``underground cells serving as military
units to challenge Satan's schemes and strike at Zionist
interests.''
   It chided peace efforts as examples of ``begging at the gates of
the Knesset and White House.'' The Knesset is Israel's parliament.
   The church leaders trying to visit Beit Sahour also included
representatives of the Greek Catholic sect and the Franciscan
religious order.
   An army officer at the scene, identified only as Colonel D.,
said the army refused to allow a large group of churchmen to enter
because they might cause ``a situation of incitement.''
   He agreed to allow three bishops to go to the town with an army
escort but said their associates and about 15 aides would have to
stay behind. The bishops refused.
   ``They said `God will protect us,' but the commander of the area
responsible for their safety felt it would be unwise,'' said an
army spokesman.
   Roman Catholic Patriarch Michel Sabbah told reporters the
churchmen had hoped to pray in Beit Sahour and meet with the mayor.
   ``They (the soldiers) did not let us do our humanitarian
duties,'' Sabbah complained.
   The religious leaders then went to Bethlehem and prayed for Beit
Sahour at the Church of Nativity, by tradition the site of Christ's
birth. The church bells were rung to show solidarity with the
nearby town.
</TEXT>
