<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1525EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Scandal     10-27 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Scandal,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hocke Comments on Resignation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The outgoing U.N. high commissioner for refugees
said Friday he resigned because it was increasingly difficult to do
his job while the target of ``irresponsible'' attacks.
   The resignation of Jean-Pierre Hocke, announced Thursday at the
United Nations in New York, followed allegations he misused a
special U.N. ``educational fund'' to subsidize first-class air
travel for himself.
   Hocke admitted he had flown first class, a right reserved for
the U.N. secretary-general under stringent U.N. austerity measures,
but denied any impropriety. He said he had gone first class on some
long intercontinental flights when he had a busy work schedule.
   A Danish statement said Tuesday the account was opened for use
by Hocke's Danish predecessor, Poul Hartling, and that Hocke showed
a ``lack of judgment'' in believing assurances by a Danish aide
that he also could draw from it to cover travel expenses.
   At Denmark's request, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar ordered that an inquiry into the case be broadened.
   At a news conference after returning to his native Switzerland
from New York, Hocke said his resignation does ``not reflect any
sentiment of culpability on my part.''
   He said he did not feel pressured to resign and decided on his
own to do so.
   Reading a statement, Hocke said ``the function of the high
commissioner requires a total commitment and availability to act,
to convince and to galvanize.''
   That commitment was sapped ``by repeated and irresponsible
attacks'' and ``destructive intentions of some people here and
elsewhere,'' he said without elaborating.
   ``These were the considerations that led to my resignation,
which should not be seen as a withdrawal in the middle of the
storm,'' Hocke added.
   He said the agency will face a ``formidable challenge in the
next few months when refugee protection and assistance will be more
difficult than ever.''
   Asked whether he was the victim of a campaign or realized he had
made mistakes, he said, ``Both.''
   ``I would never claim that I am free from making any mistakes,''
he added.
   Gerald Hinteregger of Austria, head of the U.N. Economic
Commission for Europe, was chosen as interim chief of the refugee
agency. The U.N. General Assembly will decide on a successor before
the end of the year. Norway announced Friday it named former
Foreign Minister Thorvald Stoltenberg as a candidate for the job.
   Hocke was a former director of operations of the International
Committee of the Red Cross and became the U.N. high commissioner
for refugees in 1986.
   During his tenure, private relief agencies complained that Hocke
was bending to the restrictive national polices of major donor
nations, such as the United States, Japan and West Germany, rather
than speaking out as the protector of refugees worldwide.
   Western nations are adopting more restrictive refugee policies,
accepting only those who can prove they are politically persecuted
and excluding economic refugees.
   Hocke came under particularly strong criticism in January 1988
when he ordered the burning of all 138,000 copies of the agency's
monthly magazine, Refugees, because it contained an article
critical of West Germany's policy. Hocke said the article was
outdated.
</TEXT>
