<FIRST>r a AM-PostPublisher     10-27 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Post Publisher,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian News Executive Named Denver Post Publisher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian news executive Donald F. Hunt has been
named publisher of The Denver Post, succeeding Maurice ``Moe''
Hickey.
   Hunt, 60, a co-founder of The Toronto Sun, was named publisher
on Thursday. He recently was president of MediaNews International
in Toronto, a subsidiary of MediaNews, The Post's parent company.
   ``I'm impressed by Denver,'' said Hunt, adding he will be
involved in community affairs. ``The role of the publisher is to be
involved in the community.''
   Hickey, who had been publisher of the Post since 1987, has
resigned, citing philosophical differences with William Dean
Singleton, chairman of the Denver Post Corp. Hickey has said he
will pursue other opportunities in Colorado.
   Hunt will report to Singleton, who will assume the additional
title of chief executive officer of The Denver Post.
   Hickey became The Post's publisher when MediaNews bought the
newspaper from the Los Angeles-based Times Mirror Co.
   Hunt, a native of Canada, began working for the Canadian Press
wire service when he was 17, and later worked as an editor and
reporter for newspapers in Montreal and Toronto. He served as chief
operating officer of The Toronto Sun from its founding in 1971
until 1983.
   When the Sun bought The Houston Post in 1983, Hunt moved to
Texas to serve as publisher. He was still publisher when The
Houston Post was purchased by Singleton in 1987.
   Last year, Hunt left The Houston Post, moving to Toronto to head
a MediaNews effort to buy newspapers in Great Britain.
</TEXT>
