<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1953EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-StarWars     10-27 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Star Wars,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Democrats Stand by Star Wars Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several House Democrats are asking their
colleagues to stand firm in negotiations with the Senate on a
significant cut in the Strategic Defense Initiative as Congress
moves toward completion of a $305 billion defense bill.
   In a two-page letter to Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the
House Armed Services Committee, sixteen Democratic members of the
House said the spending level for SDI should be $3.28 billion, not
the $3.55 billion congressional negotiators are currently
considering.
   ``It would not be $3.55 billion, a number which credits Senate
posturing by `undistributed reduction' amendments contained in both
the Senate authorization and appropriations bills,'' the lawmakers
said in the letter, which was released Friday.
   ``We should count only SDI authorizations backed by
appropriations, and not based on undistributed reductions,'' they
said.
   House members were referring to Senate action last month on the
defense appropriations bill. Initially, the Senate slashed $900
million from President Bush's request of $4.6 billion for the
proposed anti-missile shield, but two days later, in an attempt to
gain room to manuever in negotiations with the House, the Senate
restored $600 million.
   The House in August approved $2.84 billion for the Pentagon's
share of the program in its authorization bill. The Senate adopted
a total of $4.3 billion in its authorization legislation.
   Currently, House and Senate conferees on the defense bill for
the fiscal year that began Oct. 1 are considering a compromise
total of $3.55 billion for the program popularly known as Star Wars.
   ``Any higher SDI number should be offset elsewhere with
substantial concessions,'' the letter said. ``As (Senate Armed
Services) Chairman Sam Nunn said recently, `SDI is a perishable
commodity and it is going downhill on both sides of Congress. ...
It's a big pot of money ... and the goals are elusive and vague.'''
   Signing the letter were Reps. Charles Bennett of Florida,
Patricia Schroeder of Colorado, Ronald Dellums of California, Lane
Evans of Illinois, George Hochbrueckner of New York, Joseph Brennan
of Maine, Jim Olin of Virginia, Steny Hoyer of Maryland, Edward
Markey of Massachusetts, Vic Fazio of California, Martin Olav Sabo
of Minnesota, Barney Frank of Massachusetts, Jim Moody of
Wisconsin, Howard Berman of California, Les AuCoin of Oregon and
David Bonior of Michigan.
</TEXT>
