<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1554EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Name     10-27 0142</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Name,140</SECOND>
<DATELINE>MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crew of seismologists and geologists
feverishly gathering data on the Oct. 17 earthquake spent little
time giving it a name, and nobody suggested ``The Big One.''
   The 7.1 temblor was named Loma Prieta for a large but relatively
indistinct, flat-topped mountain just three miles from the
epicenter of the rupture. The 3,791-foot high mountain, one of the
largest in the Coastal Range, overlooks the Santa Clara Valley and
is 56 miles south of San Francisco.
   The U.S. Geological Survey almost always names earthquakes for a
geological feature closest to the origin of the first shock,
although there is no policy in place such as the one for naming
hurricanes.
   ``It was a very informal thing done within the first hour,''
said spokeswoman Pat Jorgenson.
   Translated from Spanish, Loma Prieta means ``Dark Hill.''
</TEXT>
