<DOCNO> AP891027-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1559EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Hotel Bjt   10-27 0870</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Hotel, Bjt,0896</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western-Style Hotel Stockpiles Light Bulbs, Sugar Before Opening</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three months' worth of light bulbs have
been stockpiled. So has a month's supply of sugar. Grapes have
begun growing on hothouse vines.
   Before the first Western-managed hotel in the East bloc could
open its doors Friday, owners had to forage across a grim landscape
of perpetual shortages, import the goods it couldn't find and teach
Communist-taught wholesalers about supply and demand.
   They also had to stop the toilet-seat thieves.
   The opening of 520-room Warsaw Marriott marks completion of the
first U.S.-Polish joint venture signed after the 1987 lifting of
U.S. trade sanctions imposed in response to the martial-law
crackdown of 1981.
   It is viewed as a test of the profits and pitfalls awaiting
major Western investors in Eastern Europe.
   Rapid political changes provided a timely break for the
partnership formed by the Washington-based hotelier, the Austrian
ILBAU construction company and the Polish Airlines LOT. A
non-communist government bent on resurrecting the economy has taken
over, and both tourism and business traffic are swiftly growing.
   Marriott managers tried to recreate America in the 41-story
skyscraper, which for the previous eight years had towered
unfinished over Warsaw as an embarrassing symbol of Poland's
economic ruin.
   ``People were sick and tired of seeing this building unfinished.
They felt ashamed,'' said engineering director Jan Zonneveld. ``But
now I think Warsaw residents are pretty happy ... It is a unique
building, the most luxurious.''
   Managers spent about $70 million to put in gleaming marble,
plush carpeting and luxurious decorations seen nowhere else in
Poland.
   They opened the only Italian restaurant in Poland, the only
steakhouse and the first casino, and installed the only computer
controlled air conditioning and heating system and the only hotel
fire sprinkler network.
   To open it, Marriott contractors imported spare parts for carpet
factories, trained waiters to bring the check unasked contrary to
European custom and planted an Italian herb garden in the head
chef's backyard.
   To keep it going, the hotel is girded against scarcity.
   ``No comparison,'' sighed Francois Porte, asked how the
complexities of being the executive food and beverage director in
shortage-plagued Poland compared with his last Marriott assignment:
Amman, Jordon.
   The hotel has 38 walk-in refrigerator-freezers. The storage
rooms keep a month's supply of all dry goods, including coffee,
flour and sugar that cannot be counted on in Poland's
shortage-plagued market. In addition, it has three-months' supply
of light bulbs to keep 52,000 sockets filled.
   A computer monitors supplies and can change menus within a day
in case something runs out.
   ``You go to a hotel restaurant in Poland and say, `Can I have
this,' and they say, `Oh no, we don't have that today, we don't
have this today,''' Porte said. ``I don't want to run into the same
situation.''
   Marriott has agreements with state-run farms and private
greenhouses to grow lettuce, tomatoes, peppers and other vegetables
virtually unavailable during the winter. But it had to supply the
seeds, imported from Holland.
   It has its own canning and freezing plant, provides yeast
supplies to a brewery and sugar to a cola maker, and planted its
own greenhouse grapevines to counter cold-weather fruit supplies.
   ``Meat was a tough problem,'' Porte said. ``No one wanted to
supply us. They said they were already producing whatever they
could produce.''
   Deals finally were struck, but the first day no meat arrived, a
symptom of the business ethic sapped by decades of undersupply and
disregard for captive consumers.
   ``They said simply they didn't have the meat, and we said, `You
promised.' We went back and told them how they could get the meat
and what they could do to supply us,'' Porte said.
   ``We basically are getting involved in their management. We are
not just buying the raw product. We have to be involved in the
production and teaching people how they can supply us,'' he said.
   Room rates are in dollars only _ $135 a night, but the
restaurants deal in zlotys. The prices are high but not out of
sight for better-off Poles, except perhaps for the T-bone steak
imported from the United States offered at 220,000 zlotys (an
average monthly salary), or the equivalent of $29.
   Salaries for the hotel's 1,000 employees are reviewed every
three months to combat the 600 percent inflation rate, and Marriott
went straight to manufacturers to ensure two pairs of shoes for
every waiter and kitchen helper and three suits for each local
manager.
   Although Marriott tries to buy locally produced goods, it still
must order 80 percent to 90 percent of its materials from the West.
That creates a tremendous theft problem, Zonneveld said.
   ``A lot of people are waiting for similar materials, so they
need to be guarded from the moment they get to the airport until
they get to the hotel,'' he said.
   In the first two weeks before the official grand opening, 130
telephones disappeared, along with toilet seats and showerheads.
Guards stopped one television from walking out the front door.
   ``It is understandable,'' Zonneveld said. ``The people are poor
and they are working in an environment where they see a lot of
luxury items available.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
