<FIRST>r a AM-SmallWonder     10-27 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Small Wonder,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tiny Baby Spends First Night in Her Own Bassinet</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH NORDGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A baby who was born weighing about 10 ounces,
with feet smaller than her father's thumbs, spent her first night
at home and was ``a little bit tired'' after her big day, her
father said Friday.
   ``We're just real happy to have her home,'' said James Mann,
after his daughter Madeline's homecoming Thursday. Madeline was
born June 27, about three months before her due date, weighing
about 10 ounces.
   ``Normally, the smallest a baby can survive is 500 grams _ about
1 pound 1 ounce,'' said Madeline's doctor, Jonathan Muraskas. ``But
she came out with a little cry and her eyes were open.
   ``Her lungs were immature and she needed a lot of help, but the
best thing is that she developed no ... real significant neonatal
problems.''
   The child, who now weighs 4 pounds, 3 ounces, should become a
``normal, healthy baby,'' said Muraskas. She likely will be normal
size by the time she's 1{ years old, doctors said.
   The family was exhausted after the first night home, Mann said.
   ``She had a rather big day yesterday,'' he said. ``We all did.
But for her, it was one of her biggest. We're all a little bit
tired.''
   ``We are so blessed,'' said Madeline's mother, Robyn Mann, as
they left Loyola University Medical Center in suburban Maywood.
``As long as I'm alive, as long as we're a family, I don't think
I'll ever be able to do anything to deserve this.''
   When delivery-room nurses imprinted Madeline's ink footprint on
the back of her father's hand, it was much smaller than his own
thumb, Mann recalled.
   ``I remember thinking I had never seen anyone so precious, or
small,'' he said.
   Madeline's mother developed a type of hypertension during the
26th week of pregnancy that could have been fatal if she had
carried the baby to term, said Muraskas, a specialist in newborns.
The baby was delivered by Caesarean section.
   Madeline's birth weight of 280 grams, or about 10 ounces, is a
fraction of an ounce less than the baby listed in the Guinness Book
of World Records as the smallest surviving infant.
   ``This size is unheard of,'' said Muraskas. ``But she's never
had any major setbacks. There must be good protoplasm in her
family,'' he joked.
</TEXT>
