<FIRST>r a AM-JailBeatings     10-27 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jail Beatings,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheriff Calls for `Goon Squad' Investigation at County Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANFORD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Seminole County sheriff ordered an
investigation into reports that guards at the county jail have
formed ``goon squads'' to beat up inmates considered troublemakers.
   ``It really disturbs me, even the thought of a goon squad,''
Sheriff John Polk said.
   The allegations were made by jail workers quoted Friday in The
Orlando Sentinel, which reported that bands of guards have
allegedly punched, kicked and slapped at least five inmates since
June. One was beaten for punching a guard, the newspaper said.
   ``If the statements are true, something will be done,'' Polk
said.
   Jail Director Duane Rutledge said Friday he didn't know of any
goon squads but said his guards are firm with inmates.
   ``We have to be able to work in a safe environment,'' he said.
   Rutledge said he believes the reports are being disseminated by
inmates and corroborated by a few disgruntled employees. The
newspaper said it did not use the names of jail workers it talked
too because they requested anonymity out of fear for their jobs.
   The sheriff appointed Lt. Randy Pittman to investigate the
allegations and asked him to finish the probe by the end of next
week.
