<FIRST>r a AM-ChessChallenge     10-27 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chess Challenge,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kasparov Beats 15-year-old Soviet Defector</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAUL REYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 15-year-old Gata Kamsky, the match with
world chess champon Garri Kasparov was the peak to a remarkable
year that began with his defection from the Soviet Union.
   For Kasparov, Thursday night's two-game match was just another
exhibition and two routine victories.
   ``I'm world champion. ... He's not even grandmaster,'' Kasparov
said afterward. ``Still, it's different weights, heavyweight boxer
and middleweight.''
   Kamsky was considered one of the Soviet Union's more promising
players when he and his father defected in March. He topped a field
of 15 American players, including 12 grandmasters, to earn the
right to challenge Kasparov.
   The political undercurrent helped attract 300 spectators to the
Maxwell MacMillan World Chess Challenge at the New York Public
Library. Kamsky played with a small American flag on his side of
the table.
   The teen-age challenger said he was distracted because he was
thinking of his stepmother, Bella, who he said is being held in the
Soviet Union against her will.
   ``I didn't know I would play until one day ago and I didn't
prepare right,'' Kamsky said. ``I keep in my mind my stepmother. So
it was not good for me right now. I didn't do my best.''
   Kasparov stayed away from the immigration issue.
   ``I play chess. He was my opponent,'' Kasparov replied when
asked if such matches can further thaw political relations between
the Soviet Union and the United States.
   ``I had to beat him and I had nothing else in my mind. If it
helps relations, OK,'' said the world champion, who last weekend
twice defeated the world's strongest chess computer program, Deep
Thought.
   It took Kasparov less than a half-hour and 51 moves to win the
first game against Kamsky; the second lasted 109 moves.
   Kasparov, 26, of the Soviet city of Baku, in Azerbaijan, is a
former prodigy himself. He became a grandmaster 10 years ago and
won the world championship in 1985.
   Kamsky and his father, Rustem, defected from the Soviet Union in
March while attending a chess tournament in New York.
   The two had scheduled a news conference before the Thursday
chess match to demand the release of Mrs. Kamsky. But the senior
Kamsky said that Kasparov would not have played if they had held
the news conference.
   The match marked the first time since 1907 that a reigning world
chess champion played a head-to-head match on U.S. soil. Kasparov
played the computer via telephone lines.
   Grant McCrea, of the Special Committee for Chess in America,
said the first match between Kasparov and Kamsky reminded him of
Kasparov's handy victory over Deep Thought.
   ``I don't think Gata is used to this kind of pressure. He can
put up a better fight than he did. We saw that earlier this week,''
McCrea said.
</TEXT>
