<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1604EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-IowaBlast     10-27 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iowa Blast,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Probe Finds No Evidence Devise Used to Trigger Iowa Blast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI said Friday its laboratory studies of
the USS Iowa disaster found no evidence that any device was
deliberately used to detonate the blast that killed 47 sailors.
   ``We didn't find anything that would lead us to conclude that a
device was used to prematurely detonate the charge,'' FBI spokesman
Mike Kortan said.
   ``That's not to say something wasn't there. Our findings were
inconclusive,'' he said.
   But the chairman of the House Armed Services investigations
subcommittee said he reads the FBI's laboratory report as
undermining the Navy's findings of evidence suggesting a detonating
device caused the blast.
   ``The FBI's lab report has been described as inconclusive,''
Rep. Nicholas Mavroules, D-Mass., said in a letter. ``I do not see
it that way.''
   ``It clearly says that they did not find elements that the Navy
technicians said they found,'' Mavroules wrote in a letter to Rep.
Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio.
   Oakar had requested an investigation of the Navy's findings that
a former constituent, Gunner's Mate Clayton Hartwig, was most
likely responsible for detonating the blast.
   Mavroules assured Oakar that his subcommittee staff would
``aggressively pursue'' its investigation of the Navy's findings.
   ``I seriously question the conclusion that it was a wrongful
intentional act; even if so, is there adequate evidence linking
Clayton Hartwig to the cause of the explosion?'' Mavroules wrote.
   ``We are also looking at the quality of the NIS investigation
and, more disturbing, why was a report released before all
investigative efforts were concluded,'' Mavroules wrote.
   Also on Capitol Hill, Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the
Senate Armed Services Committee, said he has asked the General
Accounting Office ``to inquire more thoroughly into the adequacy of
the investigative effort and to validate the conclusions of the
investigation.''
   In a letter to Comptroller General Charles A. Bowsher, who heads
the GAO, Nunn repeated his plans to hold hearings on the Navy's
investigation of the Iowa blast after the Senate and House complete
work on the fiscal 1990 defense authorization bill.
   Nunn said he was concerned ``with certain issues which arose
during the Navy's investigation, but which were not pursued since
they were not considered to be immediately relevant to the specific
task at hand.''
   Specifically, the senator cited the cause of the April 19
explosion once equipment malfunction and accident had been ruled
out.
   The Navy, meanwhile, continued to defend its finding that a
chemically ignited explosive device ``most probably'' was placed in
the breech of one of the battleship's 16-inch guns to detonate the
blast, which killed 47 sailors April 19.
   The Navy ``is convinced that foreign material'' was found in a
band of the projectile of the gun, said Cmdr. Mark Baker, a Navy
spokesman.
   ``We are confident about the sophistication of our equipment and
the expertise of our technical personnel'' that conducted thousands
of tests, Baker said.
   The FBI's tests were conducted as a result of a request from the
Navy to conduct a metallurgical analysis of residue found in the
gun and on the barrel of the projectile, Kortan said.
   The bureau was asked by the Navy to conduct ``an independent
examination of the materials they gave us in an attempt to
determine if there was some evidence of a device.'''
   ``We looked at them and we can't draw that conclusion,'' Kortan
said. ``What they did in their own testing proceure, it is not
appropriate to comment on.''
   Mavroules questioned the Navy's theories about Hartwig and why
it focused its investigation almost entirely on him.
   The Navy concluded that Hartwig, who died in the blast, had been
upset about the breakup of a friendship with another sailor.
   There had been reports, based on unidentified sources, that Navy
investigators theorized that Hartwig was distraught over rejection
of homosexual advances.
   Mavroules said ``I am not sure what the issue of homosexuality
has to do with the matter at hand'' even though the Navy's central
lines of inquiry focused on allegations of Hartwig's homosexuality,
alleged suicidal tendances and knowledge of explosives.
   ``Only a handful of individuals of the hundreds interviewed
avowed any knowledge of Hartwig's homosexuality,'' Mavroules wrote.
``No on had any firsthand knowledge.''
</TEXT>
