<FIRST>r a AM-GayRights     10-27 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gay Rights,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tampa Turns Down Gay Rights Measure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tampa City Council voted 4-2 not to amend
the city's human rights ordinance to protect homosexuals from
discrimination in employment, public accommodations and housing.
   The decision, which followed a volatile 90-minute hearing
Thursday night, was the second defeat for gays in the Tampa Bay
area this month. Two weeks ago, the Hillsborough County Commission
turned down a similar gay rights amendment.
   ``This isn't going away,'' said Keith Roberts, spokesman for the
Bay Area Human Rights Coalition. ``We know time is on our side, and
the trend of social progress is on our side.''
   In Thursday's roll call, council member Linda Saul-Sena, who
along with Larry Smith voted for the amendment, said the measure
was a ``challenge to the council to do what's right and fair and
just.''
   But council member Eddie Caballero said the council should not
protect people ``who have chosen a certain way of life.''
   Council member Perry Harvey abstained from the voting but said
that, as a black man, he could not see voting against the amendment
because any discrimination is wrong.
</TEXT>
