<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0680 10-27 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0680,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aoun Issues `Last Call' for Deputies to Return Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES througout with Aoun quotes. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun on
Friday issued what he termed the ``last call'' for Christian
legislators to return home to discuss a peace plan and said he
might dissolve Parliament if they don't.
   Aoun also indicated he might dissolve Parliament to block the
election of a president, which the plan mandates.
   His statements coincided with brief skirmishing between Aoun's
troops and Syrian-backed Druse militiamen in Souk el-Gharb,
southeast of Beirut. Police reported no casualties.
   Aoun, in a speech to supporters at his shell-shattered palace in
suburban Baabda, accused the Christian lawmakers of reckless
behavior and said, ``If they persist in this behavior, the
government will use its powers.''
   He said his Cabinet has ``many choices _ one of them is
dissolving Parliament.''
   The general, who heads a three-man Christian military Cabinet in
Lebanon's splintered government, apparently still hopes to scuttle
the peace plan reached by Lebanese legislators in the Saudi Arabian
resort of Taif on Sunday.
   Aoun rejected the plan because it did not include a deadline for
the withdrawal of Syrian troops from Lebanon. Christian legislators
do not want to return to Lebanon because they fear Aoun will have
them arrested.
   The accord, sponsored by the Arab League, calls for Parliament
to meet in Lebanon no later than Nov. 7 to ratify reforms that
would give more political power to Moslems and clear the way for
election of a president.
   The plan must be ratified by a Parliament session in Lebanon to
take effect.
   Aoun said at a news conference later that it would be
``illogical'' to try to elect a president in so short a period of
time.
   Asked whether he would block election by dissolving Parliament,
Aoun said, ``That's an alternative among others.''
   Moslems have accused Aoun of trying to prevent presidential
elections so he can remain at the helm in Lebanon's 310-square-mile
Christian enclave.
   Lebanon has been without a head of state since Sept. 22, 1988,
when President Amin Gemayel's six-year term ended and Parliament
was unable to agree on a successor.
   Gemayel named Aoun head of an interim military Cabinet to rule
pending election of a new head of state, but the Cabinet split
after Moslems pledged allegiance to acting Prime Minister Salim
Hoss.
   Aoun claims that most Lebanese support him and said of the 33
Christian lawmakers who voted for the plan: ``Maybe when they
return from Saudi Arabia, they will not be able to face their
supporters because they have betrayed everybody. So I will have to
protect them by assigning bodyguards for them.''
   He said the legislators are ``under obligation'' to return to
Lebanon to persuade their constituents to accept the plan.
   ``If they manage to convince you, I'll call you to follow them
and I'll follow them too. But if they don't, then they will have to
call off the Taif operation,'' he said.
   His remarks contrasted with a statement Thursday in which he
also urged the lawmakers to return for talks but made no threats.
   A Christian source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
general ``apparently upgraded his attacks again after realizing
that the legislators were not going to listen to him.''
   Also Friday, Arab League envoy Lakhdar Ibrahimi held talks in
Christian east Beirut with Aoun and Danny Chamoun, commander of the
right-wing National Liberal Party.
   He later crossed Beirut's dividing Green Line into west Beirut
for talks with Moslem leaders.
</TEXT>
