<FIRST>r i AM-Bulgaria     10-27 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bulgaria Says Police Brutality Against Activists `Regrettable'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bulgarian official expressed regret
Friday after police kicked and beat environmentalists who had
gathered in a Sofia park to collect petition signatures, diplomatic
sources said.
   The clash came during a 35-nation environmental conference being
held in Sofia. Western delegations attending the conference
severely criticized police behavior.
   Nikolai Dyulgerov, who heads the Bulgarian delegation to the
environment meeting, said the incident was ``regrettable,'' the
sources said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``In carrying out the forcible measures due to the provocative
behavior of the citizens, public authorities allowed themselves
measures that went beyond their prerogatives,'' Dyulgerov said,
reading a government statement to the delegates, the diplomatic
sources said.
   On Thursday, several dozen members of the group Eco-Glasnost
gathered in a downtown park in the Bulgarian capital to collect
signatures on petitions opposing construction of a hydroelectric
plant in Bulgaria's Rila Mountains.
   Police arrived and began rounding up the activists and putting
them on buses, beating and kicking some of them, the diplomatic
sources said, quoting witnesses.
   They were subsequently dropped off at another park on the
outskirts of town, the sources said. The activist group had been
meeting in the other park since the environmental conference began
on Oct. 16.
   The government said 22 people had been rounded up, but the
diplomatic sources quoted witnesses as saying that 30 to 40 were
detained.
   Dyulgerov reportedly said security officials could have been
more ``restrained, patient and tactful.''
   The conference includes nations that signed the 1975 Helsinki
accords on security, human rights and other European issues. The
environment meeting is one of several follow-up conferences.
</TEXT>
