<FIRST>u w AM-BudgetDeficit     10-27 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget Deficit,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Deficit Totals $152.1 Billion in 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal budget deficit totaled $152.1
billion in 1989, marking the third year of essentially unchanged
fiscal red ink, the government said Friday.
   For the first time, interest on the $2.8 trillion national debt
exceeded Social Security spending, pushing the interest category
into second place, behind military expenditures.
   The budget gap for the year ending Sept. 30 marked a $3.1
billion, or 2 percent, improvement over the $155.2 billion deficit
in 1988, the Treasury Department and the Office of Management and
Budget said in a joint announcement.
   But, it was still more than the 1987 deficit of $149.7 billion.
All three years are well under the record high of $221.1 billion in
1986.
   Budget Director Richard Darman told reporters he was ``not
satisified'' with the deficit, but said, ``The good news is that
the deficits are not heading up.''
   Private economists, however, dismissed the small improvement,
and predicted a rising tide of red ink in 1990.
   They noted that the deficit was nearly $10 billion smaller
simply because the government failed in a last-minute rush to
complete five large savings and loan rescues.
   The Resolution Trust Corp., a new agency created to bail out the
S&amp;L industry, spent $9.1 billion by Sept. 30 instead of the $18.8
billion anticipated. The $9.7 billion difference will add to the
deficit in 1990.
   ``The promises that have come out of Washington about budget
balancing have been unfulfilled,'' said economist William V.
Sullivan Jr. of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``We see virtually no progress on the budgetary front and doubt
the government can print $150 billion deficits for the indefinite
future without some sort of adverse consequences for this
economy,'' he warned.
   In August, the Bush administration projected a 1990 deficit of
$116.2 billion. Automatic spending cuts ordered under the
Gramm-Rudman law would reduce that to $100 billion, but the
administration and Congress could avoid the automatic cuts by
agreeing to a spending package with an official budget gap of $110
billion.
   However, the Congressional Budget Office is projecting a
substantially higher deficit of $140 billion and private analysts
say even that's optimistic.
   ``I think Gramm-Rudman is just a fiction. I would say the
deficit this coming year is going to be ... at least $160 billion,
possibly as much as $175 billion,'' said Michael K. Evans, an
economic consultant in Washington.
   He said weak economic growth in 1990 will cut into corporate
income tax payments, which totaled $103.3 billion in 1989. That was
up from $94.2 billion in 1988. However, corporations paid $19.4
billion in income taxes in September, down from $20.6 billion in
June, the previous month in which quarterly payments were due.
   Also, Sullivan said the 1989 deficit was held down by a
one-time, approximately $15 billion surge in personal income tax
payments in April for the 1988 tax year. He said taxpayers deferred
income from 1987 to 1988 to take advantage of a decline in tax
rates provided by the 1986 tax overhaul.
   Evans said interest payments will continue to be a growing
burden on the government.
   ``If you take interest payments out, the deficit pretty much
vanishes. We have spending pretty much under control now, but we
have to pay for the fact that earlier it wasn't under control,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891027-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1640EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-WarsawPact     10-27 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warsaw Pact,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warsaw Pact Foreign Ministers Affirm Non-Interference Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The seven East bloc foreign ministers
affirmed a policy of not interferring in the affairs of each
other's nations as they ended the first Warsaw Pact meeting led by
Poland's Solidarity government.
   The two-day meeting's final communique also urged speeding up
disarmament of conventional, chemical and short-range nuclear
weapons and stressed the inviolability of European borders.
   But no direct mention was made of the touchy area of economic
relations within the East bloc or the problems of East Germany,
where an exodus of citizens and mass protests this month led the
ruling Communists to replace aging leader Erich Honecker.
   ``As much as the situation is undefined, conditions are
ripening'' for a breakthrough that would overcome the division of
Europe and ``definitely eliminate the relics of the Cold War,'' the
communique said.
   Essential is ``the right of every nation to independent decision
making about its ... road to social, political and economic
development, without outside interference,'' it said.
   The foreign ministers met in closed sessions. Their debates were
filled with controversy but no open antagonisms, Foreign Ministry
official Boleslaw Kulski of Poland said at a news conference.
   Poland, Hungary and the Soviet Union, as well as East Germany to
a lesser extent, are experimenting with radical reforms, but the
remaining Warsaw Pact nations _ Czechoslovakia, Bulgaria and
Romania _ have resisted change.
   Kulski said some sensitive topics, such as Romania's call only
two months ago for Warsaw Pact action to prevent formation of
Poland's Solidarity-led government, were not even brought up.
   ``No one considered it advisable or desirable to raise this
issue during the meeting,'' he said.
   Although differences surfaced, Kulski said, ``I want to
emphasize that there was no case when the differences led to
antagonizing of the participants, and they never took a form that
would be improper for this friendly meeting.''
   The main sensitive area was economic relations within the East
bloc, he said.
   The nations that are reforming their economies want to put trade
relations on a market basis, using convertible currencies and
allowing economic relations directly between enterprises instead of
only between governments.
   Such changes leave non-reforming countries increasingly isolated
within the East bloc, undermining their access to imports and raw
materials from other Warsaw Pact nations or markets for the goods
they produce.
   Solidarity took control of Poland's government on Aug. 24,
becoming the first non-Communist government since the East bloc
came in existence following the end of World War II.
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki, a longtime Solidarity
activist and former political prisoner, used the meeting to
reassure alliance members that Poland will respect its East bloc
military and economic commitments and that democracy in Poland does
not threaten the security of its neighbors.
   He also called for ``radically'' restructuring Comecon, the
organization that coordinates economic relations among the seven
pact countries, to make it more market-oriented and stressed the
need to respect the internal sovereignty of pact nations.
   ``The changes that are going on in Poland now lead to
normalizing the internal situation, and thus indirectly to
stability of European relations,'' Mazowiecki said.
   ``Poland is true to her commitments as an ally and fulfills her
duties stemming from this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891027-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1645EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Refuseniks     10-27 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Refuseniks,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. to Expedite Applications from Soviet Jews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration applications from Soviet Jews who for
years have been refused exit visas by Soviet officials will be
given special consideration by the U.S. Embassy, Jewish activists
said Friday.
   The plan is to give those Soviet Jews priority over the
thousands of other Soviet citizens now seeking to emigrate to
America and swamping the U.S. Embassy, according to the activists.
   They said the arrangement to help the Soviet Jews, known as
refuseniks because of the Kremlin's refusal to grant them exit
visas, was organized during a visit by a delegation from the Union
of Councils for Soviet Jews.
   The 75-member delegation, representing groups in the the United
States, Israel and Europe, came to the Soviet Union to meet with
the refuseniks and local Jewish organizations.
   They were allowed to come only after they agreed on terminology
making it clear the trip was unofficial, Michah Naftalin, the
organization's U.S. national director, told a news conference.
   Under new American regulations that went into effect Oct. 1
because of the crush of applicants at the U.S. Embassy,
applications are sent directly to Washington for evaluation rather
than being processed by the U.S. Embassy.
   Embassy officials said they expect to receive 300,000
applications next year. The United States, under ceilings set in
Washington, will then accept 50,000 Soviet applicants and another
20,000-30,000 people on a so-called parole system that does not
guarantee government support.
   Soviet Jewish activists fear that if and when exit visas are
issued to longtime refuseniks, who they say number about 100, their
applications to enter the United States will be lost in the flood
of paperwork.
   According to the Geneva-based Intergovernmental Committee on
Migration, 7,469 Jews left the Soviet Union in September, the
largest outflow since the organization began monthly counts in 1979.
   Leonid Stonov, a Soviet Jew and chairman of the Moscow Refusenik
Legal Seminar, said a group has been organized to work with embassy
officials to make certain Washington is informed when a refusenik
is granted an exit visa by the Soviets.
   He said the operation should be in place in about two weeks.
   Most of the refuseniks have been denied permission to leave on
grounds they have knowledge of state or military secrets from
former jobs. In most cases Soviet officials put a five-year freeze
on exit visas for people believed to have had access to secrets but
the freeze has been for decades in some cases.
   During their 10-day stay in the Soviet Union, the Union of
Council delegates met with human rights leaders in Moscow and
Leningrad.
   They held seminars and meetings to discuss anti-Semitism in the
Soviet Union, the plight of refuseniks, proposed emigration reforms
and plans to establish independent organizations to foster Jewish
culture in the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891027-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1649EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Pauley-Today Bjt   10-27 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pauley-Today, Bjt,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jane Pauley Leaves `Today,' but Stays with NBC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jane Pauley became a ready-for-prime-time player
Friday as she told ``Today'' viewers she will leave the NBC program
she has co-hosted for 13 years.
   Pauley, whose move was expected and had been preceded by weeks
of reports that she was unhappy on ``Today'' and wanted out, said
she would leave the show at the end of the year.
   However, she said she had extended her contract at NBC through
1992. And she hugged her announced successor, ``Today'' news anchor
Deborah Norville, and gave her an alarm clock.
   In an interview later, Pauley said there had been a happy ending
to what had been tense talks with NBC News executives. She will
host a prime-time special in March, do special reports for the
``NBC Nightly News,'' and co-anchor a new newsmagazine series
premiering in June, NBC said.
   But she said she once had felt that NBC executives wanted her to
leave the show _ the one in charge of ``Today'' denied this _ and
that she herself had wanted to leave because of various changes on
it.
   Although taking pains not to blame Norville, she said the one
change that probably triggered her thought of leaving came last
month when Norville replaced John Palmer as ``Today'' news anchor.
NBC assigned him Norville's former anchor job on the earlier ``NBC
News at Sunrise.''
   Norville's expanded role on ``Today,'' in which she shared the
same desk and thus exposure as Pauley and co-host Bryant Gumbel,
was only one of a number of changes that had weighed on her mind,
Pauley said. She didn't elaborate.
   But talks with NBC News president Michael Gartner and NBC Sports
president Dick Ebersol, who last summer also was given ``Today'' to
oversee, left her feeling that they weren't thinking of her future,
she said.
   ``We didn't believe each other,'' she said. ``They did not
believe that I simply wanted to leave the `Today' show. I did not
believe that they were committed to my future here at NBC.''
   ``Yes,'' she said when asked if she thought they wanted her to
leave the show. She didn't elaborate.
   NBC Sports president Dick Ebersol, who made the switch that put
Norville on ``Today,'' said this and other changes, accomplished or
planned, were being done ``to position the show for the Nineties.''
   Suggesting that perhaps Pauley had been misunderstood by a
reporter, he insisted that he and Gartner had urged her to stay on
the show.
   A proposal this month for what will be her March special,
``Changes,'' about people who have faced personal and professional
change, proved the breakthrough for what has become Pauley's new
deal at NBC, he said.
   ``I can't tell you what a happy ending this story has had for
me,'' said Pauley, who was 25 when she joined ``Today'' in 1976
after Barbara Walters, the show's first full-time female anchor,
left to join ABC.
   During Friday's broadcast, she took care to play down reports
she was at odds with either Gumbel or Norville, saying ``it has
hurt to see two of my friends, Bryant and Deborah, assigned roles
in this that they did not play.''
   In her post-show interview, Pauley said she will continue
co-hosting the show through the end of year and possibly into early
January. She also will substitute-host in January when Gumbel and
Norville are on vacation, Ebersol said.
   Norville, whose news anchor replacement probably won't be named
until December, according to NBC, said in an interview she was
relieved that all the uproar over the show finally appears to be
ending.
   She also said she was offended by some reports suggesting that
at the heart of the uproar is a situation akin to ``All About
Eve,'' the movie about a young actress scheming to oust an aging
theater star.
   ``It's sexism, pure and simple,'' said Norville, 31, who began
in TV news 11 years ago while attending the University of Georgia
and anchored at NBC-owned WMAQ-TV in Chicago before joining NBC
News in January, 1987.
   ``As a woman and a reporter, I'm offended that the suggestion
would be made, that two capable, competent women can't work in a
collegial way on the same program. In 1989, that's nonsense.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
