<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Slaying     10-27 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Slaying,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRA Claims Responsibility for Slayings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Irish Republican Army on Friday
claimed responsibility for the slaying of a British soldier and his
6-month-old daughter, the ninth attack on British forces in West
Germany this year.
   Cpl. Maheshkumar Islania, 34, and his daughter, Nivruti Mahesh,
were gunned down Thursday night at a gasoline station in
Wildenrath, a town near the Dutch border, British military
officials said.
   The soldier's wife, Smita, was hospitalized with severe shock
``after having seen her husband and baby murdered right beside
her,'' said Alan Patterson, spokesman for the British Army of the
Rhine in Moenchengladbach.
   The family's car was riddled with gunfire.
   In a statement issued in Dublin, capital of the Irish Republic,
the IRA said: ``One of our active service units was responsible for
the gun attack on a member of the British forces in Wildenrath,
West Germany, which resulted in two deaths.''
   ``We profoundly regret the death of the infant of the RAF
officer and are certain that our volunteers were not aware of the
child's presence when they opened fire.
   ``We repeat that there would be no necessity for IRA attacks in
West Germany or anywhere else were it not for the British presence
in the north of Ireland.''
   The IRA seeks to drive the British out of Northern Ireland and
unite the province with the Irish Republic.
   The attack was the ninth shooting or bombing blamed on the IRA
in West Germany since June. Four people have been killed and 21
injured.
   ``We cannot let ourselves be intimidated by people who shoot
babies,'' Patterson said. ``We will continue with our duties here.''
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl's spokesman, Hans Klein, said the federal
government was ``indignant and filled with consternation'' over the
violence.
   Wildenrath is one of Britain's major air bases in West Germany,
where altogether about 66,000 British soldiers and their dependents
are stationed.
   Islania, of London, was a supervisor in the communications
center at the Royal Air Force base at Wildenrath, where he had been
based for two years.
   He was wearing civilian clothes when he was gunned down.
   Islania joined the RAF in 1974 and earlier this year was awarded
a medal for long service and good conduct, an Army spokeswoman said.
   In London, Defense Secretary Tom King said British military
officials were working closely with West German authorities in the
investigation.
   The IRA claimed responsibility for the slaying of the West
German wife of a British soldier on Sept. 7 outside Dortmund. It
said the woman was shot in the mistaken belief that she was a
member of British forces.
   Since June, two car bombs have exploded at British military
housing areas in West Germany, one of which killed a soldier at a
British military housing area near Hanover.
   A third bomb planted in a soldier's car was found Aug. 28 and
defused without incident.
   The IRA claimed responsibility for the fatal bomb attack and is
suspected by police in the others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
