<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-HighwayStories     10-27 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Highway Stories,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Seek `I Was There' Stories In Highway Collapse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's just like any accident report _
``except multiply it geometrically,'' said one California Highway
Patrol official.
   Investigators have set up a hot line to hear from people who
were on or near Interstate 880 when the double-decked highway
collapsed in last week's earthquake.
   Initial reports already are helping explain just what happened
and how some motorists managed to escape the disaster that claimed
at least 39 lives, Highway Patrol spokesman Sam Haynes said Friday.
The reports also are expected to reveal new tales of bravery as
well as bust a few stories of heroism.
   Take the widely reported story of a heroic Mayflower
moving-truck driver who stopped his truck and flagged motorists off
the still-trembling highway and onto an exit.
   ``The reality was a little different, but interesting in
itself,'' Haynes said.
   The truck, at the southern edge of the collapsed structure,
slammed into a chunk of concrete, forcing another truck behind it
to jack-knife to a halt. The two drivers then persuaded other
motorists behind them to drive down the exit ramp so the
jack-knifed truck could get out, Haynes said.
   But reports persist of another Mayflower truck driver who was
also an emergency medical technician and stayed on the structure to
help stricken motorists. Now, that's hero material, but Haynes said
they haven't heard from that driver.
   In fact, officials haven't heard from many people who were
involved _ or almost involved _ in the highway collapse.
   ``A large number of vehicles (on the upper deck) were able to
get off after the initial collapse,'' Haynes said. ``We're still
trying to determine where those vehicles are and what happened to
those people.''
   The complete report, which may be weeks in the making, will do
the same job as more typical accident reports, helping assess
damage and settle insurance claims.
   But officials also hope to glean clues about how to survive
another such collapse.
   ``We're wondering: What kind of advanced warning did people
have? How long did it take? What were the clues that allowed them
to take evasive action?'' Haynes said.
   Several motorists on the upper deck said they had no sense of
falling. The road surface was twisting and shifting from side to
side, and people found themselves coming to rest without realizing
the road had dropped about 20 feet.
   ``It was kind of like being in an amusement park ride. It's so
violent, you can't tell which way you're moving,'' Haynes said.
   Traffic on the lower deck was light and in clusters, moving 60
to 65 mph in the two left lanes, 50 to 55 mph in the two right
lanes, he said.
   Those reports jibe with the findings of relieved rescue crews
who discovered far fewer cars trapped in the rubble than initially
feared.
   The quake hit at 5:04 p.m., but the normal rush-hour traffic was
light, most likely because people were already home to watch the
World Series game between the San Francisco Giants and the Oakland
Athletics, officials said.
   Officials who rushed to the scene the night of the quake feared
the worst, resulting in officials estimamtes of 200 to 250 dead and
scores injured.
   ``We were shooting from the hip,'' Alameda County Sheriff
Charles Plummer told the San Francisco Chronicle. ``A microphone
was pushed in our faces every 10 minutes, and we responded the best
we could.''
   Tourism officials groused this week that the inflated reports of
death and destruction made a bad situation even worse.
   But emergency officials responding to the disaster were more
relieved than upset.
   ``I think our fears were overstated. But if we had
underestimated it, we would have been criticized even more,'' said
David Johnson, an assistant to Oakland Mayor Lionel Wilson. ``To
have people mobilized and ready to help is far better than being
undermobilized.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Editors: The California Highway Patrol hot line for reports from
people involved in the collapse of the highway and the Bay Bridge
is 1-800-874-4476.
   end.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
