<FIRST>u i AM-CommunistYouthLeague     10-27 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Communist Youth League,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Communist Youth League Loses 4 Million Members This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Membership in the Communist Youth League, or
Komsomol, has dropped by 4 million this year, Tass reported Friday.
   ``Young people's withdrawal from the Komsomol is one of the
signs of the crisis this social-political organization of Soviet
youth is undergoing,'' the official news agency said.
   Chairman Victor Mironenko told a Komsomol congress at its Friday
opening that the organization has 32 million members but is lagging
far behind the political reforms occuring in other parts of Soviet
society. For that reason, Mironenko said, members were deserting
Komsomol for less official groups.
   Komsomol, founded in 1918 by the Communist Party, caters to the
14- to 28-year age group. It works closely with the party,
providing most of its recruits and sponsoring educational,
recreational and political activities.
   The group is considering major reforms in its structure and
elections process in order to win back more young people, Tass said.
   There have also been reports of widespread membership loss in
the Communist Party, but no overall figure has been given recently.
