<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Housing     10-27 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Housing,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Higher FHA Mortgages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Families would be able to buy more expensive
homes with FHA-insured mortgages under legislation approved Friday
by the Senate.
   But a technical disagreement with the House over how much
mortgage insurance the government can write in fiscal 1990 is
delaying final congressional action on the measure.
   On an 84-6 vote, the Senate passed a fiscal 1990 spending bill
that includes raising the lending lid on the government's primary
home mortgage insurance program from $101,250 to $124,875 in
high-cost housing markets.
   The House approved the same Senate-originated FHA measure on
Wednesday as part of a $67 billion package of government spending
on housing, veterans, space, science and the environment for the
current fiscal year that began Oct. 1.
   Voting against the overall bill Friday were Sens. William
Armstrong, R-Colo.; Alan J. Dixon, D-Ill.; Jesse Helms, R-N.C.;
Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H.; Steve Symms, R-Idaho, and William V. Roth,
R-Del.
   The Senate, however, refused to accept a House amendment capping
at $57.3 billion the amount of new home mortages that the Federal
Housing Administration can insure in fiscal 1990.
   Instead, the Senate insisted on its cap of $75 billion. The
action sends the legislation back to a conference with the House.
   FHA-backed mortgages that guarantee lenders against losses if
buyers default are now a source of financing for nearly 900,000
home purchases a year.
   The new higher $124,875 ceiling on FHA-insured mortgages would
allow the financing of up to an additional 100,000 homes a year in
high-cost real estate markets, particularly California and the
Northeast, according to the Mortgage Bankers Association.
   The only other dispute over the bill was over a provision
inserted by House and Senate negotiators nearly doubling NASA's
construction budget above what was voted earlier by lawmakers.
   The increase will allow NASA to begin work next year on a
half-billion-dollar plant for building new advanced solid rocket
engines for the space shuttle.
   Negotiators agreed to spend $90 million this year on the plant,
which is to be built in the home district of Rep. Jamie L. Whitten,
D-Miss., and another $90 million on research and development of the
new engines.
   The Bush administration and the House had sought no money for
the new rocket engine plant at Yellow Creek, Miss., and the Senate
had approved only $10 million.
   ``I'm sure this is not a first, but I have never seen anything
quite like this,'' said Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark. ``I've seen a
little `mickeying' around here and `mickeying' around there but it
never occurred to me that conferees had that kind of latitude.''
   Bumpers, however, did not try to strike the Yellow Creek
project, saying that Arkansas and Mississippi are neighbors and
share the distinction of being poor states in need of just that
type of federal spending.
   The bill provides a total of $12.4 billion for NASA, $1.7
billion more than last year's level but $900,000 less than what the
administration sought. Of the total, $1.8 billion will go to
development of the planned space station.
   It also makes available $5.6 billion for the Environmental
Protection Agency, a $400 million boost over 1989. The Superfund
hazardous waste cleanup program would get $1.5 billion and
anti-pollution efforts would get $817 million.
   Veterans medical care would get $11.4 billion, $551 million more
than last year. And spending on housing program will rise $2.3
billion over the 1989 level of $15.1 billion.
</TEXT>
