<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovakia 1stLd-Writethru a0649 10-27 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0649,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Havel, Other Dissidents Arrested Before Independence Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS three grafs at end to UPDATE with State Department comment.
No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police pulled playwright Vaclav
Havel from his sickbed and arrested other dissidents to try to
stifle a rally set for Saturday, the anniversary of democratic
Czechoslovakia's founding in 1918.
   In a speech to about 250 Czechoslovaks at the U.S. Embassy,
Ambassador Shirley Temple Black made a veiled call for more freedom
in this communist nation, which has resisted the tide of reform
spreading through Eastern Europe.
   Havel, whose works are banned in Czechoslovakia, was taken from
his home to a police station Thursday night, then hospitalized with
a bronchial ailment.
   On Friday, police rounded up more dissidents, a common practice
before banned pro-freedom rallies. At least 11 have been detained
since Tuesday.
   Activists said those detained included John Bok and a leading
dissident in Brno, Jaroslav Sabata. Ludvik Vaculik, a banned writer
and founding member of the Charter 77 human rights group, said
police warned him and others to get out of Prague on Saturday.
   Czechoslovaks gathered in the embassy compound to hear Mrs.
Black honor Tomas Garrigue Masaryk, the nation's founding president.
   Masaryk, a Czech, and the Slovak hero Gen. Milan Stefanik had
the support of President Woodrow Wilson in realizing their dream of
an independent Czechoslovakia on Oct. 28, 1918.
   Plaques depicting the three men hang on a wall just inside the
large doors of the ornate embassy building in Prague and a few
hundred Czechoslovaks gather there every year.
   ``These three men were patriots,'' Mrs. Temple Black told the
crowd Friday. ``They helped free Czechs and Slovaks from 300 years
of bondage to an autocratic government.
   ``Let us always remember their faith that political unity and
individual freedom could lead to the new state of Czechoslovakia
and a more prosperous and happy existence for every one of its
citizens.''
   After the speech, several people adorned the plaques with
flowers and ribbons of red, white and blue, then the crowd sang an
anthem and dispersed. One of those present was Masaryk's
granddaughter, Anna.
   Two hours earlier, officials of the National Front, the
Communist-dominated umbrella organization for Czechoslovak social
groups, laid wreaths at Masaryk's grave in Lany, a village 30 miles
from Prague.
   The ceremony reflected a changing official attitude toward
Masaryk, once depicted in textbooks as a bourgeois capitalist. Last
year, the Communist authorities declared Oct. 28 a national holiday.
   An official military ceremony has been scheduled for Wenceslas
Square, Prague's central plaza, hours before the banned Saturday
rally is to be held there. Authorities have said those attending
the rally may be subject to prosecution.
   Riot police dispersed a peaceful gathering of 5,000 in the
square last year and arrested at least 87 people.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said
there had been a sharp rise in human rights violations in weeks
leading up to the anniversary celebration.
   ``We expect the Czechoslovak government to respect the right of
its people to assemble for commemorations of this year's
anniversary. The right to assemble is a basic human right,'' he
said.
   Boucher also said the recent crackdown ``calls into question the
seriousness of Czechoslovak authorities' commitment to
international agreements, as well as their stated interest in
improving U.S.-Czechoslovak relations.''
</TEXT>
