<FIRST>u i AM-Gorbachev 1stLd-Writethru a0676 10-27 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0676,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Wants to Build Soviet Silicon Valleys</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Gorbachev departing, Swedish
reaction to his submarine proposal; pickup 6th graf pvs, `What a...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OULU, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev visited Finland's
version of the Silicon Valley on Friday and told his hosts he wants
to build similar high-tech research facilities in the Soviet Union.
   ``We have done good work here,'' Gorbachev said before boarding
his plane at the end of a three-day state visit, during which he
announced a plan to decommission four older model submarines of the
Soviet nuclear-armed fleet in the Baltic Sea.
   U.S. Defense Secretary Dick Cheney dismissed the gesture as
insignificant.
   Speaking in Bonn, West Germany, Cheney said the Soviet nuclear
capability in the Baltic ``frankly wasn't all that great.'' Experts
have described the four Golf II-class Soviet subs as dated and
virtually useless.
   The proposal also received a lukewarm reaction from neighboring
Sweden, which supports a ban on nuclear weapons in Northern Europe.
   Gorbachev's proposal was interesting but ``should be studied
closely before drawing conclusions,'' said Sten Andersson, foreign
minister of the neutral nation.
   Swedish opposition leader Carl Bildt said the Golf II-class
vessels were ``the oldest, rustiest and most scraggly subs in the
world.''
   Gorbachev departed for home Friday after a four-hour tour of
Oulu, a remote Baltic Sea city of 100,000 people about 400 miles
north of Helsinki.
   Thousands of Finns lined the streets to cheer and applaud the
Soviet president, who visibly reveled in the attention.
   ``What a lot of people!'' Raisa Gorbachev said of the crowd,
which was larger than any that greeted the couple in Helsinki
during the first two days of the visit.
   Gorbachev waved, shook hands with residents and clasped his
hands above his head in victory.
   The Kremlin leader, who has admitted his strategy to restructure
the economy is in trouble, visited a technological village where 80
science-based companies work on the latest advances in computer
hardware, laser equipment and telecommunications.
   Gorbachev viewed an exhibit by about 30 companies, displaying
curiosity and knowledge in the application of some of the wares,
said Pertti Huuskonen, the director of the village.
   Huuskonen described the village to Gorbachev as Finland's
version of Silicon Valley, a center of high-technology activities
in California. He quoted the Soviet leader as saying he wanted the
Finns to help set up similar projects in his country.
   Gorbachev was presented with an electronic pulse monitor used by
athletes and even racehorses that was invented at the technology
village, associated with the 8,500-student Oulu University. ``Many
joggers in Finland don't go out without it,'' Huuskonen said.
   Soviet businessmen operating in Finland have said they have
access to technology that is denied them in the Soviet Union by
Western export limitations.
   In Bonn, Cheney said he supports retention of the limits on
technology transfers because he said the Soviet arms capability
remains a danger to the West.
</TEXT>
