<FIRST>r a AM-LaRouche-Bankruptcy     10-27 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LaRouche-Bankruptcy,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Throws Out Bankruptcy Petitions Against LaRouche Organizations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Wednesday cq in 7th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge dismissed bankruptcy
proceedings brought by the government against three organizations
associated with political extremist Lyndon H. LaRouche.
   Judge Martin V.B. Bostetter Jr. in U.S. Bankruptcy Court ruled
that the government had acted in ``bad faith'' in filing the
involuntary bankruptcy petitions against Caucus Distributors Inc.,
Campaigner Publications Inc. and Fusion Energy Foundation Inc.
   In a separate criminal trial, LaRouche was convicted on Dec. 16,
1988, of conspiracy to commit mail fraud involving more than $30
million in defaulted loans, 11 counts of actual mail fraud
involving $294,000 and one count of conspiring to defraud the
Internal Revenue Service. He is now serving a 15-year prison term.
   David R. Kuney, a defense attorney for the LaRouche-associated
organizations, said Friday about the Bankruptcy Court decision: ``I
think it's a very important decision because it's probably the
first major victory that these folks have had in their dealings
with the government.''
   ``It reflects that the government simply mishandled the filing
of the (bankruptcy) petitions and was overzealous and shouldn't
have done it,'' Kuney said.
   David Schiller, the federal prosecutor who handled the
bankruptcy case, was in court Friday afternoon and could not be
reached immediately for comment.
   In his ruling handed down on Wednesday, Judge Bostetter said
that ``an evaluation of the government's filing on an objective
level leads this court to conclude that the alleged debtors have
established that the government filed the petition in bad faith.''
   ``It is not the filing of an involuntary petition by the United
States that constitutes bad faith ... but the failure to comply
with the applicable provisions of the (legal) code that compels
this conclusion,'' he wrote.
   Bostetter found that the government was not entitled to bring
the bankruptcy proceedings against Caucus Distributors Inc. and
Fusion Energy Foundation Inc. because they are not commercial
enterprises, but not-for-profit entities.
   He said those groups ``strived more to expose the world to
(their) political viewpoint than attain private monetary gain.''
   ``While the government has alleged that their methods of
fund-raising were reprehensible, that alone does not change the
debtors' status and provide the appropriate basis for the
invocation of this court's jurisdiction,'' the judge said.
</TEXT>
