<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Defector     10-27 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Defector,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Claim Death-Squad Defector Responsible for Killings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador Death Squads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Salvadoran army deserter
who told U.S. officials in Washington about death-squad
assassinations took the initiative in the killings, according to
testimony of his former comrades obtained Friday.
   The testimony was given in recent weeks to Judge Miguel Flores
Figueroa of Quetzaltepeque, 12 miles north of San Salvador. It was
in that region that two suspected left-wing guerrillas, Lucio
Parada and Hector Miranda, were killed in July after being captured
by an army unit that included Cesar Vielman Joya Martinez.
   Joya, who deserted from the San Salvador-based 1st Army Brigade
in July, met Friday in Washington with members of Congress. He told
Washington journalists Thursday that he had been part of a death
squad responsible for killing as many as 72 suspected leftists. He
has been charged with the deaths of Parada and Miranda and fled El
Salvador.
   The government and armed forces deny the existence of military
death squads.
   Col. Francisco Elena Fuentes, 1st Brigade commander, called Joya
``a deserter, a murderer and a liar.''
   Joya, 28, told the reporters, ``My work was only to execute
these people. My job was to kill or be killed ... I realize I was
manipulated.''
   He also said some of the people he killed ``were almost dead
from being beaten during interrogation.''
   But some of Joya's former comrades told Judge Flores Figueroa
that Joya was the most zealous of torturers who beat, drowned or
suffocated prisoners.
   Joya has been charged in absentia with premeditated murder in
the deaths of Parada and Miranda. Cpl. Alcides Gomez, in the patrol
that included Joya, also is charged in the slaying of the two men.
Gomez is under arrest.
   Though Joya said he did not know the identities of the men he
killed, his former comrades told the judge that Joya was an
intelligence agent responsible for the capture of specific rebel
suspects he knew by name.
   Lt. Herbert Soriano commanded the Atlacatl Battalion company
operating north of the capital when Parada and Miranda were beaten
or shot to death. The two were among eight guerrilla suspects
captured during an operation around the village of Tres Ceibas.
   According to the testimony of soldiers who took part in the
operation, all eight prisoners were beaten and several were nearly
drowned by Joya over two days of interrogation in the field.
   Both Cpl. Gomez and another Atlacatl soldier, Eugenio Mendez,
testified Soriano had given explicit instructions that prisoners
were not to be tortured. Gomez said he told Joya not to torture the
prisoners but Joya replied, ``If I don't, they won't tell us
anything.''
   Gomez and Mendez said Soriano was not present when Parada and
Miranda were killed. They said that after the deaths Soriano told
Joya, ``You're in big trouble.''
   Gomez told the judge that after the first man died of the
beating he expressed concern to Joya about problems with the army.
   He claimed Joya told him, ``Don't worry. I'm going to kill them
all.''
   In his testimony Soriano said two 1st Brigade soldiers _ Joya
and Humberto Rodriguez _ were attached to but ``working
independently'' of his Atlacatl company.
   Soriano said a squad from his company accompanied Joya and
Rodriguez in making the arrests at Tres Ceibas. He said the squad's
``only mission was to give security to the two 1st Brigade soldiers
so they could perform their intelligence-gathering duty.''
   An estimated 70,000 people have killed in the 10-year-old war
between leftist rebels and U.S.-backed governments. Most of the
victims were civilians. Rightist death squads, allegedly sponsored
or tolerated by the military, have been accused by human rights
groups of killing more than 20,000 suspected leftists in the early
1980s.
   The number of slayings attributed to death squads declined
between 1984 and 1987 but began to increase last year.
</TEXT>
