<FIRST>r w AM-Glenn     10-27 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Glenn,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Glenn Telephones Family Of Man Who Hit Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. John Glenn turned the other cheek, in a
sense, with a courtesy call to the family of the man who slugged
him.
   ``He called them and wished them well and said he realized this
was something beyond their control,'' Glenn's press secretary,
Rebecca Bell, said Friday.
   On Wednesday, Glenn, D-Ohio, was punched in the jaw during an
outdoor television interview.
   A day later, Michael Breen, 31, was ordered held without bond
and sent to a federal prison hospital for a mental evaluation.
Later Thursday evening, Glenn talked by telephone to Breen's mother
and sister, Bell said.
   Glenn was encouraged by his wife, Annie, who expressed concern
about the impact the incident would have on Breen's mother, she
said.
   One of Breen's sisters had contacted Glenn's office on Wednesday
to express the family's regrets, she added.
   According to the criminal complaint filed in U.S. District
Court, Breen told police he believed punching Glenn would generate
publicity and catch the attention of Pope John Paul II.
   Breen said his goal was to prevent nuclear war by getting the
pope to reveal the contents of a secret message from the Virgin
Mary, mother of Jesus.
   Some Roman Catholics believe such a message has been kept secret
for 72 years, ever since it was revealed to three children at
Fatima, Portugal.
