<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Crash     10-27 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Crash,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Transport Crashes in Far East, All 36 Aboard Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the third fatal air crash in 10 days, a Soviet
military plane slammed into a mountain while trying to land in poor
weather on Kamchatka peninsula, killing all 36 people aboard, Tass
said Friday.
   The Antonov-26 two-engine turboprop transport crashed 22 miles
north of Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky, the main city on the
volcano-dotted peninsula north of Japan, Tass said. It said the
crash occurred Thursday.
   ``The aircraft had an experienced crew,'' Col.-Gen. Stanislav
Kochemasov, chief of staff of the Soviet strategic missile forces,
was quoted as telling Tass. ``Visibility was poor.''
   The plane, carrying missile crewmen and their dependents, hit a
mountain while trying to land at Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky airfield,
the general said. The 30 passengers and six crew members were
killed, he said.
   ``The plane was carrying missile crews from distant garrisons
and members of their families,'' Kochemasov said. Tass said a
commission headed by the deputy commander-in-chief of the strategic
rocket forces is investigating the accident.
   One week ago, on Oct. 20, an Ilyushin-76 transport jet carrying
supplies to earthquake-ravaged northern Armenia hit a mountain in
Armenia, killing all 17 people aboard.
   Two days earlier, one of four engines on another Il-76 caught
fire and fell off the plane after it took off in Azerbaijan. The
crippled plane crashed into the Caspian Sea, killing all 57 people
aboard.
   Among the dead were Soviet paratroopers assigned to keep order
in a territorial dispute between Armenia and Azerbaijan.
</TEXT>
