<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Collaborator     10-27 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Collaborator,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tel Aviv Strangler Reportedly Worked as Shin Bet Informant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian suspected of killing seven
Israelis in Tel Aviv worked as an informant for the secret Shin Bet
security service, newspapers reported Friday.
   The left-wing Al-Hamishmar daily said Mohammed bin Ahmed Halebi,
32, of the Gaza Strip's Jabaliya refugee camp agreed to work for
the Shin Bet in 1985 after serving five years of an 11-year
sentence on charges including drug dealing and prostitution.
   Almost two weeks ago authorities accused him of strangling seven
Israelis, five women and two men, with a nylon rope in what police
said was a criminal dispute. Despite a massive manhunt, Halebi has
eluded capture.
   The independent Yediot Ahronot daily said underground
Palestinian popular committees sentenced him to death for
collaboration after reports of his cooperation with the Shin Bet
were published.
   But it was unclear from the reports what information Halebi
provided for the Shin Bet and whether he had informed on Gaza Strip
uprising activists.
   At least 136 Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs as
suspected collaborators during the 22-month-old uprising against
Israeli rule of the occupied lands.
   Al-Hamishmar said Halebi was given a special Shin Bet
identification card that allowed him to live in Israel after his
release from prison.
   The card also allows free passage through military checkpoints.
They usually are issued only to collaborators who possess special
information and need refuge in Israel to escape death threats from
Palestinian nationalists, the independent Maariv daily reported.
   Gaza Arabs are banned from staying overnight in Israel and must
have a magnetic card issued by the military administration to pass
through army checkpoints and enter Israel. Those cards are only
granted to Arabs who pass security checks and have paid taxes.
   Maariv said hundreds of collaborators have been issued the
magnetic cards so they can travel freely in Israel, but that only a
small number of Palestinians have been granted cards by the Shin
Bet.
   Halebi worked with the Shin Bet and spent most of his time in
Tel Aviv, where he apparently became involved in drug dealing,
Yediot reported.
   The stranglings sparked outrage in Israel and led several
right-wing politicians to demand tighter restrictions on the travel
of Palestinians in Israel.
   The Shin Bet is responsible for internal security, and there
have been repeated allegations that the service uses petty
criminals as informers in the occupied territories.
   Deputy Inspector Avi Dotan said in an interview with Israel
televison that it was ``not unknown'' for Arabs with criminal pasts
to work for the police or other security services.
</TEXT>
