<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1912EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-SavannahRiver     10-27 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Savannah River,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Advisers Raise Doubts About Reactor Restart Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department may be moving too
quickly to restart nuclear reactors that produce material for
nuclear warheads and reactor managers may not be emphasizing safety
enough, advisers told Energy Secretary James D. Watkins on Friday.
   In a letter to Watkins, members of the Advisory Committee on
Nuclear Facility Safety said that while prospects for a safe
resumption of production at the Savannah River installation in
South Carolina had improved recently, they were concerned that
reactor operators were not being trained in ``reactor
fundamentals'' like commercial reactor operators.
   The operators are employed by Westinghouse Corp., which runs
Savannah River under contract. The letter did not detail what the
advisers meant by reactor fundamentals.
   The reactors produce tritium, a gas, and are similar in basic
design to most civilian power reactors, though they operate at much
lower temperatures and pressures.
   ``That this omission will remain through restart may belie
Westinghouse's claim that safety is their primary concern and that
early restart of the reactors is not the driving factor in
training,'' the letter said.
   The three Savannah River reactors, built for the government in
the early 1950s, were shut down more than 1{ years ago because of
mechanical problems and safety concerns.
   Watkins said in September that he hoped to restart the first
reactor by late next summer, although he has stressed that
unforeseen problems could change the schedule.
   The advisers told Watkins that while restart planning was
generally good, the absence of operator training in reactor
fundamentals was a serious problem.
   The advisers also said training of Energy Department personnel
at the site ``is not keeping pace with the contractor's training of
its operational personnel.''
   In addition, the committee members said Watkins may be biting
off more than he can chew in trying to get all three idled reactors
back in operation within a six-month period starting next summer or
fall. They said it might be wiser to concentrate the best talent on
restarting one reactor, then moving on to another when the first is
running smoothly.
   Restarting all three reactors in the six-month period ``will
certainly require a large number of well-trained, competent people
who may not be available,'' they wrote.
   The advisers praised Watkins' efforts to clarify lines of
authority from the department headquarters to Savannah River, and
said other needed management changes were under way.
   Even so, the committee members expressed concern that while top
Westinghouse managers had gotten the message about the need for
greater attention to safety, the ``new safety philosophy'' may not
have reached middle management and below.
   ``Procedural errors and reporting problems continue and indicate
that an emphasis on safety of operations is not yet pervasive,''
the letter said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
