<FIRST>u w AM-Soviet-Trip 1stLd-Writethru   10-27 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Trip, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0675,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>No More Afghanistans, Leading Soviet Legislator Vows</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 6, which is first bullet graf: ``The Soviets,'' to
clarify Primakov's stance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet legislature is drafting war powers
legislation to prevent another Afghan-style invasion, the speaker
of that parliament told an American audience Friday.
   ``I can tell you quite strongly that at present there would be
no repeat of what happened when our troops were sent into
Afghanistan,'' the speaker, Yevgeny M. Primakov, said at the
Brookings Institution, a liberal Washington think tank. The Red
Army ended its 10-year Afghan intervention last February.
   Primakov said the Supreme Soviet legislature was wresting power
from the Soviet executive branch, but played little role in the
decision this week to declare that a Siberian radar violated a
superpower treaty.
   The meeting was crowded with senior analysts from the Central
Intelligence Agency, scholars and journalists all eager to hear the
comments of Primakov, who in September was named a non-voting
member of the Communist Party Politburo. Previously, he headed the
largest Soviet think tank, the Institute for World Economy and
International Relations (IMEMO).
   In a wide-ranging discussion, Primakov said:
   _The Soviets are not opposed to the eventual reunification of
Germany, if the people of West and East Germany make that choice,
but that neither the capitalist nor the communist state should
``consume the other.'' Primakov's remarks, however, clearly
reflected skepticism about the benefits to Europe of reunification,
which he called ``a matter for the future.''
   _That Communist Party leaders reserved the right to fire or
criticize editors or journalists, as exercised last week by Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   _That despite an acute shortage of consumer goods, the
government would continue its compromise course of economic
restructuring, neither retreating to a fully centralized system nor
seeking quick introduction of a free market.
   _The Soviet Union wants to join international economic
activities, such as the International Monetary Fund and the General
Agreement on Trade and Tariffs.
   Primakov was asked how the Supreme Soviet solved the dilemma
posed by the U.S. War Powers Act, which allows the president to
send troops to a war zone but requires congressional approval to
leave them there.
   ``We are drafting a mechanism for making a decision of that
kind, but so far it is not in place,'' Primakov said. ``But I can
be quite firm in saying that there can be no decision of that sort
without involvement from the Supreme Soviet.''
   ``There can be no repetition of the situation when a small group
of leaders makes a decision that is not made in accord with the
legislative branch,'' he said.
   As an example of government consultation with the Supreme
Soviet, Primakov cited a speech by Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze this week. Shevardnadze said that intervening in
Afghanistan was a mistake and that a radar station in Krasnoyarsk,
Siberia, had been built in knowledge it violated the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
   Asked whether the decision to destroy the radar had been made by
the ruling Communist Party Politburo or by the legislature,
Primakov said:
   ``As to this latest decision to dismantle the Krasnoyarsk radar
... we can only be happy ... that a decision was taken to dismantle
it.''
   Pressed to say who made the decision, Primakov said, ``there is
a separation of powers. In this country, Congress just approves
overall military expenditure, not single individual projects. That
is my answer to your question.''
   Primakov has risen to power at the head of a newly reconstituted
Soviet legislature, whose members were elected this year in the
most competitive balloting in the Soviet Union since the Bolshevik
Revolution of 1917.
   His delegation is visiting Washington at the invitation of
congressional leaders, in part to study the operation of Congress.
   On Thursday, Primakov met with President Bush and Secretary of
State James A. Baker III, and was introduced on the floor of the
Senate by his hosts, Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine, and Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan.
   After two days of meetings in Washington, the group was headed
for Maine, Kansas, Los Angeles, Pittsburgh and New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
