<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 2122EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Iran-Iraq     10-27 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Iran-Iraq,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Sending Envoy for Shuttle Diplomacy Between Iran and Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council on Friday called on
Iran and Iraq to ``work constructively'' with a U.N. envoy to be
sent to the region in an effort to break the deadlock in peace
talks.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar will send his special
envoy, Swedish Ambassador Jan K. Eliasson, to begin shuttle talks
between Baghdad and Tehran on Monday.
   ``He is not taking specific proposals, but he will be listening
to all parties concerned who will be available to him,'' Perez de
Cuellar told reporters. ``Nothing is spectacularly new.''
   Eliasson's mission is expected to last two or three weeks, he
said.
   The 15 council members expressed impatience with the pace of the
Iran-Iraq talks.
   Their statement said in part: ``Members of the council noted
that over two years have elapsed since Security Council Resolution
598 was adopted and that more than 14 months have gone by since the
cease-fire went into effect with the concurrence of both sides.''
   Resolution 598 calls for a cease-fire, the withdrawal of troops
to their own countries, an exchange of prisoners of war and a
negotiated peace settlement. It would establish a panel to
apportion blame for the war that began in September 1980.
   The Iran-Iraq peace talks opened in Geneva in August 1988, but
quickly bogged down. A truce prevails along the 350-mile war front,
supervised by teams of the U.N. Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group.
   It is estimated that about 100,000 prisoners are still being
held in POW camps in Iran and Iraq.
   Iran insists the next step in the peace process must be the
withdrawal of troops. Iraqi forces still occupy about 385 square
miles of Iranian territory.
   Also on Friday diplomats said Iran has stopped flooding a
``no-man's land'' in the southern front near the Iraqi city of
Basra. Iran made no comment.
   Iran began flooding the area in Iranian territory northeast of
Basra in September 1988 just after the cease-fire took effect.
   A large canal was opened, turning the marshy region into
swampland, making it impassable to armored vehicles.
   Last year Perez de Cuellar called it a serious violation of the
cease-fire and reported the flooding covered an area 37 miles long
and about 2 miles wide.
   Iraq and U.N. officials registered complaints over the flooding
but Iran, which claims it is an internal matter, did not respond.
</TEXT>
