<SECOND>AM-Freighter Aground, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0690,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mate, Captain Charged in Reef Grounding</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with four grafs to UPDATE with mate ordered held without
bond, ADD mate's failure of breath alcohol tests and special prosecutor
named to investigate possible state charges. Picks up 4th graf, `The Coast...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first mate of a freighter that ran aground on a
coral reef was charged in the grounding and arrested in an
unrelated Louisiana case while a Coast Guard investigation
continued, officials said Friday.
   Michael Anthony Bishop, 43, was piloting the 155-foot Alec Owen
Maitland on Wednesday when the ship hit the reef in Key Largo
National Marine Sanctuary. The Coast Guard charged him with
negligence in that incident.
   Bishop failed two breath alcohol tests given five hours after
the wreck, the Coast Guard said. He told the Coast Guard he started
drinking only after the ship ran aground.
   No state charges have been filed and Gov. Bob Martinez has
appointed a special prosecutor to investigate.
   Meanwhile, Bishop was arrested Thursday night on a fugitive
warrant from Cameron, La., in an aggravated battery case, said
Florida Marine Patrol Capt. Ed Sharp. Bishop was ordered held
without bond Friday at the Dade County Jail.
   The Coast Guard attempted to hold an informal hearing Friday to
learn more about the grounding, but the session was postponed to
give the five crew members a chance to confer with attorneys.
   Bishop is accused of running the vessel aground, not maintaining
a proper fix of his position and operating the vessel without the
proper license, Coast Guard Lt. Keith Ward said.
   The ship's captain, Duane Goodwin, 37, has been charged by the
Coast Guard with allowing a person without the proper license to
operate the vessel, Ward said.
   None of the ship's 6,000 to 8,000 gallons of diesel fuel leaked,
but a few gallons of residue oil from a flooded ballast tank seeped
into the water, the Coast Guard said.
</TEXT>
