<FIRST>u i AM-CostaRica-Color     10-27 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Costa Rica-Color,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Costa Rica's Children, Not Soldiers, Salute Hempispheric VIPs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The honor guard that greeted leaders
of the Western Hemisphere who arrived here Friday consisted not of
soldiers carrying guns but school children bearing flowers.
   President Bush, the last to arrive, called it ``one of the
wonderful traditions of this great country,'' greeting foreign
visitors ``not with the gune of military salutes, but with the
cheers of those school children.''
   Costa Rica, which disbanded its army in 1948, did post 4,000
police around the capital to safeguard the VIPs, including the
presidents or prime ministers of 15 other countries and the
governor of Puerto Rico, who accepted President Oscar Arias'
invitation to the celebration of 100 years of Costa Rican democracy.
   While Bush arrived under blue skies, the morning sunlight later
gave way to clouds that shrouded 11,000-foot Irazu and the other
volcanoes that surround the lush, green valley. Finally, it rained.
   That was par for the course in this warm, humid Latin country
between Nicaragua and Panama; San Jose is famous for its afternoon
rains.
   The conference room where inaugural ceremonies were held was hot
and humid. The foreheads of several luminaries at the main table
glistened with sweat, and spectators fanned themselves with copies
of Arias' speech.
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney delighted the crowd by
using three languages _ Spanish, English and French _ to announce
that his nation would join the Organization of American States.
   Violeta Chamorro, the main opposition candidate facing
Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega in February's elections, got a
loud burst of applause as she made her way to a section for special
guests.
   Ortega arrived in military garb, a red-and-black Sandinista
bandanna draped around his neck. He managed to shake hands and
exchange a few words with Bush before the first session.
   Venezuelan President Carlos Andres Perez came up to eavesdrop,
saying, ``I'm not going to miss this.'' But then the entire group
of leaders was ushered into the meeting hall.
   Afterwards, breaking for lunch, some leaders walked and some
drove the hundred yards down a tree-lined street to the conference
center.
   Ortega chose to walk and was immediately mobbed by journalists
who blocked the street. Behind him, Salvadoran President Alfredo
Cristiani's driver leaned on his horn until the crowd parted.
   Many businesses were closed and traffic was much lighter than
usual in the capital, which was spruced up for the occasion.
   Buildings were newly painted and 20,000 roses, chrysanthemums
and tropical flowers were planted along parade routes and at
Democracy Plaza, which is to be dedicated Saturday.
</TEXT>
