<FIRST>r i AM-Libya-Terrorism     10-27 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya-Terrorism,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Says He'll Continue to Back Liberation Movements</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi, who recently declared
he had given up supporting terrorism, said Friday he will continue
to back ``liberation movements.''
   Gadhafi told a magazine during a visit to Egypt this week that
Libya once aided terrorist groups but halted such support when ``we
discovered these groups were causing more harm than benefit to the
Arab cause.''
   In an interview Friday night with the Italian state network RAI,
Gadhafi was told Italians appreciated the remarks on terrorism.
   ``Yes, certainly,'' said the Libyan leader.
   But when pressed further on the issue, Gadhafi said Libya
continues to make a distinction between terrorism and liberation
movements, which he said he will continue to support.
   He did not elaborate. In the past, Gadhafi has described such
groups as the Irish Republican Army as ``liberation movements''
rather than terrorists.
   The U.S. State Department said Thursday that Gadhafi was still
supplying funds, weapons, safe havens and training facilities to
such groups as the Japanese Red Army, the IRA and the Popular Front
for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command.
   In addition, the State Department said the Palestinian group
Fatah Revolutionary Council led by Abu Nidal still had headquarters
in Tripoli, the Libyan capital.
