<FIRST>r w AM-ChinooksGrounded     10-27 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chinooks Grounded,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Problem Grounds Most CH-47D Helicopters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army is grounding most of its CH-47D
Chinook transport helicopters again because of a new problem with
transmission oil cooling fans, the Army announced Friday evening.
   Only eight days earlier, the helicopters affected _ 211 of the
264 in the fleet _ had been cleared to fly after another fan
problem was fixed.
   The fleet was grounded in August as a precaution while fan
failures were studied.
   The Army's Aviation Systems Command and the manufacturer, Boeing
Helicopter Co., determined that vibration most probably was causing
the fans to fail. The 211 machines that had not had failures were
given the green light to fly again on Oct. 19, provided that
modifications had been made, while studies continued on the 53
whose fans had failed.
   During inspection of the first craft to be modified, however, a
new problem was found in the lubrication of the fan shaft spline,
said the Army statement.
   The St. Louis-based Aviation Systems Command and the
manufacturer are now working on the lubrication problem in the 211
newly grounded helicopters and will check the 53 that had not been
cleared to fly, the Army said.
</TEXT>
