<FIRST>r a AM-StealthPlanes     10-27 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stealth Planes,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Chief of Staff Says Stealth Fighter Will Be Unveiled Soon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The radar-evading top-secret stealth fighter
will be shown to the public fairly soon, said a top Air Force
official on Friday.
   Gen. Larry D. Welch, the Air Force chief of staff, also said his
service arm will continue to modernize its fleet to respond to a
Soviet military capability undiminished by recent political changes
in Moscow.
   The Defense Department will decide shortly when to declassify
the F-117A stealth fighter, Welch said. Although the plane has been
flying for eight years, only two official pictures have been
released, one of them a drawing.
   ``Certainly at some point you'll have an opportunity to come and
take a closer look at it. I would think fairly soon,'' he said.
   Based at the Tonopah Test Range Airfield in Nevada, the jets are
carefully screened from public view. At least 52 F-117As have been
delivered.
   Welch insisted the existing fighter and bomber fleet could not
be upgraded to stealth capability to counter increasingly
sophisticated Soviet air defenses.
   Welch spoke to reporters before addressing a meeting of the Air
Force Association.
   The bat-winged B-2 stealth bomber, which was displayed to the
public in its maiden flight in July, and its fighter counterpart,
the F-117A, use sophisticated anti-radar technology.
   Welch said he was optimistic the B-2 stealth bomber, built by
Northrop Corp., will be deployed, despite congressional objections
to the estimated $70.5 billion it will cost to build a projected
fleet of 132 aircraft.
   ``I think there's no question that the B-2 program will go,''
Welch said. ``The issue is what will be the pace over the next two
years.''
   He acknowledged political and budget considerations left open
how many bombers ultimately will be built.
   ``For any one of us to try and predict at this point in time how
we're going to feel about the size of the bomber force four or five
years from now is kind of a futile exercise,'' he said.
</TEXT>
