<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Czech     10-27 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Czech,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Foreign Minister Upholds 1968 Invasion of Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union supports the Czechoslovak
leaders who insist that the Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia
in 1968 was proper, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
said Friday.
   ``We may only change our appraisal of those developments from
the present day perspective by a joint decision (with
Czechoslovaia)'' he said. ``It is a very complicated, delicate and
difficult problem.''
   Shevardnadze made the comments in an intervicew with Adam
Michnik, an editor of the pro-Solidarity newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza.
Michnik is a Solidarity deputy in the legislature and a former
political prisoner.
   He helped draft a resolution adopted by the Polish parliament
this August that condemned the invasion of Czechoslovakia by
members of the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact military alliance.
   Czechoslovakia's hard-line Communist Party leadership is
resisting reforms being pursued in Poland, Hungary and the Soviet
Union and opposes any revision of its stand that the invasion was
necessary.
   All of the Warsaw Pack members except Romania sent forces that
invaded Czechoslovakia Aug. 21, 1968, ousted the liberal Communist
Party government led by Alexander Dubcek and established a new
administration firmly within Soviet-bloc control.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's program of perestroika,
or restructuring, has been compared to the 1968 reforms in
Czechoslovakia but Soviet leaders have never said the invasion was
a mistake.
   Shevardnadze told Michnik, ``I deem it inadmissible for anyone
to impose his view of that problem (the invasion) on others. We
regard the appraisal made by the Czechoslovak Communist Party and
the Czechoslovak government as binding.''
   ``Czechoslovakia is a sovereign state and has an unquestionable
right to assess its own history independently,'' he added. ``The
appraisals passed by the Czechoslovak leaders then are not
different from their present ones and we respect them.''
</TEXT>
