<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-27 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow in Northwest; Still Warm Across East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell across the mountains of the Northwest on Friday while
most of the East continued to bask in unseasonably warm weather.
   In Idaho, 3 inches of snow fell during the morning in the
mountains east of Grangeville, and an inch of new snow covered the
ground at Sun Valley and Stanley.
   Winter storm warnings were posted into the night for the
mountains of east central and northern Idaho. As much as 10 inches
were expected at higher elevations, along with strong winds with
colder temperatures.
   A winter storm watch was posted for Friday night for the
northwest mountains of Wyoming, where up to a foot of snow was
expected. Advisories for rain and some snow were posted for the
Wasatch Mountains of Utah.
   Rain fell over the lower Gulf Coast of Texas and over north
central Texas, southwest Oklahoma, western Montana, the lower
elevations of western Idaho, and southwest Oregon. Showers and
occasional thunderstorms were over southeast Minnesota, central
Iowa, western Missouri, eastern Kansas, northeast Oklahoma,
southwest Texas and southeast New Mexico.
   Showers also dampened east central Florida, but skies were fair
and temperatures reached into the 70s in most other areas east of
the Mississippi.
   High temperature records for the date were set in Alpena, Mich.,
and Mansfield, Ohio, where it reached 73 degrees; Marquette, Mich.,
with 71, and Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., where a reading of 72 degrees
broke the mark of 71 set in 1947.
   This morning's low for the Lower 48 was 5 degrees at Gunnison,
Colo.
   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 32 degrees at Mccall,
Idaho, to 86 degrees at McAllen, Texas.
</TEXT>
