<FIRST>u i AM-Philippines-Marcos     10-27 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Marcos,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Return of Marcos Body and Family Members</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court refused Friday to
overturn the ban on allowing Ferdinand Marcos' body to be returned
to the Philippines.
   The ruling appeared to close the last legal move to allow the
former president to be buried in his homeland. But a pro-Marcos
lawyer said he would study the possibility of other legal maneuvers
to allow Marcos' widow, Imelda, and their three children to return
from exile.
   Mrs. Aquino praised the court decision.
   ``Let us now concentrate on solving the remaining problems of
our nation and together work for development and economic growth as
one people bearing one vision for the common good,'' she said.
   Chief Justice Marcelo Fernan told reporters the court ruled 8-7
to reject a petition filed by Marcos supporters Oct. 2 asking that
his body and his immediate family be allowed to return from Hawaii,
where Marcos died in exile Sept. 28.
   Mrs. Aquino banned the Marcoses, citing threats to national
security. Marcos was entombed in Hawaii Oct. 15 in what the family
said was a temporary burial.
   ``The threats to the government, to which the return of the
Marcoses has been viewed to provide a catalytic effect, have not
been shown to have ceased,'' the eight justices said in the
majority opinion.
   They cited recent statements by Marcos' widow, Imelda, that her
husband remained the legitimate president of the Philippines until
his death.
   In the dissenting opinion, Justice Abraham Sarmiento said the
threat allegedly posed by the Marcoses ``is the realm of
conjecture, speculation and imagination.''
   ``It's very unfortunate that the government missed a very rare
chance for reconciling our people,'' said Rolando Abadilla, vice
governor of Ilocos Norte province and a Marcos supporter.
   Abadilla said Marcos' fellow northerners were angry at the court
decision, and some of the women were shouting in the Tagalog
language, ``patayin si Cory!'' or ``kill Cory!''
   Former Solicitor Gen. Estelito Mendoza, one of the lawyers who
filed the petition for the Marcoses, said he will study new legal
strategies to lift the ban on Mrs. Marcos, Ferdinand Jr., and
daughters Irene Araneta and Imee Manotoc.
   ``The decision makes no mention whatsoever of why they are not
allowed to return to the country,'' Mendoza said.
   Lawyer Rafael Recto, another prominent Marcos supporter, said it
was unlikely the ban would be relaxed.
   ``There is no more hope for President Marcos and the family of
President Marcos to return here as long as the Aquino government is
here,'' Recto said. ``And Mrs. Aquino will never change her mind.
They are afraid of the living, and they are also afraid of the
dead.''
   The Aquino government has accused Marcos, his wife and hundreds
of associates of stealing up to $10 billion in public funds.
   In October 1988, a U.S. grand jury indicted the Marcoses on
racketeering charges in the alleged embezzlement. Mrs. Marcos is to
stand trial in New York in March.
   On Tuesday, about 200 Marcos supporters began a 250-mile march
from Ilocos Norte province to Manila to demand his body's return.
   Police said the group had reached La Union province, 150 miles
north of Manila, on Friday and chanted ``Cory is afraid of ghosts''
as it marched through towns.

</TEXT>
