<FIRST>u i AM-Netherlands-Blast 1stLd-Writethru a0793 10-27 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Netherlands-Blast, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0793,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Explosions at Buildings Housing Spanish Firms</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with police report, details. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buildings housing the Spanish
Trade Mission and Spanish Labor Bureau were damaged by bombs Friday
night and a passerby suffered cuts from flying glass in the second
blast, police reported.
   On Tuesday a bomb destroyed the car of Spanish Consul General
Gil Catalina. There were no injuries in that attack.
   No individual or group has claimed responsibility for the
bombings but Dutch newspapers speculated they were carried out by
terrorists of the ETA Basque separatist organization. ETA
guerrillas have been fighting for years for autonomy for the Basque
provinces in northern Spain.
   Police spokesman Nico Laterveer said the first explosion Friday
occurred at 10:45 p.m. at the Spanish Trade Mission and the second
blast came minutes later at the building of the Spanish Labor
Bureau, about two blocks away.
   The passerby was injured in the Labor Bureau bombing.
   Laterveer said that in both cases explosive devices apparently
were thrown through windows into the buildings.
   The explosion started a fire in the Trade Mission that was
quickly extinguished, he added.
   Police increased security near all Spanish government buildings
in this diplomatic capital after Tuesday's bombing.
   The Spanish Embassy issued a statement Wednesday saying no
threats had been received.
   The initials ETA stand for Basque Land and Liberty in the Basque
language.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
