<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 2219EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Burma     10-27 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports 1,087 Detained for Anti-Government Actions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government spokesman said Friday that
1,087 people have been detained for ``disruptive activities'' since
army commander Gen. Saw Maung seized power in September 1988.
   Western diplomatic sources said the number of political
prisoners is much higher.
   Col. Than Tun told a weekly news briefing that the figure of
1,087 detentions since the Sept. 18, 1988, coup did not include
common criminals.
   Saw Maung has ruled by martial law since the coup.
   Some Rangoon-based Western diplomats, contacted by telephone,
estimated the government had detained several thousand people since
it intensified its crackdown on dissidents in July. The diplomats,
speaking with the condition of anonymity, said they did not have
specific figures.
   A week ago a government spokesman said civilian courts and
military tribunals had sentenced 100 people to death in the past
three months for various crimes. He said 24 of the defendants were
convicted by military courts set up to deal with martial-law
violations.
   The diplomats said Burma's leading opposition group, the
National League for Democracy, has been hardest hit by the
political suppression.
   On July 20 the government put league chairman Tin Oo and general
secretary Aung San Suu Kyi under house arrest on charges of
subversion.
   The government allowed the formation of some 200 political
parties after it announced plans to hold multiparty elections next
May _ the first such elections in Burma for a quarter of a century.
   But the opposition ``has very little opportunity to talk or to
organize'' because of the crackdown on dissent, one of the
diplomats said, and many of the parties are not active.
   The military junta has said it will not support any party in the
campaign but the diplomats said it obviously favors the
pro-military National Unity Party, successor to the Burma Socialist
Program Party that ruled from 1962-88.
   Two other groups, the League For Democracy and Peace led by
former Prime Minister Nu and the Union National Democracy Party
headed by Aung Gyi, apparently are more free to operate than the
National League for Democracy, the diplomats said.
</TEXT>
