<FIRST>r a AM-JamieFiske     10-27 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jamie Fiske,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transplant Recipient Going Home to Massachusetts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jamie Fiske, whose 1982 liver transplant
helped shape the nation's organ transplant policy, is going home in
time for Halloween after recovering from spleen removal surgery, a
hospital spokeswoman said Friday.
   The 7-year-old and her mother, Marilyn, are scheduled to fly
home Saturday to East Bridgewater, Mass., said Mary Stanik,
spokeswoman for the University of Minnesota Hospital.
   ``She has been just great for two weeks'' since being readmitted
to the hospital after suffering internal bleeding, Stanik said.
   Jamie was admitted on Oct. 5 after suffering three bouts of
internal bleeding within a month. Doctors removed Jamie's spleen,
which doctors said was seven or eight times its normal size.
   The day after she left the hospital, however, Jamie suffered
more internal bleeding and was readmitted. Stanik said Jamie has
had no more bleeding since then.
   Charles Fiske said his daughter often asked if she would be home
in time for Halloween, her favorite holiday. She plans to dress as
the Queen of Hearts.
   Jamie was born Nov. 26, 1981, with biliary atresia, a condition
in which the liver's bile ducts are blocked. Months later, the
Fiskes learned only a liver transplant could save her life.
   In 1982, Fiske made an emotional appeal for a donor during a
convention at the American Academy of Pediatricians. A few days
later, a Utah family offered to donate the liver of their
11-month-old son, who was killed in an accident.
   Jamie's case raised questions about the procedures for determing
who should receive organ transplants and the properiety of awarding
organs on the basis of publicity. One result was the National
Transplant Act, which created a national computer system that
matches donors to recipients.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
