<FIRST>r a AM-Abortion-Illinois     10-27 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Illinois,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Opponents Give Up Legislative Fight for Fall Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS CONRAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abortion opponents Friday dropped
efforts to put proposed abortion restrictions before the General
Assembly this fall but pledged to renew their efforts in the spring.
   Ralph Rivera, chairman of the Illinois Pro-Life Coalition, said
there appears to be no chance of getting the bill through the House
Rules Committee, which blocked the measure by a one-vote margin
earlier this month.
   ``As of this time, we haven't been able to get the 10th vote
based on the makeup of the committee,'' Rivera said.
   The decision likely postpones any action on abortion legislation
until the General Assembly's spring session, which begins in early
April.
   Gary LaPaille, chief of staff to House Speaker Michael Madigan,
confirmed that the measure would not be scheduled for consideration
in the Rules Committee this week, the last scheduled week of the
fall session.
   The proposal, drafted to mirror Missouri restrictions upheld by
the U.S. Supreme Court in July, would require doctors to determine
the viability of any fetus believed to be 20 weeks old or older
before performing an abortion.
   It also would require a second physician to be present at the
abortion of any fetus determined to be viable, and would bar public
employees and public facilities from being involved in abortions.
   Pam Sutherland, executive director of Planned
Parenthood-Illinois, said the announcement was a clear signal
lawmakers had responded to lobbying by abortion rights supporters.
   ``They heard from a lot of people,'' she said.
   Rivera said anti-abortion groups would work to defeat
abortion-rights lawmakers in the statewide primary in March.
   ``We're going to be working very strongly to secure more votes _
not just in the committee, but the General Assembly as a whole,''
he said. ``Those who haven't been with us we are going to have to
replace if we can.''
   Ms. Sutherland said pro-choice groups are prepared to work
actively on behalf of their candidates as well.
   ``My reaction is, isn't it wonderful that Illinois families
don't have to worry about this this fall, but they will later this
spring,'' she said.
</TEXT>
