<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 2318EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Baker-Speech 1stLd-Writethru   10-27 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker-Speech, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0663,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pessimistic Speech About Gorbachev By U.S. Expert Quashed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-8: ``The State,'' with grafs 7-11 bgng: ``In a,''
to give Baker and Quayle comments; picks up 9th graf pvs, now 12th graf:
``Baker frequently;'' drops now-redundant first name and title of Quayle
in 14th graf: ``Some other,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III blocked
a speech by a senior White House official that gave a pessimistic
assessment of Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's prospects of
revamping the Soviet economy, the White House said Friday.
   On a flight to Costa Rica, White House Press Secretary Marlin
Fitzwater acknowledged there were various opinions about
Gorbachev's prospects within the Bush administration.
   But, Fitzwater said, even with opinions ``all over the lot''
about the future of perestroika, ``the point is we want it to
endure.''
   The White House spokesman added: ``That's the president's
policy.''
   The speech had been scheduled by Robert M. Gates, the deputy
national security adviser. The New York Times gave the first
account of his muzzling.
   Fitzwater told reporters aboard Air Force One as President Bush
headed for a hemisphere summit meeting in San Jose: ``It's not
really a question of policy. It's a question of analysis and
interpretation of events that the State Department felt was better
left unsaid at this point.''
   In a San Jose news conference, Baker said ``there is no division
of opinion whatsoever about policy.''
   ``I suggested the timing was not the very best'' for Gates'
speech, he said, coming soon after two Baker speeches sounding a
very positive tone toward the Soviets and a speech by Vice
President Dan Quayle that Baker said he had been reported as
harder-line than was really the case.
   ``This is strictly a question of timing,'' Baker said.
   ``This speech dealt with the durabilty of reforms, not the
desirability of the reforms. It did not deal with the policy
question _ Do we, should we, want to see perestroika succeed?''
   Quayle, in an interview on the Cable News Network ``John
Mclaughlin's One-on-One'' show taped Friday for weekend broadcast,
said, ``I think the decision was correct'' to stop the Gates'
speech.
   Baker frequently has wished Gorbachev well in his reconstruction
effort. But except for offering some undefined technical advice,
the secretary of state has stressed it was up to the Soviets to
determine their future.
   Gates, a former deputy director of the Central Intelligence
Agency, had been scheduled to speak to the National Collegiate
Security Conference in Bethesda, Md., a student seminar.
   Some other officials of the Bush administration, including
Quayle, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and Deputy Secretary of State
Lawrence Eagleburger, have registered public skepticism about
Gorbachev's prospects.
   Baker, whose top aides initially described Gorbachev as mostly
deft at public relations and adapting U.S. ideas on arms control,
has gradually warmed to the Soviet leader's uphill campaign to
change the Soviet system.
   Gates, in a speech last year, said Gorbachev had ``not really
changed'' the Soviet pattern. ``Russian and Soviet history caution
us to be skeptical and cautious,'' the then-CIA official said.
   The speech disturbed George P. Shultz, who was then secretary of
state. According to a knowledgeable U.S. official, Shultz
complained to Gates after it was delivered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
