<DOCNO> AP891027-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0105EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DrugPoll     10-27 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Poll,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: Kids Would More Likely Heed Parents' Advice if Past Use Admitted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighty-six percent of children say they'd be more
likely to listen to parents' advice about drugs if parents were
honest about their own drug use, according to a nationwide survey
released Thursday.
   Ninety-seven percent of the 500 parents polled said they discuss
drugs with their children, but 70 percent agreed most parents are
ill-equipped for such talks.
   Yet 95 percent of both parents and children reported a
``positive impact'' from the talks, which was not defined.
Eighty-nine percent of the 500 children surveyed said they had
discussed drugs with their parents.
   The survey was conducted by The Gallup Organization for Waste
Management Inc., the world's largest waste handler.
   The random interviews involved parents of children 8 to 17 years
old and children 10 to 17 years old. The survey had a margin of
error of plus or minus six percentage points, Gallup said.
   ``Talking can be the most important element to avoiding drug
problems,'' said Dr. Martin Goldstein, a child psychologist at
Chicago Lakeshore Hospital. ``But God knows, it's more than telling
kids to `Just say no.'''
   If all such efforts were successful, ``I don't think we'd have
as many teens in crisis as we do,'' Goldstein said.
   The survey said 66 million Americans have tried drugs and that
many parents don't know whether to acknowledge their own use while
discouraging their children from it.
   But most children surveyed agreed at least somewhat that ``if
your parents told you that they had used drugs in the past, you
would be more likely to listen to what they have to say.''
   ``If the message is, `I had a problem and I got help,' it's very
helpful because it teaches kids there are solutions,'' Goldstein
said. ``But it's just hypocritical if they say, `Do as I say, not
as I do.'''
   George Gallup Jr., co-chairman of the polling company, said he
was surprised so many parents had talked to their children about
drugs.
   ``The good part of all this is that it may be opening up deeper
channels for communication between parents and children,'' Gallup
said in a telephone interview after a Chicago news conference
Thursday.
   Waste Management, based in suburban Oak Brook, said it
commissioned the study partly because some job applicants were
failing drug-screening tests. An estimated 700 failed this year out
of a total of 10,000 applicants.
   ``In my view, an alarming number of employees are failing these
tests,'' company Chairman Dean L. Buntrock said in a telephone
interview Wednesday.
   ``We're aimed at children because that's where we can make the
greatest impact with education at a vulnerable age,'' he said.
``Time goes fast, and very quickly they'll become part of the labor
force in this country.''
   The company has produced a videotape, available free through
schools and some video stores, to encourage discussions between
parents and children.
   The Gallup survey also found:
   _ Fifty-eight percent of the children surveyed felt they knew
more about drugs than their parents, while 40 percent of parents
felt they were better informed.
   _ Both parents and children believe drug education should have
begun sooner in their case. Parents suggested it start when
children are 5{; the youngsters suggested 8{.
   _ Nearly 75 percent of parents agreed that ``it doesn't matter
what you say, some kids will have drug problems anyway.''
   _ Twenty-two percent of all children and 34 percent of 10- and
11-year-olds agreed with the statement, ``My parents don't have
time to talk to me about drugs.'' Fourteen percent of parents said
their children don't have time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
