<FIRST>r a AM-LandlordFine     10-27 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Landlord Fine,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Landlord Pays $700 Discrimination Fine Under Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landlord accused of discrimination for
denying housing to an unmarried couple paid a $700 fine under
protest Friday, but said he would take his case to the U.S. Supreme
Court if necessary.
   Layle French, 33, of Marshall, and his attorney James Anderson
delivered the money in $1 bills to the office of Attorney General
Hubert Humphrey III.
   ``I'm being force to allow people, who in my opinion are living
in sin, on my property,'' said French.
   On June 7, French was fined $1,048 by an administrative law
judge who held that French violated the state's anti-discrimination
law when he reneged on an agreement to rent his former house to Sue
Parsons. She said she intended to live in the house with her fiance
and French decided it would violate his religious beliefs to rent
to the couple before they were married.
   French said he willingly paid $348 in compensatory damages
earlier because he broke a verbal contract to rent the house to
Parsons. He said the $700 to pay the civil penalty was raised in
individual contributions of $1 each.
