<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Election     10-27 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Election,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frontrunner Holds Large Lead in Presidential Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fernando Collor de Mello held a
2-to-1 lead over his closest rival three weeks before the
presidential election, according to a poll published Friday.
   However, support rating for the right-of-center candidate
dropped from 45 percent in early September to 29.3 percent by the
first week of October, according to the poll by the Gallup
institute, the daily O Globo reported.
   On Nov. 15, 82 million Brazilians are to choose a successor to
President Jose Sarney for a five-year term, the first popular vote
for president since 1960. Free elections were banned during a
1964-1985 right-wing military regime.
   If no candidate wins a majority, the two top vote-getters will
face each other in a runoff in December.
   For the poll, Gallup questioned 4,922 people in 226 cities
between Oct. 18-25 across this nation of 145 million. Surveyors
interviewed people at random in the street and their homes. The
margin of error was 3 percent.
   Left-wing populist Leonel Brizola, a former governor of two
states, was in second place with 13.7 percent support, roughly what
he polled a month ago, according to the survey.
   Rep. Luis Inacio Lula da Silva of the radical-left Workers'
Party polled 12.4 percent. Sen. Mario Covas of the left-of-center
Brazilian Social Democratic Party received the support of 8.2
percent of those surveyed.
   Eight percent of voters were unsure of who they would vote for
and 3.5 percent said they would cast blank ballots.
   Collor de Mello, of the National Reconstruction Party, has held
a large lead in the polls since April. His image as a political
``outsider'' and promises to fight corruption won him national
appeal.
   But analysts say charges of corruption during his tenure as
governor of Alagoas state caused Collor de Mello's popularity to
slip.
</TEXT>
