<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 2307EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-FreewayCollapse     10-27 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Freeway Collapse,450</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Engineers this summer discovered and
were moving to fix a seismic design flaw on three San Francisco
double-decker freeways _ a flaw that scientists believe caused the
deadly collapse of a similar double-decker, a top state engineer
acknowledged Friday.
   Oakland's Interstate 880 was overlooked, despite the fact that
it was the oldest of five such double-decker freeways in Northern
California, because ``nobody in the Department'' of Transportation
remembered until after last week's earthquake that I-880 might also
share the flaw in its upper support column ``hinges,'' Caltrans
chief structural engineer Jim Roberts said.
   Two scientific teams from the Universities of California at
Berkeley and San Diego have tentatively decided that the
``hinges,'' or joints, sheared off during the quake, permitted
I-880's upper deck to slam down, killing more than three dozen
motorists on the lower deck.
   Would the repair planned for San Francisco's double-deckers have
prevented Oakland's I-880 collapse? Roberts was asked during a
daily press briefing.
   ``The answer, I believe, is affirmative,'' he said. ``I think it
would have gone a long way.''
   But, Roberts said, even if I-880 had been on the list for
repair, it would not have been done prior to Oct. 17.
   Hinge repairs on the other three will be expedited following the
I-880 collapse, he said. The three, the Embarcadero, the China
Basin, and the Central viaducts, all were damaged in the quake and
are temporarily closed.
   Engineers discovered the hinge flaw in the Embarcadero Viaduct
during an August review on whether it more earthquake-proofing
work, Roberts said. He confirmed the contents of an Aug. 21
internal memorandum brought to his attention Thursday.
   The memo, from one of his engineers to another, turned up in a
flood of departmental documents turned over to the news media this
week.
   Roberts, who said Thursday he was not aware of the memo and
questioned its acccuracy. On Friday, he confirmed the memo's
statement that at his request, the other two San Francisco viaducts
would be added to the list because state engineers recalled that
they too contained the flaw.
   Asked how I-880 could be overlooked, Roberts said, ``Maybe it
was the lack of foresight.'' And later he said, ``That's
hindsight.''
   Roberts also acknowledged that repair on the three was not
awaiting development of ``technology'' to strengthen
``multicolumn'' bridges, despite his and other Caltrans' officials'
assertions to the contrary earlier this week.
   While this remains the case with most of the state's 700
multicolumn structures that need column bolstering, engineers
planned to  a physician stabilizes a leg, he said.
   But the splints ``are not very good looking, and you're not
going to leave them up permanently,'' he said.
</TEXT>
