<FIRST>r a AM-NoahRobinson     10-27 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Noah Robinson,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Half Brother of Jesse Jackson Charged in Murder, Drug and Fraud Scheme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Noah Robinson, the half brother of Jesse Jackson,
was charged Friday with hiring members of a gang to kill a business
associate, defrauding a restaurant chain and supplying narcotics to
the gang's drug operation.
   In addition, 65 top leaders and members of the El Rukn street
gang were indicted on charges including racketeering, murdering 20
people, attempting to kill seven others, witness intimidation,
kidnapping and obstruction of justice, U.S. Attorney Anton R.
Valukas announced at a news conference.
   The El Rukns were charged with controlling a major part of
Chicago's drug market over the last 24 years. The indictment also
charged five Robinson associates with fraud, racketeering and
conspiracy.
   A number of El Rukns also were charged with racketeering and
traveling across states to acquire an M-72 Series Light Anti-Tank
Weapon, known as a LAW rocket, to carry out terrorism activities in
the United States for the government of Libya.
   ``The El Rukns developed from a street gang into a paramilitary
organization which acquired money and power ... (through) murder,
narcotics distribution, terrorism, robbery, extortion,
intimidation, fraud, bribery, kidnapping and obstruction of
justice,'' Valukas said.
   The arrests could help solve up to 50 unsolved slayings dating
to the late 1960s, said Dot Koester, spokewoman for the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms in Washington.
   Robinson, 45, was arrested at his South Side home Friday,
Valukas said. If convicted, he could be sentenced to 249 years in
prison.
   Robinson and Jackson, a Democratic candidate for president in
1984 and 1988, have the same father, but Jackson has described
their relationship as strained.
   Robinson's associates face an average of 160 years in prison if
convicted. The El Rukns face anywhere from four years to life in
prison.
   The indictment charged that Robinson sold heroin and cocaine to
a drug operation that controlled hundreds of markets in Chicago and
Milwaukee and had ties to several states including New York, South
Carolina, Florida, Michigan, Texas, Wisconsin and Mississippi.
   The drug operation netted millions of dollars in profits,
Valukas said.
   Robinson is charged with paying El Rukn leader Jeff Fort $10,000
to kill business associate Robert Aulston in 1985. It also alleges
that Robinson offered $10,000 to kill Leroy ``Hambone'' Barber in
Greenville, S.C.
   Barber was killed Jan. 3, 1986. Robinson was convicted and
sentenced earlier this year to 10 years in prison in connection
with the murder-for-hire of a witness to the Barber killing. He is
free on a $1.1 million bond pending an appeal.
   Fort is serving 155 years in a federal prison on a 1988
conviction for offering to commit terrorism for Libya. Four other
gang members also were convicted of conspiracy to commit terrorism
and conspiracy to violate federal firearms and explosives laws.
   Robinson and five associates also were charged with skimming
$650,000 from the profits of three Wendy's International Inc.
restaurants on Chicago's South Side through the management company
they controlled.
   Seventeen of the El Rukns and the five Robinson associates
charged were in custody. The remaining defendants were being sought
in Milwaukee, Minneapolis, South Carolina, Ohio and New York,
Valukas said.
</TEXT>
