<FIRST>a i PM-Brazil-Leftists Adv01   10-27 0869</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil-Leftists, Adv 01,0894</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PM Wed Nov. 1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rise of Leftist Candidates Worries Brazilian Business Elite</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds Retransmitting to restore dropped release line</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<UNK>By STAN LEHMAN ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist candidates have gained
popularity in the campaign for Brazil's presidential election Nov.
15 and conservatives and some top businessmen are voicing concerns.
   The conservative, pro-business candidate Fernando Collor de
Mello, the front-runner in the polls, has slipped from a high of 44
percent in August to 31 percent in late October, according to a
survey by the Brazilian Institute of Public Opinion and Statistics.
   At the same time, pollsters have recorded a sharp rise for Luis
Inacio Lula da Silva, a former labor union president and candidate
of the radical Workers Party, and a lesser one for Leonel Brizola,
a veteran populist of the center-left Democratic Labor Party.
   The institute's poll gave Lula da Silva 15 percent in late
October, up from 5 percent in August, and Brizola 14 percent, up
from 13 percent. Other private surveys had similar figures.
   Their gains have strengthened the possibility of a runoff in
December between the two top vote-getters _ most likely Collor de
Mello on one side and either Lula da Silva or Brizola on the other.
A runoff is called for if no candidate wins a majority Nov. 15.
   The long-outlawed Brazilian Communist Party is in the race for
the first time since 1945 but its candidate, Roberto Freire, has
only 1 percent of the vote in polls.
   The bearded, 44-year-old Lula da Silva _ popularly known simply
as Lula, a nickname he legally made part of his formal name before
the campaign _ most frightens many of the businessmen and
conservatives about the outcome of Brazil's first direct
presidential election in 29 years.
   Not all businessmen are as concerned, however, as those such as
Mario Amato, president of the Federation of Industries of the
sState of Sao Paulo.
   ``If Lula takes office there will be chaos in the country,''
Amato said in a comment typical for those expressing the most
concern.
   He predicted capital flight would increase and ``800,000
businessmen will flee the country if Lula becomes president.''
   Edson Vaz Musa, president of the Brazilian subsidiary of Rhodia,
the French chemical and textile company, differed with that outlook
in an interview published by the Jornal da Tarde newspaper.
   ``Brazil will continue to exist and businessmen and government
will have to adjust to a new reality,'' he was quoted as saying.
``This has happened in other countries, such as France, and their
economies were not destroyed.''
   In a television debate, Lula called Amato's statement an
``imbecility.'' He said ``productive capitalism'' would be welcome
in a Workers Party administration but not ``speculative
capitalism.''
   In the campaign, Lula has promised that if elected he will
sharply raise workers' salaries and limit profits, nationalize
banks, expropriate big ranches and farms for poor peasants, suspend
payment of Brazil's $110 billion foreign debt and restrict profit
remittances by multinational companies.
   Brizola, a former governor of Rio de Janeiro state who spent 15
years in exile during Brazil's 1964-1985 right-wing military
regime, favors what he describes as a European-style socialism. But
he also proposes expropriation of some private companies and
non-payment of the foreign debt, much of which is owed to U.S.
banks.
   ``I'll simply show up there and say, `Look, our people don't
want to pay any more,'' Brizola told a recent rally.
   Right-wing candidates have sought to capitalize on fears of a
leftist victory.
   ``This is also an ideological election,'' said Paulo Maluf of
the rightist Social Democratic Party. ``We must repudiate communism
and candidates like Leonel Brizola and Lula, who are supported by
communists.''
   Jose Alvaro Moises, a political scientist at the University of
Sao Paulo, disputes contentions such as Maluf's.
   He said in an interview such fears are ``unfounded and
exaggerated, because Lula and his party are not naive enough to
want to destroy the capitalist system.''
   ``He has made it clear that what he wants is to correct the
distortions that exist in Brazilian capitalism _ distortions that
have led to an extremely unfair distribution of income, low
salaries and an almost total lack of social priorities such as
health, education, housing and transportation,'' Moises said.
   He maintained that Lula's rise in popularity is due to ``the
people's desire for a change, for something new, for a president
with no links to the corruption-filled political past of this
country.''
   Emerson Klapaz, president of a large plastic-products industry,
said, ``A possible Lula government will be different from the one
he has described in his campaign. He will have to tune into what is
happening in the rest of the world, especially in communist
nations.''
   If the choice comes down to Brizola or Lula, some businessmen
have said they would prefer Brizola.
   ``We could deal with Brizola because he defends capitalism and
free enterprise. Lula doesn't,'' said supermarket tycoon Joao
Carlos Paes Mendonca.
   Carlos Alberto de Oliveira, president of the Commercial
Association of the southern state of Parana, said Lula ``defends
communist ideas that are out-of-date and this makes him even more
dangerous than Brizola.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs Nov. 1</NOTE>
