<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1423EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv30   10-27 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 30,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Monday, Oct. 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>Is Greenspan Chasing Butterflies?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Is Alan Greenspan so intent on netting the
fluttering butterfly of inflation that he'll run off a cliff and
take the economy with him?
   That's one cartoonist's view of the Federal Reserve chairman,
whose pursuit of inflation is his No. 1 priority. In effect, he
told Congress that last week, saying he was even willing to endure
subpar economic growth for several years.
   Another view, however, depicts Greenspan as a patient economic
scientist, carefully laying a trap for the evil insect of inflation
that, unless killed, could spread a debilitating virus throughout
the economy.
   In between is probably the real Greenspan, a man who is indeed
willing to see the economy operate below its potential but who is
ready to suspend his efforts, temporarily of course, to avert any
economic calamity.
   If Greenspan is successful in lowering inflation to near zero by
the mid-1990s, as he seeks to do, the economy at that time quite
likely would be positioned for healthy growth. But the price would
be high.
   Some of that price already is becoming evident. While inflation
has been moderating, the weakened performance of American industry
is showing up in various statistics, most ominously in a
merchandise trade deficit.
   Inflation might be the No. 1 issue with the Fed chairman, but
closing that deficit is No. 1 with other groups, including some in
the White House. It had been declining, but shot back up in the
third quarter.
   That situation raises the question of whether a below-par
economy is an important cause of the trade problem.
   During the third quarter, for example, industrial production
slowed to a 2.8 percent gain, vs. 4.2 percent in the second
quarter. Could some of that lost production be equated with the
worsening export situation?
   The capacity utilization rate for manufacturing also has been
falling. Earlier this year it was feared that plants were operating
at an inflationary rate. No longer; the rate retreated to 83.7
percent in September, well below the mythical, and much disputed,
inflation-causing rate of 85 percent.
   An industrial slowdown means lost jobs. That impact is showing
up clearly in automotive industry layoffs, although the jobless
rate remains steady because of hiring in the service sector. A
continuation of the industrial slowdown, however, inevitably will
mean layoffs sufficient to push up the jobless rate.
   Corporate profits are declining too, and have been since the
first quarter of the year. That situation could force some
companies to rely more heavily on debt rather than internal
financing, putting upward pressure on interest rates.
   Inventories are rising. When inventories rise it can mean two
different things: one, that business is bullish and expects higher
sales, or two, sales are weakening and unsold goods are piling up.
In this instance, blame No. 2.
   Weaker corporate sales are bad news for the stock market too,
and that institution already is unsettled by its own shenanigans.
Incredible nosedives of late must be watched, lest one of them
trigger a financial collapse.
   Greenspan's pursuit of inflation, therefore, is not without
great costs and constant dangers. It might put a stronger
foundation beneath the economy in the mid-1990s, but in the
meantime it will take its toll.
   If that toll becomes more painful, the Greenspan course will
raise doubts, some of which might be expressed in a plea to suspend
the experiment and allow a little inflation in exchange for
additional growth.
   In the long run, and considering that politics inevitably butts
heads with economic theory, it could be the biggest threat of all
to the Fed chairman's scientific ideal of the near perfectly
stable, non-inflated economy.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Monday, Oct. 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
