<DOCNO> AP891027-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0802EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Children'sBooks Adv01   10-27 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Children's Books, Adv 01,0851</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday AMs, Nov. 1, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Chris Van Allsburg: An Imagination Running Wild</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BEZDEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chris Van Allsburg, who recently shared in one of
the largest advances ever paid for a children's book, didn't
hesitate when asked to cite an important influence on his work.
   ``Harold and the Purple Crayon,'' he announced with speed and
surety.
   It was upon reading that Crockett Johnson book as a child in
Grand Rapids, Mich., that Van Allsburg, one of America's most
successful children's book authors and illustrators, set sail on
his wild imaginings that have led in recent years to such works as
``Jumanji,'' ``The Wreck of the Zephyr,'' ``The Garden of Abdul
Gasazi'' and ``The Polar Express,'' which just sold its millionth
copy.
   His latest venture marks his first collaboration. He was paid
part of an $800,000 advance to do the illustrations for Mark
Helprin's ``Swan Lake'' (Houghton Mifflin, $19.95). Helprin and the
``packager'' who cut the deal also shared in the $800,000. The
80-page book was recently published.
   In this derivative of the Tchaikovsky ballet, Van Allsburg tried
to give his illustrations the look and flavor of a 19th century
picture book to accompany the story of an ill-fated prince and
princess.
   Helprin's rich, although sometimes strained, style, and Van
Allsburg's satiny portraits with a Far Eastern tinge largely make
for a nice fit.
   But most youngsters will need an adult to get them through the
work, marked by passages such as ``... the forest was in its own
way inviolable _ a domain of hearth smoke in unwavering columns
against a flawless blue sky, of mountains clad in wind-buffed ice,
of the thinnest air, of rivers running white and bursting with
oxygen.''
   Van Allsburg, an admirer of Helprin's New Yorker pieces and
especially his novel ``Winter's Tale,'' stumbled only once as he
tried for the first time to put pictures to someone else's script.
When he was called upon to supply a picture of the old emperor
reclining on pillows on the floor, Van Allsburg kept shaping the
pillows into the form of dogs.
   ``We talked and he said if I needed the dogs OK,'' Van Allsburg
said. ``The pillows just looked too much like dogs and I had to go
with the pitch.''
   The scene remains slightly imperfect; the text says the emperor
has a book beside him, but the illustration shows him reading it.
   The hardest part for Van Allsburg began when the book was
completed.
   Houghton Mifflin decided on an enormous first run of 275,000
copies, including book club printings. Van Allsburg was asked to
handle East Coast promotions and Helprin the West. That meant 25
days on the road.
   Van Allsburg, a soft-spoken and retiring man of 40 who says one
reason he teaches at the Rhode Island School of Design is to force
himself out of the studio, is not particularly fond of public
appearances.
   But he is most engaging, and likely to be a fine salesman.
   An encounter with him is like bumping into Peter Pan at the A&amp;P
and talking about the English poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge _ or
vice versa _ and the ways of the imagination.
   As a teacher, he forces students to stretch their imaginations
by such assignments as composing their own version of ``The Star
Spangled Banner'' and singing it to the class.
   As a writer and illustrator, he tries to fit the pieces of his
own wonder, sometimes in pastel, sometimes in pencil, sometimes in
pen and ink. ``Sometimes I actually see an image in my mind's eye
which is puzzling to me, and then the story comes from it as I try
to figure it out.
   ``My stories are a little like encountering a missing
illustration.''
   He avoids conventional story resolutions with the hope that
``you close the book but your mind stays engaged,'' thus prolonging
fantasy.
   ``Society encourages giving up those beliefs. But I'm in favor
of stretching them out,'' he says.
   About the child's trip to see Santa Claus in ``The Polar
Express,'' he says: ``If the mean age (of giving up the notion of
Santa Claus) is, say, 7 years, 9 months, I like to think that maybe
it (the book) pushed it back to 7 years, 10 months for some.''
   Santa Claus and the tooth fairy ``make the world have greater
potential.''
   His books are an open heart, at times whimsical, at times sad,
at times even perplexing. And even after 10 popular works in as
many years, an American Book Award and two Caldecott Medals, he has
set no pattern and has no idea of exactly where he is going.
   The most he can say about his next book is that ``I'm sort of
working on something.''
   Like Harold, who used his purple crayon to draw his way in and
out of many adventures.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Nov. 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891027-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1418EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-TickerTalk Adv30   10-27 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 30,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Oct. 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>Analysts Say Market Still Unsafe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the stock market staged a brisk rally right
after its scary slide on Oct. 13, most onlookers were relieved and
impressed. There evidently wasn't going to be a Crash of 1989 after
all.
   But that performance failed to reassure some Wall Street
analysts, who found almost as much cause for concern in the rebound
as they did in the drop.
   After the Dow Jones industrial average fell more than 190 points
on Friday the 13th, the optimists' rallying cries began almost
immediately.
   The selloff was an ``aberration,'' caused mainly by the
spreading realization that the mergers-and-buyouts boom of the past
several years was coming under increasing strains.
   The squeeze on takeover credit, furthermore, would ultimately
prove beneficial by restoring investors' attention to the
traditional values that make the stock market go, such as earnings
and dividend growth.
   Besides, everybody with memories of the Crash of 1987 had
learned that bargain-hunters in big market drops could be
handsomely rewarded when confidence was restored.
   While any or all of these points may be valid, the skeptics now
say, investors rushed to embrace them with an eagerness bordering
on unreality.
   ``Just because Monday, Oct. 16, wasn't a repeat of Black Monday
1987 doesn't mean that all is well,'' contends Joseph Feshbach,
technical analyst at Prudential-Bache Securities.
   ``This isn't the worst of all possible investment worlds, but it
certainly isn't the best.''
   Two years ago, Feshbach noted, ``pessimism abounded, and
pessimism proved wrong. Today, optimistic investors are comparing
1989 with 1987, although the fundamentals and the internals of the
market are very different this year from what they were two years
ago.''
   Those differences have been widely described as favorable for
the market outlook now. For instance, price-earnings ratios of
stocks are much lower now than the lofty levels they reached in the
summer of '87.
   Similarly, there appears much less danger now of an accelerating
economy that would prompt the Federal Reserve to tighten credit.
   But many analysts view the contrasts in sentiment between
October 1987 and October 1989 much differently.
   The Crash of '87 was almost universally viewed as a fearsome
event. Friday the 13th this October was dismissed by many as just a
brief dizzy spell.
   If the past is any guide, significant market declines don't end
in periods of eagerness to shop for bargains in stocks, but rather
when ``sentiment surrenders its enthusiasm and becomes scared,'' in
the words of Justin Mamis at Cowan &amp; Co.
   The 1989 selloff and its aftermath prompted Joseph Barthel,
technical analyst at Hopper Soliday &amp; Co., to recommend that
investors reduce their exposure to the stock market.
   ``The burden of proof that Friday, Oct. 13, was just a fluke
remains squarely on the shoulders of the bulls,'' he asserts.
   Whatever the eventual outcome, analysts who see the market's
recent antics in a negative light say the prevailing optimistic
view was self-contradictory.
   On the one hand, the selloff was described as unlike the '87
crash because it occurred in such different circumstances.
   On the other, it was embraced as a ``buying opportunity'' very
similar to what occurred two years before.
   Either one of those interpretations could turn out to be true,
the skeptics say, but not likely both.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Oct. 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891027-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0749EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-JaclynSmith Adv10-11   10-27 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Jaclyn Smith, Adv 10-11,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 10-11, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jaclyn Smith Deep in Money, Intrigue in ABC Mystery Series</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jaclyn Smith is up to her neck in money in
her new ABC mystery series ``Christine Cromwell'' _ old money, new
money and stolen money.
   She stars as a San Francisco investment counselor who keeps
getting involved in crimes in the show that begins this weekend on
``The ABC Saturday Mystery Movie.''
   ``It's a different feeling from the movies and miniseries I've
been doing,'' said Smith, whose last series was ``Charlie's
Angels'' in 1976-81.
   ``It's regular, but it's not every week. It's a character who
can change and develop and that I can put more of myself into. I've
been playing so many victims, so many emotional roles. This is much
more intellectual. The mysteries are quite complex. I have to read
the scripts twice to understand them, but I think the viewers will
find them easier to follow visually through the eyes of the
characters.''
   ``Christine Cromwell,'' along with the newly added ``Kojak,''
joins ``Columbo'' and ``B.L. Stryker'' in the rotating movie
series. It gives the mix a glamorous element and lighter mystery.
Peter Falk is the diamond-in-the-rough Columbo, Burt Reynolds is
the reluctant Florida private eye Stryker and Telly Savalas is back
as the tough, flashy detective Theo Kojak.
   Smith's show originally was called ``Amanda Vanderbilt.'' That
caused conflict because of a line of designer clothes, and it
became ``Christine Claiborne.'' Conflict arose again because of
another line of clothes and a fragrance. Wanting a name that
conveyed elegance, glamour and old money, everyone finally agreed
on ``Christine Cromwell.''
   ``It's about the charmed life of the very rich,'' said Smith.
``It's somewhat reminiscent of the movies of the 1930s. Christine
is from old money back East. She's very bright, involved in
charities, and works because she wants to. She has many qualities
and values that I admire.
   ``Celeste Holm plays my mother, who's been married seven times.
Each of my stepfathers has an expertise that I call on in solving
the cases. Mother's a kind of `Auntie Mame' type. My boss at the
investment firm is Ralph Bellamy.''
   Although she'll come up against the rich, they won't all be
refined. In one show, she deals with a coarse detective played by
Dennis Franz. That particular episode also marks one of the series'
few ventures into humor.
   Most of the stories will show that the rich not only get into
trouble, they also have more money with which to dig themselves in
deeper.
   ``I'm used to doing straight, serious roles,'' said Smith. ``The
role of the intellectual, and having to put across what she's
thinking and doing, is more difficult than an emotional role. It's
a great challenge. The memory work is extensive, having to say all
the legal background.
   ``This is also a long way from `Charlie's Angels.' That was very
tongue-in-cheek. This is much more real.''
   Since ``Charlie's Angels,'' Smith has starred in such movies as
``Escape From Bogen County,'' ``The Users,'' ``Jacqueline Bouvier
Kennedy,'' and most recently, NBC's ``Settle the Score.''
Miniseries include ``Rage of Angels,'' ``George Washington,''
``Rage of Angels II,'' ``Windmills of the Gods'' and ``The Bourne
Identity.''
   ``When I started the series, I thought, `I'm going to be away
from the children,''' she said. ``My kids have been to San
Francisco for some location filming. They've come to the set after
school. It's good for them to see that their mother works.''
   After completing ``The Bourne Identity,'' she took seven months
to devote time to her children, Gaston, 7, and Spencer Margaret,
who'll be 4 in December.
   ``This is a longer commitment than a movie or miniseries,'' she
said. ``I enjoy it. I work 12-hour days, but I'm home in time to
have dinner with the children, read them stories and put them to
bed.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 10-11</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891027-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1404EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-WalterMears Adv29   10-27 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv 29,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 29, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Earthquake Shakes Government Spending Limit, Too</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At first, the instinct was to wave it off, the
way a referee picks up the penalty flag he didn't intend to throw.
   But then Congress decided that the $2.85 billion appropriated
for disaster relief after the California earthquake should, after
all, count against the government's deficit quota, probably
starting next year, not now.
   The government tried to discipline itself with the law that
limits annual deficits, but it also can change laws. That amounts
to optional discipline.
   Rep. Bob Michel, the Republican leader, said the Gramm-Rudman
rules for deficit reduction are a disciplinary tool that shouldn't
be evaded. ``You don't discard it because it is inconvenient,'' he
said. ``It is supposed to be inconvenient.''
   There's a tendency to argue that some appropriations, like this
one, are just too important to be counted against a budget ceiling
that's already been reached and passed, because it makes them
harder to enact.
   And moves that provide budget leeway also serve the Republican
administration, which is determined to keep its barrier high
against new taxes. The White House said none will be necessary to
finance the disaster relief bill, the largest in history. The
second largest also passed this fall, $1.1 billion as a result of
Hurricane Hugo.
   Nobody questioned the decision to provide the money, but there
was ample House debate on how to count it. The Senate, in a vote
that is only advisory, said budget negotiators ought to cut other
programs by $1 billion, the amount of disaster relief money likely
to be spent this year.
   Californians were candid about their determination to get as
much as possible as quickly as possible, before the sense of crisis
eases.
   Later on, ``we'll be just another budgetary problem,'' said Rep.
Vic Fazio, D-Calif. He also said that the emergency appropriation
was little more than a down payment and that added funds probably
will be sought in the spring.
   The double disasters of hurricane and earthquake already are
another budgetary problem. The government is operating under
automatic spending cuts imposed two weeks ago to trim $16.1 billion
from projected spending. That's because Congress has not settled on
a measure to prune the projected deficit to no more than $110
billion for the year that began Oct. 1.
   And that was before the disaster appropriations.
   Hence the search for ways to keep the bill from adding to the
squeeze. As drafted for House action, the disaster appropriation
said the spending it provided would not be charged against the
Gramm-Rudman ceiling.
   That was fine with the White House, more interested in resisting
pressure for new taxes than in the fine print of the budget control
system. According to the administration, the earthquake money won't
affect the current deficit crunch because the deadline for dealing
with it has come and gone, without action.
   That would leave the extra spending to be counted next year
when, according to White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater,
``it's a whole other ballgame.'' It may be a more difficult
ballgame, since the deficit ceiling for that budget year will be
more stringent, only $64 billion unless Congress decides to ease it.
   That's not unlikely.
   ``Just as surely as we erect one barrier, we find a way around
it,'' complained Rep. Sylvio O. Conte, R-Mass., who got the
disaster appropriation amended so that it will have to be counted
against future Gramm-Rudman ceilings.
   He said the idea of pretending the earthquake spending wasn't
being added to the deficit was ``an escape hatch to fantasy land .
.. We spend it _ ha, ha, ha _ but it doesn't count, it's magic,
it's voodoo. And it's bogus.''
   There were counter-arguments that counting the disaster spending
against the limit is going to force cuts in other programs that
already are short of funds. ``Every nickel you are spending will
come out of some other program's hide, education, child care,
nutrition, the homeless, drugs, defense, you name it,'' said Rep.
Bob Traxler, D-Mich.
   Those are indeed difficult choices. The people running
government are supposed to make tough choices.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national
politics for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 29</NOTE>
