<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0811</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy shrugged off Hurricane Hugo
and the poorest trade performance in six years to grow at a
moderate 2.5 percent annual rate from July through September, the
Commerce Department reported.
   The department said Thursday that the increase in the gross
national product, the country's total output of goods and services,
was accompanied by a slowing of inflation to an annual rate of 2.9
percent, the slowest in three years, as both energy and food costs
moderated.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advisers to United Airlines' pilots and flight
attendants met to draft a new strategy following a failed buyout
bid, as leaders of the Machinists' union discussed ways to prevent
an outside takeover of United's parent, UAL Corp.
   The meetings Thursday could lead to a compromise among the
unions, whose cooperation is seen as the key to any restructuring
of UAL.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas S. Brady, who once
headed an investigation into the causes of the 1987 stock market
crash, told Congress that federal regulators need authority to halt
trading in future market emergencies.
   Brady also said Thursday his crash study may have
``overreacted'' in calling for a super-regulator to oversee all the
financial markets and that he had not formulated an opinion about
computerized program trading, which is often cited as a factor in
the 1987 crash.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's treasury chief,
Nigel Lawson, and her personal economic adviser both resigned in a
dramatic government upheaval during difficult economic times.
   Lawson quit his Cabinet post as chancellor of the exchequer
saying he could not work for Mrs. Thatcher unless she dropped her
adviser, Sir Alan Walters. Walters, who was visiting the United
States, resigned shortly afterward.
   The financial markets were shaken by the news Thursday and the
pound fell 3 cents against the dollar.
</TEXT>
