<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0215EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-StockBaskets Bjt   10-27 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stock Baskets, Bjt,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Baskets Get Off to Slow Start Amid Criticism of Program Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock dealers in New York and Chicago were slow
to warm to the latest innovation in program trading of stocks.
   But officials of the New York Stock Exchange and Chicago Board
Options Exchange said they were satisfied with the lackluster
first-day trading Thursday of so-called stock baskets, and
predicted the new products would become accepted over time.
   ``We had no real expectations of activity that we were aiming
for,'' said NYSE spokeswoman Sharon Gamsin. Her exchange traded
nine of the stock baskets Thursday.
   But critics said they had doubts about whether the baskets would
ever catch on. They cited bad publicity about program trading, a
strategy involving the simultaneous trading of a range of stocks
that has been criticized as worsening stock market volatility.
   ``All of the clients are telling us they don't like program
trading. We don't do it,'' said Brad Weeks, a senior vice president
at Donaldson Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp.
   The baskets essentially are portfolios that allow big investors
to buy or sell, in a single transaction, every stock in the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock index. That is aimed at investors who
want to bet on the direction of the overall stock market without
picking individual stocks.
   Investors bet on the overall market now mainly by trading
stock-index futures and options in the Chicago commodities markets.
   At the NYSE, nine baskets were traded Thursday at a price of a
little more than $5 million apiece. The Chicago options exchange
handled 14 trades of a cheaper version at about $1.7 million each.
   Trading began one day after the Securities and Exchange
Commission gave provisional six-month approval to the baskets.
   The NYSE, sensitive to bad publicity about program trading, said
the baskets were introduced in response to a recommendation of the
Brady Commission, which investigated the October 1987 stock market
crash.
   ``It's not something we designed to facilitate program
trading,'' Ms. Gamsin said.
   But one Brady Commission member, Robert Kirby, said he was
unimpressed with the innovation.
   ``The world needs another step toward the commoditization of
common stocks like it needs an addition to the national debt,''
said Kirby, chairman of Capital Guardian Trust Co. in Los Angeles.
   Trading proceeded smoothly albeit slowly at the New York and
Chicago exchanges except for a miware glitch in Nnor softew York,
several market makers and exchange officials said.
   The spread between bid and ask prices _ the difference between
what market makers will pay for a basket and what they will sell it
for _ was narrower than it would be if each of the 500 stocks were
bought separately, making the basket a more efficient way to
participate in the market, according to Matthew Celebuski, vice
president of futures and options strategy at PaineWebber Inc.
   The efficiency of the baskets eventually should attract big
investors such as pension funds and life insurance companies,
Celebuski predicted. NYSE officials agreed.
   ``We would hope that over time the nine baskets would become 20,
30, 50, etc.,'' said Donald Solodar, a senior vice president at the
exchange.
   The four firms making a market in the NYSE's version of the
market basket, which officially is known as the Exchange stock
portfolio, were PaineWebber, Morgan Stanley &amp; Co., First Boston
Corp. and Salomon Brothers Inc.
   PaineWebber's Celebuski said he believed basket trading would
slow the form of program trading known as index arbitrage by
keeping stocks and futures closer in line.
   The software glitch at the New York Stock Exchange prevented use
of a mechanism by which investors could sidestep the four
market-making firms and buy or sell a market basket by going
straight to the specialists who make markets in the 500 stocks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891027-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0709EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BeerWar Bjt   10-27 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Beer War, Bjt,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beer Getting Cheaper as Price War Heats Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A beer price war that's heating up across the
nation has turned heads on Wall Street, but the folks who ring up
the six-packs at the cash register aren't impressed.
   ``We've seen and heard these kinds of things over and over,''
said Don Cowan, a spokesman for the Dallas-based Southland Corp.,
which owns 7-Eleven, the nation's largest chain of convenience
stores.
   ``I think this is more like standard operating procedure,''
Cowan said Thursday.
   But the decision by Anheuser-Busch Cos. Inc., the world's
largest brewer, to match price cuts made by competitors in an
effort to shore up some declining markets did attract a great deal
of attention from the financial world.
   ``It's going to be flat-out war,'' said Julie Neimann, a
securities analyst for St. Louis-based Stifel Nicolaus Co.
   ``There has been a beer war in this country for the past 18
months, but we've really tried to stay above the fray. Now, we are
joining the fray,'' said Jerry Ritter, a vice president and chief
financial officer for St. Louis-based Anheuser-Busch.
   Talk of a beer price war was news to Miller Brewing Co., the
nation's second-largest brewer.
   ``Our pricing and Anheuser-Busch's have not been significantly
different this year,'' Susan Henderson, a spokeswoman for the
Milwaukee-based company, said Thursday.
   The Stroh Brewery Co. ranks third among domestic brewers,
followed by Adolph Coors Co. and the G. Heileman Brewing Co. Last
month, Coors said it signed an agreement in principle to acquire
most of the beer-related assets of Stroh Brewery.
   The new Anheuser-Busch policy is going to mean slightly lower
beer prices for consumers and fiercer competition for the nation's
beermakers, according to market analysts.
   ``The level of discounting in the beer business has been going
up for some time, but now Anheuser-Busch has said it's coming out
with both guns blazing,'' said Ben Steinman, executive editor of
Beer Marketer's Insights, a trade publication.
   It's too early to tell how much Anheuser-Busch's new policy is
going to push down prices in the premium beer category, but some
analysts estimate consumers will save about a quarter on a six-pack.
   Six-packs of Budweiser, Miller Genuine Draft and Coors generally
cost about $3.50, although all companies offer frequent sales that
drop the price below $3 in many areas of the country.
   Ritter said Anheuser-Busch decided to match price cuts by Miller
and Coors because consumers have been buying Budweiser and
Michelob, the two main Anheuser-Busch brands, at a slower rate in
the past few months.
   ``Sales had been growing between 3 and 4 percent, but now
they've slipped to a little below 3 percent. We decided it was time
to turn up the heat,'' said Ritter.
   Anheuser-Busch, which has been the country's leading brewer for
more than three decades, sells about 42 percent of the beer in the
United States. It hopes to boost that to 50 percent over the next
several years.
   The new pricing strategy is certainly going to accelerate that
growth, at the expense of the nation's other breweries, said Roy
Burry, an analyst at Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. in New York.
   The American beer industry has become much more competitive in
the 1980s because beer sales have been increasing only slightly and
per capita beer consumption has been going down.
   The stepped up competition has led to an increase in the number
of brands being sold by breweries and more promotion, advertising
and price cutting, analysts said.
   While Anheuser-Busch's new policy will be great for consumers,
advertising agencies and convenience stores, analysts say the
aggressive stance is going to hurt the rest of the industry, which
has been struggling.
   ``The big question is what's going to happen to Miller,'' Burry
said.
   Miller has been enjoying one of its best sales years ever. The
company sold more beer in August than it ever sold in any other
month, said Steve Forsyth, a Miller spokesman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
