<FIRST>r f PM-Import-ExportPrices     10-27 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Import-Export Prices,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Of Imported Goods Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prices Americans paid for imported goods
fell 1.3 percent during the summer, reflecting a stronger dollar
and falling energy costs, the government reported.
   The Labor Department said Thursday the price decline in the
third quarter was identical to a 1.3 percent decline in same period
a year ago. Falling oil costs played the major role in both price
decreases.
   In the latest quarter, energy costs fell by 7.4 percent while
imported food costs were down by 4.7 percent. The price of imported
chemical products fell by 2.2 percent.
   The decline in food costs was the fifth drop in the past six
quarters and marked the biggest decrease in three years. It was led
by a giant 38.6 percent decline in the price of coffee.
   The overall moderation in prices was aided by a stronger dollar,
which lowers the costs Americans must pay for imported products.
   On the export side, the price of American goods sold overseas
dropped by 0.7 percent in the third quarter, the biggest price
decline since a 1.2 percent fall in the third quarter of 1986.
   Labor Department analysts said that most of the decline stemmed
from a 4.2 percent drop in agricultural exports, reflecting lower
grain prices.
   Non-farm products edged down by 0.1 percent, the first decline
in this sector in more than three years.
   Allen Sinai, chief economist of the Boston Co., said that the
drop in non-farm export prices was unusual given the big rise in
the value of the dollar, which makes Americans goods more expensive
on overseas markets.
   He said U.S. manufacturers apparently are shaving profit margins
in an effort to hold onto foreign markets in the face of the rising
dollar.
   ``American companies are attempting to stay competitive in
overseas markets by lowering their break-even points by squeezing
profits and cutting back on costs rather than raising prices,''
Sinai said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
