<FIRST>r f PM-Pentagon-TV     10-27 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon-TV,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Agency Selects U.S. Contractors for Advanced Television</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency
has selected three more contractors for its $30 million program to
develop defense-related high-definition television technology.
   The Pentagon said Thursday the three contracting teams will
develop processor technology for HDTV displays.
   The teams are: David Sarnoff Research Center, Princeton, N.J.,
with Sun Microsystems Inc. of Mountain View, Calif., and Texas
Instruments Inc. of Dallas; Adams Russell Electronics of Waltham,
Mass., with Massachusetts Institute of Technology; and Qualcomm
Inc. of San Diego, Calif.
   Lt. Col. Mark Pullen, the deputy director of DARPA's Information
and Science Technology Office, said the development work would help
with military display systems and promote the development of U.S.
technology in high-definition TV.
   Previously, the Pentagon has selected five contractors to
develop HDTV receivers and displays. Four are working on projection
displays: NewCo Inc. of San Jose, Calif.; Raychem Corp. of Menlo
Park, Calif.; Texas Instruments; and Projectavision Inc. of New
York City.
   The fifth company, Photonics Technology Inc. of Northwood, Ohio,
is working on a plasma flat panel display similar to the liquid
crystal displays found on many watches and portable computers.
   Texas Instruments also is working on the plasma display
technology as a subcontractor to Photonics.
   NewCo has told the Pentagon it is working with Spectra Physics
Inc., while Raychem has listed the Xerox Corp. as a subcontractor.
Texas Instruments has listed the Sarnoff center as a subcontractor.
   Sarnoff, along with NBC and RCA, also is developing a
high-definition transmission system, as is MIT.
   The House has appropriated an additional $50 million to DARPA's
HDTV program for next year.
</TEXT>
