<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0230EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Airlines-Outlook Bjt   10-27 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airlines-Outlook, Bjt,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline Takeover Frenzy Should Continue Despite Leaner Times</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Though several highly publicized attempts to
take over major airlines failed recently and the industry is facing
leaner times, the wave of airline restructurings should continue,
airline officials and analysts say.
   Many airlines are predicting slimmer profits in coming months as
fuel prices rise and the economy slows. For the weaker players in
the increasingly competitive environment, the outlook is even
dimmer.
   On Thursday, Presidential Airways, a feeder carrier for United
Airlines, filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of
the bankruptcy laws. The move follows Chapter 11 filings by two
other airlines this year: strikebound Eastern Airlines in early
March and Braniff Inc. in late September, its second such filing in
seven years.
   Braniff said Thursday it had hired Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. to advise
it on a possible sale of the beleaguered airline.
   Airline fuel costs are up 20 percent to 25 percent over a year
ago, according to Edward Starkman, an industry analyst at
PaineWebber Inc.
   ``We're looking at a couple of tough quarters to come,'' he
said. ``The numbers have withered and died in the last couple of
weeks.''
   Al Frei, senior vice president of finance at America West
Airlines, says he expects passenger traffic overall to remain flat
or grow only slightly next year.
   ``We're beginning to see a softening,'' said Bruce Nobles,
president of Trump Shuttle, the former Eastern shuttle in the
Northeast that developer Donald Trump acquired this spring for $365
million. ``Business travel is tightening up a little bit. The
airlines tend to lead a recession and follow a recovery.''
   Nevertheless, analyst Starkman and others say, the weakness
won't have a chilling effect on takeover activity in the industry.
In fact, Starkman said, investors who were going after airlines
when their stocks were trading much higher now could ``see some
bargains out there.''
   ``The takeover activity is going to continue even in the face of
an uncertain, at best, stock market,'' Eastern President Phil Bakes
said in an interview.
   Bakes is a former attorney for the Civil Aeronautics Board who
had been influential in drawing up the 1978 law deregulating the
nation's airline industry. As one of the architects of
deregulation, he says he wasn't surprised by the pack of investors
bidding for major airlines _ only by how long it took them to make
their moves.
   The panic selling that rocked the stock market this month was
largely triggered by the breakdown of a $6.75 billion offer for
United Airlines parent UAL Corp. from its pilots and top managers.
And while UAL touched off the slide on Wall Street, its stock price
probably was the biggest casualty of the selloff.
   UAL stock has plummeted by more than 40 percent since Oct. 13,
when the pilot-management bid collapsed due to inadequate
financing. It closed at $170.75 a share Thursday on the New York
Stock Exchange, down sharply from $285.25 on Oct. 12.
   Other airline stocks _ which also had been lifted by the
takeover euphoria _ have followed suit.
   Another splashy airline deal, Trump's $7 billion proposal to buy
AMR Corp., parent of industry leader American Airlines, also was
called off.
   The failures come against a backdrop of growing anxiety in the
Bush administration and Congress over airline takeovers.
   Despite the loss of altitude, airlines remain hot properties
because of their enormous cash flows and asset values. Bakes points
out, for example, that healthy carriers like American and United
own several billions of dollars in equity in new aircraft they have
ordered.
   Some megadeals still seem to be going through _ notably an
investor group's acquisition of NWA Inc., parent of Northwest
Airlines, for $4 billion.
   And despite recent posturing by Bush administration officials
against leveraged buyouts of airlines including foreign carriers,
senior Transportation and Treasury department officials said this
week that proposed legislation to restrict airline takeovers
wouldn't be good for the industry _ or the economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
