<DOCNO> AP891027-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0244EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-RenamingZayre Bjt   10-27 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Renaming Zayre, Bjt,0602</SECOND>
<BYLINE>What's In a Name? A Lot, Connecticut Town Says</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LIGHTFOOT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMFIELD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Ames Department Stores Inc.
celebrated its acquisition of the Zayre chain by officially
renaming 254 Zayre stores, at least one town found something
sinister about the changeover.
   Bloomfield officials say Ames' decision not to rename the local
Zayre could be interpreted as racist, since Ames officials
acknowledge that the Zayre stores retaining that name are
patronized by ``metropolitan residents'' who might not be as loyal
to an Ames store.
   Officials in Bloomfield, where one-third of the population is
black, interpret that as a slap at minorities, and they aren't
happy about it.
   ``While some might defend the current decision as economic,
others are likely to characterize it more as racism and
stereotyping,'' Mayor David A. Baram said in a letter to Rocky
Hill-based Ames.
   Ribbon-cutting ceremonies were held Thursday to celebrate the
renaming and remodeling of 254 former Zayre stores, but the
Bloomfield store is one of 61 in the country and three in New
England that are rentaining the Zayre name. The other two New
England stores are in the Roxbury and Roslindale sections of
Boston, both of which have large minority populations.
   Executives at Ames, which doubled in size when it bought the
392-store Zayre chain for $778 million a year ago, say market
research indicated Zayre's name recognition was strong and
favorable in the ``metropolitan areas'' where the switch won't be
made, mainly in Chicago, Miami, Baltimore and Washington, D.C.
   Ames' so-called urban-market strategy means that, in addition to
not taking on the Ames name, the 61 stores will carry merchandise
more suited to urban customers _ clothing and accessories, for
instance, as opposed to products like lawn mowers and patio
furniture, said Douglas Ewing, Ames' vice president for investor
relations.
   Bloomfield officials complain that because the town north of
Hartford has a significant black population among its 20,000
residents, Ames officials decided to lump its store there with
inner-city stores serving a lower-income clientel.
   ``Ames has decided to designate the Bloomfield outfit as an
urban outfit and they have made that distinction because they have
suggested their patrons are primarily minorities and lower-income
people who are renters,'' Baram said. ``They picked the wrong
community.''
   The mayor described Bloomfield as ``perhaps the most
successfully integrated community in the state of Connecticut,''
with its population one-third black and one-third Jewish, along
with a smattering of other minorities.
   It is also one of the state's most affluent communities, ranking
in the top 25 percent for per-capita income in Connecticut. Eighty
percent of Bloomfield families own their own single-family homes.
   ``The residents here need and require lawn items, snow-removal
items, things (Ames) claims Zayre doesn't sell because its patrons
are residents who don't engage in mowing their lawns or swimming in
their pools or playing tennis,'' Baram said.
   Ewing said shoppers at Ames and Zayre will find essentially the
same items, although Zayre ``will offer expanded selections of
apparel and accessories and a more limited assortment of the kinds
of merchandise that metropolitan residents don't purchase as much.''
   Ewing said the Bloomfield store was the only one that produced
objections for not taking on the Ames name and merchandise.
   The Ames-Zayre consolidation looks to be a profitable one for
the company, Ewing said. Ames now estimates it will save $40
million by the end of the year because of the Ames-Zayre
consolidation, compared with the $10 million it originally
estimated, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
