<FIRST>r f PM-TalkingAds     10-27 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Talking Ads,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Absolut Vodka Plans Talking Holiday Ad in Selected Issues of Vanity
Fair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This time, the voice coming from your magazine
will be wishing you good tidings.
   When readers open the four-page Absolut Vodka ad in selected
December copies of Vanity Fair magazine,they'll hear holiday
greetings in English, Italian and Spanish. The voices say,
``Absolut Vodka wishes you Merry Christmas ... Buon Natale ...
Feliz Navidad ... Happy Chanukkah.''
   It will be the second talking magazine ad in as many months when
it comes out in late November.
   Last week, Texas Instruments Inc. ran a talking ad in selected
issues of Business Week magazine extolling the company's
technological capabilities.
   Nonetheless, Carillon Importers Ltd. touts its Absolut ad as the
first of its kind to present a spoken message in support of a
``consumer'' product.
   The ad, with an embedded microchip to do the talking, cost about
$1.2 million to produce and distribute and is being included in
issues going to 200,000 subscribers of the magazine in New York
State and California.
   It is the latest in a series of unusual holiday ads from Absolut
admakers.
   Last year, they developed a magazine ad in which a clear plastic
wrap that contained a liquid and simulated snow was pasted over a
photo of an Absolut bottle. When the page was shaken, the ``snow''
seemed to fall around the bottle, just like in one of those plastic
snow globes tourists often buy.
   An Absolut magazine ad two years ago had a chip that played
Christmas music when the page was opened.
   In its latest ad, an Absolut Vodka bottle is draped in Christmas
ornaments, candles and tinsel on the first page above the words
``Absolut Joy.''
   Across the two-page center spread, bottles are lined up with the
name and description inscribed in Japanese, Russian, English,
Polish, Korean, Portuguese, Ukranian, Chinese and Greek above the
slogan ``To the World.''
   The message ends on the back page, ``(And an Absolut New Year.)''
</TEXT>
