<DOCNO> AP891027-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0736EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     10-27 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Pound Stabilizing, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was higher in calm European trading
early today and the pound was stabilizing after its tumble due to
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson's resignation.
   Gold prices moved up.
   The sharp drop in the pound, signaling disarray in the British
financial markets after the Cabinet revolt Thursday, helped the
dollar as traders switched funds from the British into the U.S.
currency, dealers said.
   ``It was a signal to favor the dollar over the pound,'' said one
dealer at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt.
   Another trader at a French bank in Frankfurt said the move into
the dollar was a logical first reaction because it is the most
liquid currency where investors seek refuge in times of turmoil.
   ``But I believe the move is more a technical reaction and won't
last,'' he said. ``Next week, we should go weaker again.''
   ``But we have to wait to see whether this was an overreaction
Thursday or means a sustained weakness in the pound,'' he said.
   Traders said the Bank of England may have intervened in the
market to support the pound.
   Another dealer at a West German bank said Lawson's replacement
by John Major won't mean a change in British monetary policy, which
is likely to remain very tight.
   But some traders said the resignation has triggered a deep
crisis for Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and will further
undermine the trust of the financial markets in the soundness of
British economic policy. The falling fortunes of Thatcher's
government, coupled with the huge British current account deficits,
could prompt a further decline in the pound's value, they said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.85 yen to a closing 142.75 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at a lower rate of 142.63 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Thursday's
prices, included; 1.8502 West German marks, up from 1.8390; 1.6203
Swiss francs, up from 1.6085l; 6.2805 French francs, up from
6.2455; 2.0928 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0810; 1,357.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,347.75; and 1.1760 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1750.
   In London, it cost $1.5755 to buy one pound, compared with
$1.6130 late Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $371 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $369. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $371.55.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $371.75 compared with $368.25 late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.13 to close at a bid $371.87.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.18 a troy
ounce, up from Thursday's $5.13.
</TEXT>
