<DOCNO> AP891027-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0737EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     10-27 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Resignation Sends Pound Plunging, Dollar Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The resignation of the British treasury chief sent
the pound plunging and the dollar rising against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell sharply,
dealers said.
   The dollar closed at 142.75 yen, up 0.85 yen from Thursday's
finish and 0.62 yen higher than the New York finish overnight.
After opening at 142.02 yen, it rose to the day's high of 143.15
yen in early afternoon trading.
   Currency dealers said Japanese market players were selling
British pounds and buying dollars, resulting in the dollar's
relative bullishness against other currencies, including the
Japanese yen.
   Masafumi Koyama, a Bank of Tokyo trader, said dollar-yen trading
was light, but the dollar was bought actively against the
widespread selling of the British pound following British
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson's resignation.
   Lawson, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's treasury chief, and
her personal economic adviser Sir Alan Walters resigned Thursday in
a dramatic government shakeup.
   On the stock market, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost
151.90 points, or 0.42 percent, to close at 35,527.29.
   The market's main barometer opened slightly higher, but the
instability in the currency market and a poor showing in Wall
Street gradually pushed the index downward.
   Securities dealers attributed the Nikkei index decline to a
40-point fall in the Dow Jones industrial average of 30 major
issues in New York overnight, but they did not say it was caused
directly by the news from London.
   ``The instability in the currency market doesn't seem to bother
stock investors because they are aware that it is only dollar-pound
business,'' said a dealer at Nikko Securities Co., speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   He added, however, that market players share the view that share
prices have ``reached an excessively high level,'' and that is
causing most shares to ease downward.
   Another dealer at a major Japanese securities firm said
construction shares, which have been the driving force of the
recent rally in the Tokyo market, were mostly bearish because of
the market's general sentiment that construction shares are higher
than their acceptable level.
   Trading of shares in Sansui Electric Co., which announced a
buyout by British Polly Peck International Plc. Friday, was
suspended.
</TEXT>
