<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0848EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-UAL     10-27 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>Machinists May Compromise On UAL Ownership Stake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The airplane mechanics who helped scuttle an
employee buyout of UAL Corp. say they are willing to compromise
with United Airlines pilots on an employee ownership stake to
prevent an outside takeover of the company.
   The machinists union favors a restructuring of UAL but ``if we
have to get into some kind of ownership, we want minority ownership
just to keep the raiders out,'' John Peterpaul, vice president of
the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers,
said Thursday.
   Separately, the buyout group led by the pilots and UAL
management reiterated its intention to revise its bid for the
airline.
   Also Thursday, UAL reported its third quarter earnings were down
sharply from 1988, partly because of a $58.6 million charge related
to the botched buyout bid and partly because the year-earlier
period included a $393 million gain from the sale of UAL's share of
a computerized reservations system.
   The vehement opposition of the machinists to employee ownership
was seen as a factor in the failure of the $6.75 billion buyout
plan. The $300 a share proposal collapsed two weeks ago when the
buyout group, which also included British Airways PLC, failed to
secure financing.
   United's flight attendants joined forces with the group after
British Airways dropped out last week.
   UAL stock, which had plunged by more than 40 percent since the
plan collapsed, rose $9.75 a share to $170.75 Thursday on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   The price drop since the buyout group's Oct. 13 announcement
that it could not get financing has raised speculation that a
raider might attempt to buy up UAL shares to mount a takeover
attempt.
   Leaders of the Machinists, which represents United's mechanics
and ground-crew workers, met Thursday with financial advisers to
review the situation.
   Peterpaul said before the meeting his union was ready to
consider anything to ``get this company out of play and back into
the real world.''
   ``Ultimately, if we have to get into a posture between us and
the pilots to protect the airline and protect the jobs of
employees, I think ... we can reach a spirit of compromise,''
Peterpaul said in a telephone interview from Washington, where the
meeting was held.
   Frederick Dubinsky, chairman of the United pilots union, has
said the pilots still would like majority ownership by the
airline's employees but would settle for some form of control over
the airline, perhaps through super-majority voting rights.
   Financial advisers to United's pilots and flight attendants met
separately in New York on Thursday ``to fully explore the issues
and options,'' said Kathie Hardin, a spokeswoman for the United
chapter of the Air Line Pilots Association in Chicago.
   In a statement issued late Thursday, the pilot-management group
said it was ``reviewing the situation with a view toward revising
its transaction and proceeding with the employee acquisition of UAL
Corp.''
   The statement said the group expected to have a proposal ready
for the UAL board ``in the near term.''
   The flight attendants' union represents about 14,000 United
employees, compared with 7,000 workers represented by the pilots'
union and 25,000 by the Machinists.
   UAL's top management was a 10 percent partner in the failed
buyout bid. But Chairman Stephen Wolf said Monday he was returning
his attention to running the airline, apparently at the urging of
UAL's board of directors.
   The board decided Monday not to sell the company for the time
being, while it explores other ways to increase shareholder value.
   In its earnings report, UAL posted a profit of $110.8 million,
or $5.11 per share, down from $402.4 million, or $18.68, a year
earlier.
   Excluding the $393 million gain from the sale of its interests
in the Covia reservations system, UAL's profit in the year-earlier
period was $179 million, or $8.31 per share.
   Revenue during the quarter rose to $2.6 billion from $2.4
billion in third quarter 1988.
   Earnings also were depressed by a $58.6 million charge for stock
appreciation rights, stemming from the surge in UAL's stock after
billionaire Marvin Davis made a buyout proposal that later was
countered by the pilot-management group's bid.
   Davis later withdrew his offer but said he remained interested
in UAL.
   For the first nine months of the year, UAL posted a profit of
$317.4 million, or $14.66 a share, compared with $1.1 billion, or
$34.35 per share, a year earlier. Nine-month revenue rose to $7.4
billion from $6.75 billion.
</TEXT>
