<FIRST>u f PM-Braniff     10-27 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Braniff,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Braniff Hires Merrill Lynch to Explore Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Braniff Inc., which is currently undergoing
bankruptcy court reorganization, says it has hired Merrill Lynch &amp;
Co. to explore the possible sale of the airline.
   A Merrill Lynch team will work full-time with Braniff to seek
the best possible plan for the airline and its creditors, Mark J.
Schulte, managing director of Merrill Lynch Capital Markets, said
Thursday.
   In late September, Braniff filed for protection from creditors
under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code. It was the airline's
second such filing in seven years.
   ``We believe that Braniff, its assets and its fine personnel
have an appropriate role to play in today's commercial air
transportation system,'' said William G. McGee, Braniff's chairman,
president and chief executive officer.
   ``We look to Merrill Lynch to help us appropriately define that
role and explore the best feasible plans to put these assets back
into the competitive environment.''
   Braniff now serves 11 U.S. markets with 46 daily flights.
   Separately Thursday, Presidential Airways, a feeder carrier for
United Airlines, announced that it had filed for bankruptcy
protection under Chapter 11. In early March, Eastern Airlines filed
under Chapter 11 a few days after it was struck by the unions
representing pilots, Machinists and flight attendants.
