<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0940EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Britain-Economy 2ndLd-Writethru   10-27 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Economy, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0831</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Chancellor To Continue Economic Policies, But Financial Markets
Rocked</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to restore dropped word, higher.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's new treasury secretary is expected to
pursue mostly the same economic policies, but London financial
markets were rocked today by the news of revolt in Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's Cabinet.
   The new chancellor of the exchequer, John Major, was named to
the post Thursday night after Nigel Lawson abruptly resigned,
saying he couldn't continue to serve as long as Mrs. Thatcher
retained her economic adviser, Sir Alan Walters. Walters resigned
himself several hours later.
   Financial markets were hit hard by the government upheaval. The
pound plummeted late Thursday, sank in early trading today and then
stabilized, while stock prices skidded today before recovering some
of their losses.
   The Bank of England, which normally does not comment on its
activities, appeared to have intervened in the foreign exchange
market today to support the pound, dealers said.
   The markets were concerned about uncertainty and feared that the
government again would push up interest rates, which already stand
at an eight-year high of 15 percent. Even higher interest rates
would worsen fears of a recession in Britain.
   Mrs. Thatcher told reporters outside her 10 Downing St. office
today that government policies would continue ``precisely as they
were'' despite Lawson's resignation.
   She expressed regret at his departure, citing his ``enormous
achievements,'' but said her new appointees were all experienced.
   The pound traded at $1.5790 in late morning today, compared with
a low of $1.5620 earlier in Asian trading, and $1.6130 in London
before Lawson resigned Thursday.
   On London's stock exchange, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-stock index was down 33.5 points, or 1.6 percent, at 2,095.9 at
midday after having been down nearly 44 points earlier in the
session.
   ``The market was already very uncertain about the economy and
this has just worsened matters,'' said Andrew Smith, a British
equities analyst at Laing and Cruikshank.
   ``Lawson's resignation will be very damaging to the market,''
said Charles Larkum, an analyst at the London investment firm James
Capel and Co. ``The focus will now be on sterling and whether U.K.
base (interest) rates will have to rise.''
   Major on Thursday quickly vowed to continue Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's fight against resurgent inflation with high
interest rates.
   But economists said they doubted Major would see a strong pound
as key in the fight against inflation, as Lawson did.
   The pound's decline reflects the disappearance of the ``Lawson
premium,'' said Nigel Richardson, an economist at the London
investment firm Warburg Securities.
   ``It takes the floor from under sterling,'' said Gavyn Davies,
an economist with Goldman Sachs International in London.
   Major, who was first secretary of the Treasury before being
named foreign secretary in July, said in his statement: ``I
strongly supported the government's economic and monetary policies
when last at the Treasury and I still do.''
   ``Inflation is the most damaging problem we face and its defeat
remains our overriding objective,'' he said.
   ``Monetary policy is tight and is beginning to have its
effect,'' he added. ``I shall keep it tight for as long as
necessary.''
   So far this year, Britain's annual inflation rate has more than
doubled to its current 7.6 percent, and the country's trade deficit
ballooned to the equivalent of $31 billion, from $23 billion at the
same time a year ago.
   The government has increased official interest rates 11 times
since June 1988, bringing them from a decade low of 7.5 percent to
15 percent, their highest level in eight years.
   The latest interest rate increase, on Oct. 5, of a full
percentage point was made in line with a West German interest rate
increase.
   The British move was attacked as excessive by the government's
critics, who warned that it could push Britain into a recession.
   But the government stood by its interest rate increases, which
are designed to curb consumer spending and borrowing.
   Economists said there were likely to be far fewer doubts about
Major's allegiance to Mrs. Thatcher's policies than there were
during Lawson's 6{ years at the Treasury.
   Mrs. Thatcher has been more faithful to free-market principles
in regard to foreign exchange movements than Lawson, who believed
in the benefits of a strong and stable exchange rate.
   Stability could be achieved by tying the pound to the exchange
rate mechanism of European Monetary System, which links eight of
the Common Market's 12 currencies and limits their movements,
Lawson believed.
   But Mrs. Thatcher believes the pound should be linked only after
Britain's inflation comes down to the level of inflation in other
European countries, and capital flows freely in Europe.
   Walters, who had public disagreements with Lawson, has been a
staunch proponent of allowing sterling to float to its natural
level.
</TEXT>
