<FIRST>r f PM-FCC-Indecency 1stLd-Writethru   10-27 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FCC-Indecency, 1st Ld-Writethru,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stations Fined by FCC</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf pvs, ``WZTA-AM, Miami,'' to CORRECT to FM sted
AM station.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission is
warning ``shock jocks'' that they will be fined if they broadcast
indecent material during daytime hours.
   The commission's mass media bureau Thursday issued $20,000 in
fines against four radio stations and said it was investigating
four others for alleged indecent broadcasts.
   The bureau, under new chief Roy Stewart, also eliminated a
backlog of 87 indecency complaints built up during the last two
years under former FCC Chairman Dennis Patrick.
   Fifty-one cases against 40 stations were dropped because the
purportedly indecent material was broadcast after 8 p.m., and 36
others were dropped because of defective complaints or inadequate
proof of violations, said Bill Johnson, deputy chief of the mass
media bureau.
   Thursday's action was another indication that the commission
under Chairman Alfred Sikes will crack down on indecent programming
between 6 a.m. and 8 p.m. Since Sikes took over in August, the FCC
has issued warnings to three radio stations and fined another
$2,000.
   Sikes and his three fellow commissioners also voted Thursday to
launch an inquiry into establishing a 24-hour ban on indecent
broadcasting Congress ordered last year.
   A court stayed implementation of the FCC rules in January, and
in September ordered the agency to conduct a study to justify the
ban.
   The commission defines broadcast indecency as language or
material that ``depicts or describes, in terms patently offensive
as measured by contemporary community standards for the broadcast
medium, sexual or excretory activities or organs.''
   It will take action when there is a ``reasonable risk'' that
children may be in the audience, the FCC said.
   Congress specifically ordered a ban to protect children and in
its announcement Thursday, the commission said it would consider
children to be age 17 and under.
   The stations cited Thursday and their fines were:
   _WIOD, Miami, licensed by Cox Broadcasting, $10,000 for five
alleged instances of indecent programming from Nov. 7 through Dec.
20, 1988.
   _WZTA-FM, Miami, licensed by Guy Gannett Publishing Co., $2,000
for allegedly broadcasting an indecent song Oct. 27, 1987.
   _KLUC-FM, Las Vegas, Nev., licensed by Nationwide Communications
Inc., $2,000 for broadcasting an allegedly indecent song May 16,
1988.
   _KFI-AM, Los Angeles, licensed by KFI Inc., $6,000 for alleged
indecent material on a telephone talk show Nov. 12, 1988.
   The stations were given 30 days to show why they should not pay
the fines, which can be appealed to the full commission.
   Four other stations were given 30 days to respond to complaints
they had broadcast indecent material. They were:
   _WXRK-FM, New York, licensed by Infinity Broadcasting, for a
Christmas party skit aired Dec. 16, 1988. The commission said the
material also may have been broadcast on two other Infinity
stations, WYSP-FM in Philadelphia and WJFK-FM in Manassas, Va.
   _KCCL-AM-FM, Paris, Ark., licensed by Diamond State
Broadcasting, for a broadcast telephone conversation between
station manager Gene Williams and his son.
   _WWWE-AM, Cleveland, licensed to Independent Group Limited
Partnership, for alleged indecent material on several days.
   _KSD-FM, St. Louis, licensed to Pacific and Southern Co., for
allegedly broadcasting excerpts from a Playboy magazine interview
with Jessica Hahn.
   Mike Disney, general manager of WIOD, told the Miami Herald: ``I
liken it to the Starship Enterprise going into a time warp and
suddenly the rules are different. Since Al Sikes has come in (as
FCC chairman) it's been a tremendous shift to the right.''
   Disney said he hasn't decided if WIOD will pay the fine. ``The
fact is that this is, I think, censorship and this would not stand
up against the First Amendment,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891027-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1027EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     10-27 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0312</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market lost more ground today,
extending its week-long decline amid worries over weakness in
corporate earnings.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 5.53 to 2,608.20
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by nearly 2 to 1 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 309 up, 601
down and 493 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 21.18 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said a series of unpleasant surprises in companies'
earnings reports for the third quarter raised concerns that have
continued to weigh down the market.
   When stocks have been under pressure lately, brokers added, they
haven't attracted much support from ``bargain hunting'' investors.
   The market's extreme volatility of late is presumed to have
frightened off a good many participants who might otherwise be
buying stocks at marked-down prices.
   In addition, many Federal Reserve-watchers remain uncertain over
whether and when the Fed might take any further steps to relax its
credit policy.
   Losers among the blue chips included American Express, down } at
36\; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, down ] at 43\; General
Electric, down { at 53~, and United Technologies, down [ at 52{.
