<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1104EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Sansui-PollyPeck     10-27 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sansui-Polly Peck,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Audio Maker Bought by British Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amid a wave of buyouts by Japanese companies
overseas, a British company surprised the Japanese public Friday by
announcing plans to take over Sansui Electric Co., a well-known but
financially troubled Japanese audio manufacturer.
   Sansui agreed to a friendly takeover by the British conglomerate
Polly Peck International PLC, Sansui president Ryosuke Ito told a
news conference.
   PPI is to purchase 51 percent of Sansui shares by buying 39
million shares which are to be newly issued in early January, in
addition to 37.6 million shares currently held by other
shareholders, he said.
   The British company will pay some 15.7 billion yen, the
equivalent of $111 million, buying Sansui shares at 400 yen, or
$2.80, per share.
   ``After thorough examination, we have decided the tie-up with
PPI (Polly Peck International) will be the best way to restructure
our company,'' Ito told reporters.
   At the end of October 1989, Sansui had a cumulative debts
amounting to 13.8 billion yen, ``mainly due to our failure in
management to overcome the worsening external environment and tough
competition with other makers,'' he said.
   The deal made front-page news in major Japanese evening
newspapers Friday and prompted lively comment.
   ``Amid a recent wave of mergers and aquisitions of foreign
companies by Japanese firms, this is the first case in which a
major Japanese company is being saved by a foreign company,'' wrote
Yomiuri Shimbun, the nation's largest newspaper.
   With the British company's help, Sansui hopes boost profits by
starting production of VCRs to enter the audio visual equipments
market, while further developing its audio products, Sansui said in
the statement.
   Sansui has been financially in trouble since 1985, largely due
to the dollar's appreciation, and paid no dividends for the fourth
straight year, said Ito.
   Hikaru Matsunaga, minister of Ministry of International Trade
and Industry, told Japan Broadcasting Corp. he thinks the deal is
fine as long as it helps Sansui by solving its financial problems
and favorable management.
   He said the case proved that while Japanese companies are buying
foreign companies overseas, foreign investors are also seeking
opportunities in Japan, which is a good thing, the minister said.
   Asir Nadia, chairman and chief executive of PPI told a press
conference the same day that the tie-up between the two companies
proved that foreign firms are powerful enough to buy Japanese firms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
