<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1125EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-LincolnS&amp;L 1stLd-Writethru   10-27 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lincoln S&amp;L, 1st Ld-Writethru,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulators Say Lincoln Owner Used Political Influence</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs last graf, Patriarca, Black to CORRECT first to second.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Regulators who tried to close Lincoln Savings
and Loan Association say the thrift's millionaire owner fought back
as late as this spring with political influence reaching the
highest levels of government.
   William J. Crawford, commissioner of the California Department
of Savings and Loans, told the House Banking Committee on Thursday
that two attempts were made from Washington on behalf of Phoenix
businessman Charles H. Keating Jr. to approve the sale of Lincoln
to a group of investors.
   Crawford never approved the sale, described as a ``sham'' by
federal regulator William Black.
   Within weeks of the calls, the Irvine, Calif.-based S&amp;L was
taken over by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and is expected
to require a $2 billion bailout, making it the nation's costliest
thrift failure.
   Carolyn Jordan, an aide to Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., urged
approval of the sale in March. In April, according to Crawford,
Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., called Crawford's boss, Business,
Transportation and Housing Secretary John Geoghegan.
   Crawford said DeConcini called at the instigation of the top
federal thrift regulator, M. Danny Wall.
   In an 8{-hour hearing, Crawford and San Francisco-based
officials of Wall's agency, the Office of Thrift Supervision,
detailed Keating's three-year effort to deter them from bringing
enforcement action against his institution.
   The effort included what they characterized as secret meetings
in 1987 between Keating and Wall as well as the enlistment of five
senators to plead Lincoln's cause and the hiring of Federal Reserve
Board Chairman Alan Greenspan, then a private economist, as a
consultant to defend the thrift's financial condition.
   Michael Patriarca, the thrift office's chief supervisory agent
in San Francisco, and Black, counsel in that office, had
recommended in May 1987 that the government seize Lincoln to end
reckless activities and prevent further losses.
   Their recommendation was rejected, and in an unprecedented move
the case was transferred from the San Francisco office to agency
headquarters in Washington. Patriarca and Black said that delayed
action by two years.
   ``If our recommendations had been followed, the taxpayers ...
would have suffered dramatically smaller losses,'' Black said. ``It
need not have happened and would not have happened if (regulators
in Washington) had showed any backbone.''
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, chairman of the banking panel,
said he would ask President Bush to have Wall take administrative
leave during the hearings.
   Gonzalez complained that Wall, by having a thrift office lawyer
meet earlier this month with Patriarca and Black, was attempting to
influence their testimony.
   In other developments:
   _Gonzalez revealed that shortly after the FDIC took over Lincoln
the agency discovered that telephones in an office used by
California state S&amp;L examiners had been rigged so that others in
the institution could eavesdrop on the examiners' confidential
conversations.
   An FDIC memo released by the committee said the matter was
referred to the FBI for criminal investigation.
   Leonard Bickwit, a Washington attorney representing Keating,
said corporate officials deny authorizing or participating in phone
tampering.
   _Patriarca revealed that in an apparent attempt to influence
him, his wife, Laura Patriarca, then an attorney with the thrift
office, was offered a job with American Continental.
   Testimony by Patriarca and Black illustrates Keating's wide
political reach, which included persuading five senators whose
campaigns he had helped fund to meet with regulators on his behalf
in April 1987.
   The five are Cranston; DeConcini; John McCain, R-Ariz.; John
Glenn, D-Ohio; and Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich.
   Patriarca and Black said the bank board under Wall seemed more
protective of Keating's interests than of its own field staff.
Without informing regulators in San Francisco or asking for their
side of the story, they said Wall and other bank board officials
met dozens of times with Keating.
   In 1984 and 1985, when Keating was fighting a bank board effort
to restrict direct commercial and real estate investments by
thrifts, he enlisted the help of Greenspan, who in a ``very
influential'' letter distributed to members of Congress described
Lincoln as a strong institution, Black said.
   Patriarca, Black and Crawford appeared at the second of four
scheduled hearings on Lincoln. Keating and Wall are scheduled to
appear Nov. 7.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
