<HEAD>Grain Futures Weaken on Slack Export Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
lower in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade,
reflecting disappointment in the low level of export sales this
week.
   Although the Agriculture Department announced sales of 100,000
metric tons of corn to South Korea and 25,000 tons of wheat to
Algeria this morning, traders said those transactions were
insignificant compared to the several million tons of U.S. grain
the Soviet Union bought last week.
   Despite the relatively slack demand this week, export sales of
U.S. corn and soybeans are running well ahead of last year and some
experts believe prices are headed higher in the long run.
   ``On any good breaks, buy some for your grandmother,'' advised
John Frazier, an analyst with Balfour Maclaine Corp. in Chicago.
   In early trading, wheat futures, which closed at four-week lows
Thursday, were \ cent lower to { cent higher with the contract for
December delivery unchanged at $3.98{ a bushel; corn was \ cent to
1\ cents lower with December at $2.43{ a bushel; oats were \ cent
to } cent lower with December at $1.45 a bushel; soybeans were
unchanged to 3{ cents lower with November at $5.64 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were lower in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent to .40 cent lower with December at
74.25 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .62 cent lower
with November at 82.45 cents a pound; hogs were .12 cent to .62
cent lower with December at 46.35 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .30 cent to .45 cent lower with February at 52 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled lower on Thursday.
