<FIRST>u f BC-Mobil-Restructuring 2ndLd-Writethru f0081 10-27 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mobil-Restructuring, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0081,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mobil Says Restructuring Will Reduce Workforce By About 400</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 6th graf `Offices in ...' to include cities that will gain
workers and CORRECT that Bakersfield will gain, sted lose; picks up 7th
graf pvs `Mobil had ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mobil Corp. said Friday that a previously
announced reorganization of its U.S. operations would involve the
reduction of approximately 400 employees nationwide.
   The country's second largest oil company behind Exxon Corp. said
the biggest reduction would come from slashing the staff in its
Denver office from 430 people to 105.
   Charles E. Spruell, president of Mobil's exploration and
production unit, said the changes would be concentrated in
operations responsible for drilling wells and pumping crude and
natural gas.
   The cutbacks are scheduled to begin ``in a few weeks'' and will
continue over several months, Mobil said.
   Mobil disclosed the reorganization Tuesday, calling it part of
an effort to cut costs and improve profits in the United States,
where depressed oil prices have made exploration and drilling much
less profitable.
   Offices in Dallas, Houston, New Orleans, and Midland, Texas,
also will lose workers, said Mobil spokesman John Lord, while
offices in Bakersfield, Calif., Liberal, Kan., and Oklahoma City
will gain some.
   Mobil has 69,500 employees worldwide, including 5,000 in its
U.S. exploration and production units.
   In its third-quarter earnings report on Tuesday, Mobil said it
had taken a $40 million provision for the restructuring costs.
   Mobil reported a 4 percent decline in net income compared with
the 1988 third period _ $532 million, or $1.30 a share, vs. $557
million, or $1.36 a share. Revenue totaled $13.6 billion, up 4
percent from $13.1 billion a year earlier.
   Analysts said Mobil's restructuring reflects an industrywide
reshuffling of assets because of declining U.S. output. Domestic
production fell by more than 500,000 barrels a day during the first
nine months of this year.
</TEXT>
