<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0045,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Sharply Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed sharply lower Friday in active
trading in London, depressed by Chancellor Nigel Lawson's
resignation and a rapid selloff on Wall Street.
   London shares were driven lower initially by Thursday losses in
New York and by the drop in the British pound after Lawson's
resignation. They showed some early resilience after reported
central bank intervention supported the pound, but were overcome by
Wall Street's decline late in London trading and signs of further
weakness in sterling.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index shed 47.3
points, or 2.2 percent, to close at 2,082.1. That was down 4.5
percent from last Friday and 6.8 percent from Oct. 13, when Wall
Street's collapse helped spark the current weakness on the London
Stock Exchange.
   The Financial Times 30-share index settled 42 points lower at
1,678.5. The Financial Times 500-share index fell 26.31 points to
1,157.08.
   Volume was 840.8 million shares, up sharply from 443.6 million
on Thursday.
</TEXT>
