<DOCNO> AP891027-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 2152EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-RJRNabisco Adv29 1stLd-Writethru 10-27 1111</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-RJR Nabisco, Adv 29, 1st Ld-Writethru,1149</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday Oct. 29</HEAD>
<HEAD>Takeover Era Irony: Deal That Inspired the Biggest Fear is Doing
Fine</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 20-23, beg `The company has sold ...' to UPDATE with
sale of Baby Ruth, Butterfinger; picks up 24th graf, `Maxwell, the Wheat
First ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street was stunned. Bond brokers froze.
Doomsayers talked of financial disaster.
   That was the scene a year ago, as the biggest takeover battle of
all time consumed RJR Nabisco Inc. When it was over, the investment
firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. had defeated the food and
tobacco giant's top management, paid a record $24.53 billion in
borrowed money and put the company heavily into debt.
   Critics of the 1980s takeover era said RJR Nabisco would be
crushed by the weight of its debt load and jeopardize the banks
that financed the deal. The bond market, already reeling from a
rash of high-priced takeovers, was traumatized because investors
thought the buyout binge had gone too far.
   What a difference a year makes.
   Despite a debt of $23 billion, RJR Nabisco now is seen as a
relative rock of stability while the financial markets are buffeted
with uncertainty raised by smaller takeovers.
   ``I think the company is doing tremendously well,'' said Kurt
Feuerman, a securities analayst at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Jack Maxwell of Wheat First Securities in Richmond, Va., said,
``It's a good company and they've got a good team.''
   Investors also praise the new RJR Nabisco. Confidence in the
company was evident in the recent performance of the company's
high-yield ``junk bonds'' that were used to finance the takeover.
Prices skidded on the high-yield market after other big buyouts ran
into trouble recently. RJR Nabisco's didn't.
   There are two reasons why.
   Because of the nature of RJR Nabisco's business, the company is
considered inherently more stable than other companies. Investors
also have confidence in its management.
   The biggest worry for highly leveraged companies like RJR
Nabisco is cash flow _ without a strong, steady influx of money,
they can't pay their interest bills.
   Several buyouts have stumbled because cash flow hasn't matched
projections. The most notorious case has been Campeau Corp.'s $6.6
billion takeover of Federated Department Stores Inc., a wobbly
transaction that jolted the stock and bond markets a few weeks ago
because Campeau couldn't pay its interest.
   Kohlberg Kravis, the acknowledged leader of debt-financed
takeovers, played no role in the Campeau-Federated problem, but
some of its financial deals have faced difficulty. For example, its
$360 million buyout of Seaman Furniture Co., had to be refinanced.
   No one expects that to happen at RJR Nabisco, because the
company's products are considered ``recession proof'' _ even in
hard times, people would still eat Oreos and smoke Camels.
   ``They have a predictable cash flow generating capability which
exceeds interest expense and capital expense,'' said Michael
Dahood, a bond market analyst. ``The stability of the enterprise is
not threatened by debt expense.''
   The company's R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. _ along with other
tobacco firms _ has lost market share to industry leader Philip
Morris Cos. Inc. in recent years, but the analysts see little cause
for concern.
   ``Tobacco profits should grow 15 percent his year and another 20
percent next year,'' said Drexel's Feuerman, noting that profit
growth from overseas sales is also in the range of 20 percent.
   Analysts and investors say they're satisfied with the way RJR
Nabisco Chairman Louis Gerstner has handled the company since he
arrived there from American Express Co. eight months ago.
   They particularly like the prices he's gotten for assets RJR
Nabisco has sold to help repay its debt load.
   The company has sold five European food businesses for $2.5
billion; its Chun King division for $52 million; its Associated
Biscuits International Ltd. for $44 million; Del Monte fresh fruit
operations for $875 million; Del Monte's canned food business for
$1.48 billion; and most recently, its Baby Ruth, Butterfinger and
Pearson candy businesses for $370 million.
   The sold divisions won't cost RJR Nabisco that much business and
``what they have left is very strongly positioned,'' Feuerman said.
   RJR Nabisco must still dispose of some $230 million in assets to
reach its goal of $5.5 billion in divestitures. ``There are some
smaller parts of the company that we're exploring at this point,''
but the company does not plan to shed any major divisions, Gerstner
said in an interview.
   Individual product lines are the most likely to go.
   Maxwell, the Wheat First analyst, said he was pleased by cost
and inventory reductions and by the company's plans for boosting
tobacco sales. In recent years, R.J. Reynolds has turned around its
once-lagging Camel brand, and is focusing on revitalizing Winston
and Salem sales, Maxwell said.
   The battle for RJR Nabisco marked a quantum leap in the scope of
the takeover trend reshaping American business. For the first time,
it seemed to raise the possibility that any company could be
acquired with borrowed money.
   The company announced on Oct. 20 that its chief executive, F.
Ross Johnson, was considering a bid of about $17 billion.
   That kind of money was beyond comprehension on Wall Street. But
four days later, Kohlberg Kravis announced a $20.25 billion offer,
signaling the start of a bidding war that for a while included the
investment firm First Boston Corp.
   The RJR Nabisco fight not only dwarfed all records for
takeovers, it came against a background of brawls for two other big
food companies.
   Just days before, Philip Morris had launched an $11 billion
offer for Kraft Inc. and Pillsbury Co. had rejected a $5.23 billion
bid from the British firm Grand Metropolitan PLC.
   In both cases the suitors won. And late in the evening of Nov.
29, RJR Nabisco announced that Kohlberg Kravis had emerged the
winner.
   Johnson was vanquished but still rich from a severance package
and the sale of his own RJR Nabisco stock when he resigned in early
February. He took several top RJR Nabisco managers with him, but
analysts said they were satisfied with Gerstner's replacements.
   Kohlberg Kravis is also said to be happy with RJR Nabisco's
performance. The investment firm is smarting from Seaman's problems
and reports that it has been disappointed by other investments, and
its reputation rests on the outcome of its biggest takeover.
   For Gerstner, the outside world's obsession with the size of the
takeover is irrelevant. It's running the business that's most
important.
   ``You've got to separate that financial transaction from the
great marketing strength and production strength of this company,''
he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday Oct. 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891027-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1542EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-Economy Bjt   10-27 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Economy, Bjt,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain's Markets Are Buffeted by Political Storm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's financial markets were buffeted Friday
by the political storm over the abrupt resignation of Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher's treasury secretary.
   The markets were jolted by uncertainty over the government's
exchange-rate policy and were highly nervous that a resulting steep
decline in the British pound would prompt the government to push up
interest rates above their 8-year high of 15 percent.
   The pound ended at $1.5750 in London Friday, up from a low of
$1.5620 earlier in Asian trading, but down from $1.6130 in London
Thursday before Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson resigned.
   On the London Stock Exchange, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-stock index fell 47.3 points, or 2.2 percent, to close at
2,082.1, near its session low.
   Higher interest rates would increase the growing chances of a
recession in Britain, already suffering from the highest interest
rates and inflation among the major industrialized countries.
   ``That's obviously the big fear at the moment,'' said Anthony
Thomas, an economist with the London investment firm Kleinwort
Grieveson Securities.
   Said Keith Skeoch, economist at James Capel and Co.: ``That's
going to be touch or go whether we go to 16 percent.''
   He added: ``We're pretty close to a recession here at the moment
anyway.''
   Mrs. Thatcher declared Friday that it was ``business as usual,''
and that she would continue her economic policies.
   A new chancellor of the exchequer, John Major, was named to the
post Thursday night after Lawson abruptly resigned after six and a
half years in the position.
   Belatedly on Friday evening, the Treasury issued the text of a
speech Major was to make later, saying, ``I favor a firm exchange
rate.'' But most of the day's trading had wound down by then.
   Lawson, an elected member of Parliament, said he couldn't
continue to serve as chancellor as long as Mrs. Thatcher retained
her economic adviser, Sir Alan Walters. Walters also resigned
Thursday, several hours later.
   Lawson's departure, forcing a Cabinet shuffle in the face of a
deteriorating economy, is Mrs. Thatcher's biggest crisis since
coming to power in 1979, the British press and her critics say.
   Some of London's investment firms stayed open all night Thursday
to trade the pound and shares because the news of Lawson's
resignation came after the stock market closed.
   The Bank of England intervened in the foreign-exchange market
Friday to support the pound, dealers said. The British central bank
normally does not comment on its market activities. The U.S.
Federal Reserve was reported intervening late in the London day to
help support the pound.
   But the Bank of England refrained from pushing up interest
rates, for the time being, by leaving its money-market rates
unchanged.
   Analysts said the government was in a difficult position. An
interest-rate increase could signal _ and cause _ panic. But
standing pat could encourage the pound to slide further, and that
might fuel inflation _ just what Mrs. Thatcher wants to avoid.
   ``The government is falling over itself to emphasize this is not
a crisis,'' Thomas said. ``If they put up interest rates, it's
tantamount to admitting it is a crisis.''
   Analysts complained that they weren't sure of what Major's
currency policy was. Lawson believed a strong pound was key to
fighting inflation, and supported managing exchange rates. Walters
believes in free-floating rates.
   Britain's annual inflation rate has more than doubled to its
current 7.6 percent. The country's trade deficit ballooned to the
equivalent of $31 billion so far this year, from $23 billion at the
same time a year ago.
   The government has pushed up interest rates 11 times since June
1988, bringing them from a decade low of 7.5 percent to 15 percent,
their highest level in eight years.
   ``Clearly, the next week or 10 days is going to be a very
uncertain period until that confidence is established in the
market,'' Thomas said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
