<HEAD>Soybean Futures Slip; Grains Finish Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed moderately lower
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid expectations for an
active harvesting weekend in the Southeast and the Mississippi
Delta region.
   Corn futures also fell while wheat futures finished mixed.
   With most of the Midwestern corn and soybean crops now in, the
harvest is moving south. Dry weather is expected in southern
soybean areas this weekend, which should allow the fieldwork to
move along rapidly.
   A lack of significant export business limited buying interest in
the grain markets, analysts said.
   Although the Agriculture Department announced overnight sales of
100,000 metric tons of corn to South Korea and 25,000 tons of wheat
to Algeria, traders said those transactions were insignificant
compared with the several million tons of U.S. grain the Soviet
Union bought last week.
   Nevertheless, export sales of U.S. corn and soybeans are running
well ahead of last year and some experts believe prices are headed
higher in the long run.
   ``On any good breaks, buy some for your grandmother,'' advised
John Frazier, an analyst with Balfour Maclaine Corp. in Chicago.
   At the close of trading, wheat futures were } cent lower to 2\
cents higher with the contract for December delivery at $3.98{ a
bushel; corn was 2} cents lower to \ cent higher with December at
$2.42 a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to 2} cents lower with December
at $1.43} a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 5{ cents lower with
November at $5.62 a bushel.
