<FIRST>u f AM-RJR-Nabisco-BabyRuth     10-27 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-RJR-Nabisco-Baby Ruth,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>RJR Nabisco Sells Candy Businesses for $370 Million to Nestle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. announced Friday it is selling
its Baby Ruth, Butterfinger and Pearson candy businesses to Nestle
Foods Corp. for $370 million.
   The sale leaves RJR Nabisco about $230 million from its goal of
$5.5 billion in asset sales for raising cash to reduce the
company's debt load following its $24.53 billion leveraged buyout
by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
   The deal with Nestle, a division of Switzerland's giant Nestle
SA, includes a manufacturing plant in Franklin Park, Ill.
   The company began its asset sales program earlier this year
after Kohlberg Kravis completed its acquisition of the food and
tobacco giant. Kohlberg Kravis agreed to sell $5.5 billion in
assets in return for financing the deal, the most expensive
corporate takeover ever.
   RJR Nabisco earlier sold five European food businesses for $2.5
billion; its Chun King division for $52 million; its Associated
Biscuits International Ltd. for $44 million; Del Monte fresh fruit
operations for $875 million; and Del Monte's canned food business
for $1.48 billion.
   RJR Nabisco Chairman Louis Gerstner has said the company would
not sell any more major divisions to reach its goal. Individual
product lines are considered the most likely sale candidates.
   Analysts say RJR Nabisco has negotiated good prices for the
divisions, and will not lose much in operating income because of
the divestitures.
   Nestle produces such well known goods as Nestle chocolate bars
and Raisinets candy, Nescafe coffee and Nestle Quik chocolate drink
mixes.
</TEXT>
