<DOCNO> AP891027-0285 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1711EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-BankLoans Bjt   10-27 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank Loans, Bjt,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sagging Real Estate Market Drags Down Banks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sagging real estate market in New England is
causing trouble for the region's banks, which competed to lend
money during a building boom earlier this decade but now have seen
many loans go bust.
   ``Everyone was caught up in the euphoria of the market and they
didn't remember that what goes up will also come down,'' said Leo
Spang, senior vice president in the real estate division at Shawmut
Bank in Boston.
   The result of the downturn will be lower stock prices and
earnings for shareholders, and more reluctance by banks to finance
real estate projects, experts say. Also, analysts predict that some
small financial institutions could be forced to shut down.
   ``This real estate correction is going to take a pound of flesh
from most banks and thrifts,'' said Gerard Cassidy, a banking
analyst with Tucker Anthony Inc. in Portland, Maine.
   In recent weeks, the region's largest banks have been wounded
because of shaky real estate loans.
   Moody's Investors Service lowered its ratings for both Bank of
Boston and Bank of New England, in both cases citing the weakened
real estate market.
   For example, Bank of Boston reported that in New England, it has
around $400 million in non-performing commercial real estate loans,
meaning developers are having trouble making payments.
   To cover the bad loans, Bank of Boston shifted money into its
reserves and reported a $125 million loss in its last quarter.
   ``It's clearly a problem,'' company spokesman Wayne Taylor said,
``otherwise the bank would not have reported its biggest loss in
history.''
   Similar news came this week from smaller banking companies.
Heritage Bancorp of Holyoke, Mass., and One Bancorp of Portland,
Maine, both reported that their non-performing assets had grown
sharply, and as a result they took losses for the quarter.
   ``The banks that were really players are all experiencing
difficulty,'' said Vincent Furey Jr., president and chief executive
officer of One Bancorp.
   Analysts say these losses can be blamed on natural cycles in the
real estate market, but also on a failure by many banks to see that
the cycle would change.
   ``Things were straight up,'' Cassidy said. ``Everyone was having
a great old time.''
   The real estate fortunes mirrored growth in the region's
economy, which boomed in the mid-1980s. But problems began when the
economy started to weaken, because many commercial developments
were already in the works but still needed tenants.
   ``It's not the boom times,'' said Michael Manzo, president of
the Greater Boston Real Estate Board. ``The demand for office space
is off. Job formation, job growth is not what it was.''
   With office buildings and condominiums having a hard time
finding tenants, many developers have had trouble paying off their
loans. The result is that banks are now struggling with some loans
that they should not have approved, analysts say.
   ``A lot of banks were competing (for developments) and some of
them got into poor lending practices,'' said James Moynihan, senior
vice president of Advest Inc. in Boston.
   Banking officials defend their past lending practices, but they
also say they have tightened the current availability of loans.
   ``The fact is there are not many new deals out there,'' said
Spang, at Shawmut Bank. ``Developers are not moving forward on
speculative products, and banks wouldn't approve them anyway.''
   Analysts say banks could feel bad effects from the real estate
market for another couple of years, until the excess commercial
space is absorbed.
   But that does not mean new construction is dead. Developers can
still get financing for projects that have minimal risks, said
Wayne Clough, vice president of Boston Financial Group.
   ``The old days of speculative building are gone,'' he said.
``But there's still a good appetite for well-sponsored deals.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
