<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-27 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower; Pound Still in Slump; Gold Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar weakened substantially against all
major currencies except the British pound Friday, undermined by
another poor session in the U.S. stock market and expectations of
lower interest rates.
   Sterling stayed stuck in the slump it lapsed into when the
British government's top finance official abruptly quit on Thursday.
   Gold prices gained sharply. On the Commodity Exchange in New
York, gold bullion for current delivery settled at $378.30 a troy
ounce, up $5.80 from Thursday. The Republic National Bank of New
York quoted an ounce of gold at $377.25 as of 4 p.m. EDT, $6.15
higher than Thursday's late bid.
   The dollar ended near its lowest levels of the day. Currency
dealers said selling motivated by internal market factors
accentuated the weakness.
   But much of the impetus to unload dollars came from the stock
market where the Dow Jones industrial average closed with a loss
for the week of 92.42 points, at 2,596.72.
   Rumors circulating in the bond market that a major Japanese
investor was dumping long-term U.S. Treasury bonds also depressed
the dollar. If U.S. stocks and bonds fall out of favor, there would
be less demand for dollars.
   News that the U.S. budget deficit totaled $152.1 billion in
fiscal 1989, which ended Sept. 30, highlighted another weak spot in
the U.S. economy. The deficit has shown little improvement for
three straight years.
   ``The market's perception of a fragile stock market, a possibly
faltering economy and announcement of the size of the budget
deficit'' pushed the dollar down,'' said Bob Morrissey, senior
trader at the Bank of Boston in New York.
   A bearish attitude toward the dollar has been reinforced lately
by numerous economic numbers showing sluggish growth. There is
speculation that the Federal Reserve Board soon will decide to
stimulate growth by nudging interest rates lower. Declining U.S.
rates would reduce returns on dollar-denominated investments,
tending to curb dollar demand.
   The British pound, jarred by the resignation of Chancellor of
the Exchequer Nigel Lawson on Thursday, finished the London trading
day at $1.5750, substantially lower than $1.6130 the day before.
   But sterling managed to rebound slightly from its worst levels
with a little help from the Bank of England and the Fed. Both
central banks reportedly bought pounds and sold dollars to stall
the pound's slide. The London closing price was up from a session
low of $1.5620.
   The pound also dropped to 2.8820 Deutsche marks, compared with
2.9650 marks late Thursday.
   Later, in New York, sterling fetched $1.5795, up slightly from
$1.5780 on Thursday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.85 yen to a closing 142.75 yen. But
in London, it fell back to a late rate of 141.90 yen. The dollar
ended New York trading at 141.75 yen, down from 142.125 late
Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Thursday's
quotes, included: 1.8295 West German marks, down from 1.8410;
1.6005 Swiss francs, down from 1.6115; 6.2150 French francs, down
from 6.2545; 1.17475 Canadian dollars, down from 1.17545; and
1,348.00 Italian lire, down from 1,351.00.
   Late rates for the dollar in London compared with Thursday's
late rates included: 1.8300 West German marks, down from 1.8390;
1.6005 Swiss francs, down from 1.6085; 6.2190 French francs, down
from 6.2455; 2.0820 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0810; 1,342.00
Italian lire, down from 1,347.75; and 1.1746 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1750.
   Precious metals gained around the world.
   Gold traded in London at a bid price of $374.25 a troy ounce,
the highest since July 26, compared with late Thursday's $369.00.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $373.00 compared with $368.25 late
Thursday.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose $3.13 to close at a bid $371.87.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.19 a troy
ounce, up from Thursday's $5.13. On New York's Comex silver bullion
for current delivery rose to $5.279, up from Thursday's settlement
of $5.194.
</TEXT>
