<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-27 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Hits 3{-Month High On Stock Jitters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold futures prices surged to their highest levels in 3{ months
Friday on New York's Commodity Exchange as investors unnerved by
the stock market's gyrations opted for the perceived safety of
precious metals.
   ``The market is getting back into the viewpoint that gold is a
store of value, that it retains purchasing power,'' said Bette
Raptopoulos, a metals analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Silver and platinum futures also rose sharply.
   On other futures markets Friday, copper advanced, oil prices
rose, livestock and meat were mostly lower, and grains and soybeans
were mixed.
   Gold futures settled $5.80 to $7 higher with the contract for
spot delivery at $378.30 a troy ounce, the highest spot price on
the Commodity Exchange since July 12. The most active gold
contract, for December delivery, settled at $381.20 an ounce,
braking the $380 barrier for the first time since Aug. 3.
   Silver finished 8.3 cents to 9.2 cents higher with December at
$5.32 an ounce; platinum futures climbed $9.30 to $9.70 on the New
York Mercantile Exchange, where the January contract settled at
$499.30 a troy ounce.
   The precious metals markets have been in a slump for most of
this year. Gold has not approached $400 since late January.
   But the stock market's recent volatility _ beginning with a
190-point plunge in the Dow Jones industrial average on Oct. 13 _
has stoked recession fears in investors whose appetite for gold had
already been whetted by the weakening dollar.
   ``The gold market is no longer solely dependent on dollar
movement,'' said William O'Neil, research director with Elders
Futures Inc. ``The key fundamental behind this rally is the general
uncertainty surrounding equities.''
   The Dow average fell a total of 92.42 points this week,
including a 17-point drop on Friday that analysts attributed to
concern about lower corporate earnings.
   Stock-index futures also lost ground Friday on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of
stocks represented by the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index fell 2.35
points to 337.20. The contract is worth $500 a point.
   Ms. Raptopoulos said a sharp drop in the London stock market
triggered by the resignation of British Chancellor of the Exchequer
Nigel Lawson added to the economic worries.
   Copper futures posted moderate gains on the Comex, erasing
Thursday's losses in a technically inspired rebound after falling
sharply for two weeks.
   Copper settled .25 cent to 1.7 points higher with December at
$1.158 a pound.
   Most oil futures rose on the New York Mercantile Exchange as
traders evened up their positions after a week of losses.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 8 cents lower to 39
cents higher with December at $19.77 a barrel; heating oil was .40
cent to .59 cent higher with November at 57.68 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .60 cent to 1.07 cent higher with November at
54.62 cents a gallon.
   Livestock and meat futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange amid expectations for weaker spot markets, especially for
hogs, next week.
   Cattle futures settled .45 cent to .68 cent lower with December
at 74.12 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .50 cent
lower with November at 82.40 cents a pound; live hogs were .80 cent
lower to .20 cent higher with December at 46.17 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .40 cent to .60 cent lower with February
at 51.85 cents a pound.
   Soybean futures ended moderately lower on the Chicago Board of
Trade amid expectations for an active harvesting weekend in the
Southeast and the Mississippi Delta region. Corn futures also fell
while wheat futures finished mixed.
   Wheat settled } cent lower to 2\ cents higher with December at
$3.98{ a bushel; corn was 3 cents lower to \ cent higher with
December at $2.41} a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to 2} cents lower
with December at $1.43\ a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cent to 4} cents
lower with November at $5.61} a bushel.
</TEXT>
