<SECOND>AM-Telerate-Dow Jones,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Jones Extends Offer for Telerate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Jones &amp; Co. Inc. said Friday it had extended
until Nov. 6 its $576 million offer for the 33 percent stake in the
electronic financial information company Telerate Inc. that it does
not already own.
   Dow Jones, which publishes The Wall Street Journal and provides
an array of electronic business services of its own, had previously
said its $18-a-share offer for the Telerate stock would expire at
midnight Friday, Nov. 3.
   But Dow Jones said it was extending the offer until 5 p.m.
Eastern time Monday, Nov. 6, because it is mailing a supplement to
its offer to Telerate shareholders and wants to give them ``ample
time'' to review it.
   The statement said the supplement ``does not otherwise amend the
terms and conditions of the offer.''
   A committee of independent directors of Telerate rejected the
offer as inadequate earlier this month, and urged Dow Jones to meet
with them to achieve ``a mutually agreed upon transaction that
would be fair to all Telerate shareholders.''
   Dow Jones said its representatives met with members of the
special committee of Telerate on Thursday to discuss the offer, but
said those discussions did not result in any changes to the terms
of the offer.
   A Dow Jones spokesman declined to say how many shares had been
tendered so far under the $18-a-share offer.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange Friday, Telerate fell
50 cents a share to $20.
</TEXT>
