<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0878</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three major Wall Street firms capitulated to an
investor outcry, abandoning or curtailing a computerized trading
strategy widely blamed for turmoil in the stock market.
   In addition, an insurance company that manages more than $8.6
billion in assets stopped doing business Friday with brokerages
that conduct program trading and the New York Stock Exchange said
it would contact members about possible reforms.
   Morgan Stanley Group Inc. and Bear, Stearns &amp; Co., two of the
biggest users of program trading, said they would stop using a form
of the strategy known as index arbitrage to trade for their own
accounts. PaineWebber Group Inc. ended use of all forms of the
strategy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' personal income, dealt a blow by
Hurricane Hugo, rose a lackluster 0.3 percent in September as
consumer spending posted its weakest advance in a year, the
government said.
   The Commerce Department said Friday that personal income in
September rose $12.8 billion at a seasonally adjusted annual rate
to $4.47 trillion, the smallest increase in four months.
   Spending increased 0.2 percent, the most anemic gain in 12
months, to an annual rate of $3.53 trillion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal budget deficit totaled $152.1
billion in fiscal 1989, marking the third year of essentially
unchanged fiscal red ink, the government said.
   For the first time, interest on the $2.8 trillion national debt
exceeded Social Security spending, pushing the interest category
into second place, behind military expenditures.
   The budget gap for the year ending Sept. 30 marked a $3.1
billion, or 2 percent, improvement over the $155.2 billion deficit
in 1988, the Treasury Department and the Office of Management and
Budget said Friday.
</TEXT>
