<FIRST>u f AM-EarthquakeDamage     10-27 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earthquake Damage,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Insured Property Damage From Bay Area Quake Put At $960 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insured property damage from the Oct. 17 San
Francisco Bay Area earthquake has been estimated at $960 million, a
New York-based insurance concern said Friday.
   The preliminary estimate by American Insurance Services Group
Inc. includes damage to homes and businesses covered by earthquake
insurance.
   It also includes damage for automobiles covered under
comprehensive policies, losses for business interruption and damage
from fire.
   The estimate does not include claims under workers'
compensation, life, health disability and liability insurance or
damage to bridges and highways, the company said.
   The estimate of total damage stands at $7.1 billion, according
to reports from state, city, county and federal officials. That
would make the Oct. 17 earthquake the most expensive natural
disaster in U.S. history, based on Independent Insurance Agents of
America records.
   American Insurance Services estimates that only about 30 percent
of homes and businesses in the earthquake area had quake coverage.
   AISG, a subsidiary of the American Insurance Association which
has 195 members, includes property and casualty insurance companies.
</TEXT>
