<FIRST>r f AM-CerealRecall     10-27 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cereal Recall,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gerber Recalls Rice Cereal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerber Products Co. recalled 9,800 cases
of its rice cereal on Friday, saying three consumers reported
finding tiny metal pieces in the 8-ounce packages.
   ``While no injuries were reported and the particle sizes do not
constitute a health hazard, we decided a voluntary withdrawal was
in keeping with Gerber high quality standards,'' Ron Lovasz, vice
president of Gerber's quality control division, said in a news
statement.
   The contamination was isolated in a 9,800-case batch produced
Aug. 24 at the company's Fort Smith, Ark., plant, he said. The
affected packages were recommended for use by Aug. 24, 1991, and
marked with codes S1 through S8.
   The Food and Drug Administration was told of the recall, and
product removal from grocery shelves was under way, Lovasz said.
   Consumers who have the packages should return them to the stores
where they were purchased for a full refund, the company said.
</TEXT>
