<FIRST>r f BC-TBSRefinancing     10-27 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-TBS Refinancing,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turner Broadcasting Completes Refinancing, Expects Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $1.6 billion refinancing by Turner Broadcasting
System Inc. puts the entertainment company in a position to react
quickly to changes in the coming decade, Chairman Ted Turner said
Thursday.
   TBS said Thursday it had completed the refinancing, which
included repayment or redemption of substantially all of its
outstanding long-term debt. The refinancing will result in a
fourth-quarter loss of about $122 million, it said.
   The move ``puts our long-term financing on a much more
reasonable basis than before and provides us the flexibility we
need to deal with the fast-changing television marketplace in the
1990s,'' Turner said.
   The Atlanta-based company said the refinancing was funded by
about $900 million borrowed through a bank credit facility, the
sale of $550 million in debentures due in 2001 and the sale of $200
million in notes due in 2004.
   In addition, the company called for redemption on Dec. 15 of
$200 million in notes due 1994.
   TBS owns TBS SuperStation, Turner Network Television, Cable News
Network, Headline News, the Atlanta Braves and most of the Atlanta
Hawks. TBS also owns a film library that includes MGM's pre-1986
films, Warner Brothers' pre-1950 films and a number of RKO films.
