<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0019EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-RailroadSale     10-27 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Railroad Sale,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Bank Agrees to Purchase Part of Troubled Railroad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago, Missouri &amp; Western Railway Co. announced
Thursday that a New York investment bank has agreed to purchase the
railway's lines from Springfield and East St. Louis, Ill., to
Kansas City, Mo.
   The letter of intent calls for the sale to Wertheim Schroder &amp;
Co. for $24 million cash, Trustee Daniel R. Murray said, calling
the agreement ``an exciting milestone for CMW and its employees.''
   Rio Grande Industries Inc., the parent of the Southern Pacific
Transportation Co., agreed in August to purchase the remaining part
of the 630-mile railroad, from Joliet, Ill. to East St. Louis, for
$22 million.
   Murray said a competing bid from investor Karl Ziebarth would be
made Friday for $26 million, but that he supported the Wertheim bid.
   ``The consummation of these sales will ensure the future
viability of all of CM&amp;W's service for Amtrak, for our shippers as
well as for the citizens of both Illinois and Missouri,'' Murray
said.
   Creditors, primarily Citicorp North America Inc. and Heller
Financial Inc., are owed more than $100 million. They have opposed
any sale of the railroad and have fought in court for its immediate
liquidation.
   The Wertheim bid will be submitted to U.S. Bankruptcy Court
Chief Judge John D. Schwartz on Tuesday, and the creditors will be
asked then whether they oppose the sale, Murray said.
</TEXT>
