<FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 0048EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-McDonnellDouglas     10-27 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-McDonnell Douglas,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>McDonnell-Douglas Profit Drops 54 Percent In Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Corp., the nation's largest
defense contractor, reported Thursday a 54 percent decrease in its
third-quarter profit, reflecting continued problems in both its
commercial and govenment segments.
   The company earned $38 million, or 98 cents a share, compared
with $83 million, or $2.18 a share, in the same quarter a year ago.
Revenue was $3.7 billion, up from $3.68 billion in the year-ago
period.
   The current quarter's figures include $6 million, or 14 cents a
share, in earnings from discontinued operations in the information
systems area.
   For the first nine months of the year, the company had a profit
of $159 million, thanks to a $179 million one-time gain as a result
of an accounting change. Without that gain, the company would have
had a $26 million loss for the period.
   Sales for the first nine months totaled $10.32 billion, almost
the same as the figure for last year's first nine months, $10.33
billion.
   The principal factors cited for the lower earnings in the
quarter were a jump in interest expense to $95 million from $57
million a year earlier, an operating loss in the commercial
aircraft segment and decreased earnings from the combat aircraft,
missiles, space and electronic systems segments.
   The commercial aircraft segment lost $3 million on revenues of
$1.3 billion in the quarter, compared with earnings of $15 million
on revenues of $1.3 billion last year.
   The company attributed the loss to parts shortages and problems
arising from the need to assimilate and train a large number of new
workers. A major reorganization was also a factor, McDonnell
Douglas said.
   ``They've gone through a major restructuring in Douglas Aircraft
and they're doing the same now in helicopters,'' said Phil
Friedman, an analyst with Drexal Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Analyst Paul Nisbet of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. said the
third quarter figures troubled him.
   ``They're a lot better than the first two quarters,'' Nisbet
said, ``but still not near the level that one would consider
normal. I suspect that a lot of it is continued problems with
research and development.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
